text: I am so glad my friend told me about this hidden gem!!!! We took a cab here from Chinatown because we were not sure where it was, but it&#39;s actually a short walk from a subway station, so take the subway to save on transportation expenses. <br> <br>We had the Hagrid&#39;s Afternoon Tea and I am so glad we ordered it!  Everything on the menu was delicious. I have to admit that I wasn&#39;t sure if the items would look exactly like it was on the menu because there are those places where the pictures in the menu are better then what you get and then there are those places where the pictures in the menu don&#39;t do them justice. Well, these pictures represented exactly what we received! <br><br>This is a perfect place for any &#34;true&#34; fan. Yes I say true because I have read reviews on here where they say that their friend didn&#39;t realize it was a HP café. How are you a true fan and not notice this? Seriously!!!! From the menu, to the decorations, to the photo area, it all screams Harry Potter!!!!!  <br><br>If you want to order the Hagrid&#39;s Afternoon Tea, keep in mind that it starts at 2pm and it&#39;s in limited quantities. Also, come with an appetite as it is a lot of food for 2 people. At least I think it&#39;s a lot of food. My husband had the seafood menu items, and he said they tasted really good. I had the non-seafood menu items and it was so delicious! All the desserts were amazing! Though I did order some coffee to counteract the sweetness of the desserts. <br><br>Overall, a must for any HP fan that is visiting Singapore!

text: I was a little skeptical at first because it kind of sounded gimmicky, but we had such a good experience here. The food was absolutely delicious. My friends got breakfast food that they really enjoyed (side note: I&#39;m pretty sure they put truffle oil in their eggs, so just keep that in mind in case you don&#39;t like truffle), while I got pasta with chicken and pesto. I was a little dismayed that they put lemon in it, as I personally do not like lemon at all, but it was still very good. The sauce was so creamy, and the plating was beautiful, as it was for the other meals. We also had a piece of chocolate cake that was amazing - it was rich, decadent, and moist. I split the cake with a friend, which was definitely a good idea because the food is quite filling here. One of my friends ordered Mr Lich&#39;s Flaming Brew, which was an alcoholic drink that they light on fire by sprinkling what I think was cinnamon onto it. It was definitely a cool sight, though I&#39;m not sure how it tasted. I&#39;m not really one to go all out with themes like this, but my friends convinced me to wear the robes they had for each of the houses in Harry Potter, and it ended up being a fun touch. Overall had a great time and would definitely recommend for a weekend brunch spot.

text: Harry Potter is my childhooood and coming to this place in all it&#39;s entirety I had a lot of expectations! I saw this place in one of the Facebook videos being shared. I had an opportunity to go to Singapore and went directly here to see what the hype was all about! <br><br>Singapore is a great place by the way and I love the country and its great food! <br><br>Now going back here, the decor was amazing and they have costumes and wands and broomsticks you can wear to take the coolest pictures and videos with their food! I remember while waiting for our food and drinks, my friends and I had battles with the wands haha. <br><br>I ordered the famous drink that lights up when sprinkled with cinnamon. It was the coolest thing I&#39;ve ever done. It was particularly of course my favorite part in the restaurant. The drink itself was good and let me tell you that it&#39;s an alcoholic drink. <br><br>We ordered a lot of desserts since we ate from one of the hawk centers there. <br>The food we got was why this place is only a three stars for me. <br><br>I took out two because it was just not very good. I had so much expectations. I wanted it to be as magical in my mouth with the expensive price point. For one dish it was like $15-16 and so I was hoping it would be worth it. But it&#39;s not. <br><br>This restaurant just needs better food and more people will flock here especially since it&#39;s Harry Potter, the business owners need to use that to their advantage and give their customers a more deserving magical and whimsical experience.

text: Located along 1094 Serangoon Road, lies a newly opened Harry Potter themed cafe. The moment you stepped in, you will be welcomed with brown decorated interior (brown chairs, brown wooden tables, brown wall tiles and etc...) that adds up to the theme. <br><br>We asked for the signature drink and was told that it was on the menu, &#34;Mr Lich&#39;s Brewing Brew&#34; ($15). When served, it is a cup of neon blue colored drink that looks like magic portion, which is actually made up of lime juice and Curacao liqueur. A spoon full of Barcardi 151 Rum, was then torched by the server before pouring it into the mixture. You will be given cinnamon powder to sprinkle for the sparkling effects. Abracadabraaaa boom!<br><br>We ordered the 2 cakes that taste as good as they looks! The Lychee Cake has a very nice fruity lychee flavor, very fluffy and not too sweet. The Chocolate Peanut Butter Cake is interesting good, with a complex flavorful the first spoonful.<br><br>Tips: <br>~ Feel free to pick a few props from the side table when posing with your food and Goblet of Fire drink.  <br>~ They accept reservations, call them in advance as they get pretty booked for dinner and on weekends.<br><br>[009/100]

text: This place is so adorable. We arrived pretty late at night and I was surprised to see diners dressed up in what appeared to be Harry Potter cosplay - but no, the cafe has outfits that you can wear to get in the spirit of things! The decor is so cute and very appropriately Hogwarts-like. Had I come in the daytime, I think the natural lighting would have made for some amazing pictures. <br><br>We got the butterscotch ale, and though I&#39;ve never been to the Wizarding World of Harry Potter, my friend who has said it tasted JUST like the butterbeer you can find there. It was delicious. <br><br>The food was surprisingly good for a theme cafe. We got the confit chicken with pesto spaghetti and the pesto mayo pork ribs. Both were really well cooked, not too much pesto on either but enough to give you a could flavor. The pork ribs were super tender and the sides that came with it were delicious, very American-style like mashed potatoes and sweet corn. I loved it and that&#39;s coming from an American mashed potato addict. <br><br>The witch&#39;s brew, although I didn&#39;t try it, seems like it&#39;s something you can&#39;t miss here. I was excited to see another diner get it, and the flaming drink looks exactly like a potion from Harry Potter. If I have one regret it&#39;s not trying that!

text: Very cute and quaint cafe with Harry Potter themed food and decor. I recommend this place is you have any leisure time to spare. We enjoyed this very cool and fun blue cocktail that went up in flames. It was also fun to dress up in robes &amp; take some fun photos. It&#39;s bit off the beaten path so make sure to come if you have time to spare.

text: If not for the theme, my expectations would have been much lower. Food-wise the menu is the usual brunch and cafe fare with a twist. You can also play dress up with the ropes for Gryffindor, Slytherin, Ravenclaw and Hufflepuff. Interesting drinks as potions. It would have been better if the staff were more upbeat or dressed to fit the theme instead of just black tee shirts. Wouldn&#39;t mind coming back to try the dinner menu.

text: Such a cute theme! And yet, disappointing in execution.<br><br>I came to Platform 1094 for the ever-famous cauldron drink and was thrilled to find a costume rack complete with robes, hats, wands and stuffed animals to complete the experience. This feature was the extent of the magical experience. While I loved the small touches, like the wooden stag chairs, the cauldron drink we received was less than impressive, beyond the sparks that fly when you dash it with cinnamon.<br><br>It was great to visit once, but definitely won&#39;t be making a repeat appearance in my itinerary.

text: Being an incredibly huge Harry Potter fan, having a themed Harry Potter cafe really excited me. Unfortunately, I must admit that it was pretty underwhelming. <br><br>For a themed cafe, I expected more; to see the theme being reflected in the food, the drinks, the decor, etc. Ambience wise, the only thing close to Harry Potter were the brick plastered walls... they had props, but there wasn&#39;t enough to go around (&amp; also, they only had gryffindor robes :/). <br><br>To give them credit, they did try to create &#34;potions&#34; which lit up, but again, that was only one drink (their signature)  <br><br>Taste wise, everything was pretty standard; drinks needed more alcohol,

text: We are from out of town and had to come here since I&#39;m a huge Harry Potter fan! I am only rating on the drinks as we did not try the food. <br><br>Based on theme, it is really cutely Harry Potter. You cannot miss it- the corner had a whole wardrobe and some of the wall decor looks like ads out of Harry Potter. <br><br>The drinks were mediocre at best and pricy. While the signature drink was clever and fun, it was weak. My husband had it because I don&#39;t like the taste of alcohol. However, when I drank it, it tasted like fruit juice that I think I could have handled it. I ordered a fruit smoothie (S$8), and I feel like I could have gotten 3 of these at the nearby food courts. Nothing memorable. <br><br>Overall, I feel the experience and quality together rounds this place to a 3 stars

text: A cute little Harry Potter themed restaurant close to Boon Keng MRT. Lots of interesting sounding dessert and drinks!<br>Check out my visit: <a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.jamienan.com%2F2017%2F01%2F20%2Fplatform-1094-singapores-first-harry-potter-themed-cafe%2F&amp;s=a94ac8439e01c12728fd0154f10abcc279e6f0c5642687a00768ee70b4dcfa3c" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">jamienan.com/2017/01/20/…</a>

text: I am a Harry Potter super fan, and this place is so whimsical! Harry Potter&#39;s movie soundtrack is playing in the background, the walls are adorned with decor from the wizarding world, and the cleanliness is excellent. The menu is pretty good at providing an assortment of options; quinoa salad, crab pasta, duck, truffle fries, gorgeous desserts, and fun drinks (alcoholic and non-alcoholic). I can definitely feel the Harry Potter vibe in the menu selection, and I glad they didn&#39;t make it exactly like in the movies, I want food that I am actually able to eat lol. I love this place, and if I wasn&#39;t just here on vacation, I would be coming back here regularly!

I&#39;ve been here twice and I enjoyed it. <br><br>Gashouse Egg is their specialty and I strongly recommend you to try it if it&#39;s your first visit. It&#39;s like egg in the hole, bread toasted till crispy but the yolk is not overcooked. I&#39;m in love with their bacon jam on the side.<br><br>Coffee is definitely the selling point here.<br><br>I tried their choc croissant during my second visit. It was good. And because I couldn&#39;t forget my love for their bacon jam, I requested for the jam on the side (add $2). I know it sounds weird but the savoury jam actually went well with the sweet croissant.<br><br>Be warned that this place is always very crowded on weekends!

text: Recently the cafe had updated its menu with new items such as XL crispy chicken burger and Furikake Mushroom pasta. Order was taken at counter with only cash and NETS payment accepted.<br><br>Sriracha Pork Belly Burger ($15)<br>served with sweet potato fries<br>The pork belly was fatty with a texture similar to soft bone, although I was expecting a melt in a mouth fatty part with a crispy crust. The burger was not as spicy as expected. It was not messy to eat the burger. The fries was lacking of crispiness.<br><br>Coffee Soda ($6)<br> It was a glass of soda, accompanied with a glass of espresso. Just add the espresso into the soda before drinking. It tasted like soda drink with a coffee aftertaste. Quite refreshing for a hot day.

text: Most people come here for the Gashouse Eggs but the Croissants are excellent as well. I tried the basic croissant which comes toasted warm with a side of their homemade jam and butter. <br><br>The croissant was large and flakey, but not too buttery. It was so good that I devoured it before taking a picture. I&#39;ll definitely have to come back to try the coffee next time!<br><br>They also have some outdoor seating which includes a few hanging coves, which I found perfect for reading. Sitting outside is a nice alternative if you want a bit of peace and quiet. Most of their tables are in the shade, so it&#39;s not too hot on a typical day. <br>L

text: One Man Coffee is tucked away in Crust&#39;s shop, using the venue during the day before it gets transformed into a pizza bar at night. Nice ambience, not too noisy for a lazy Sunday morning, and very affordable prices (average $10 as opposed to the $15 average in other cafes).<br><br>Tried the Gashouse Eggs ($10) and Brioche French Toast with Berry Compote, Candied Walnuts &amp; Fresh Cream ($10). <br><br>The Gashouse Eggs seemed like a Croque Monsieur, satisfactory, though slightly on the greasy side. Egg could be runnier as well, though the bacon jam on the side was interesting.<br><br>The French Toast was perfect, not too sweet, crisp on the outside and fluffy on the inside. Thoroughly enjoyed it.

Well I can say that for a company that has Coffee in its name sure live up to its name.  Came here just for coffee and was intrigued by the number of people here.  Though aircon was a little warm but still the vibe was still good.  Cappuccino - not bad!  Latte art - nice.  Long black - excellent.  Like they rebaked the banana cake :).  Earned a revisit for sure!

text: Ordered the gas house eggs and they tasted awesome. Was more expertly prepared than I expected, which is why I&#39;m rating it 4 stars. <br><br>Place was small and cosy too (with free wifi)<br><br>But for a cafe, the coffee definitely needs some work for improvement. (I ordered magic)

I am not in the habit of awarding five stars for a single dish as I normally feel that it requires more than that but trying the French toast with caramelized bananas and salty caramel is just great. I will return just for that. It is perfectly fluffy, not overly sweet and feels fresh. The big brekkie is also very good but it does pale in comparison to the French toast but as I seldom come here alone I will force anyone going with me to share a Big Brekkie and the French toast with me (just a fair warning if I ever suggest going here with you).<br><br>The coffee is nicely made, perfect execution on all the espresso based beverages. Unfortunately no filters but can head down the road to Pacamara for that. The service has also been very friendly and they managed the packed place rather well. <br><br>Worth mentioning is that it shares the space with a pizza place so in the evenings it transforms into a pizza place. Never tried the pizzas there but it does make the setting feel a bit strange but nice with some variety from all the other similarly looking places.

I&#39;ve been rather hardworking for the past couple of weeks in checking out the cafes. Well I must say that Instagram has been most helpful in keeping me updated with the prettiest cafés on the block and that kinda led me to One Man Coffee, a hole in the wall that shares their shop front with Crust gourmet Pizza Bar along Upper Thomson Road. <br><br>Sip on the Melbournian Axil Coffee Roaster beans pulled by Sarah Jane (formerly from Immigrants) or E-gene (who pulled his way around MEL). Coffee is little acidic with medium finish. My latte wasn&#39;t quite full bodied or milky though. While it&#39;s not quite my style, it was sufficient in packing a punch to last me through my afternoon meeting. Coffee is priced between $3 to $6.50. <br><br>OMC also stocks B.A.O&#39;s pastries. I simply love Christophe&#39;s croissants, well the French makes the best croissants! The Chocolate pain is also amazing. Get them to heat it up for that crispy flakiness. Better still, have them with honey ham and melted cheese ($6). Cakes are also available and I was seduced by a Salted Caramel Banana Cake.<br><br>For something a little more than sweets, OMC does all-day-breakfast with a lean but mean menu, all of which come out of a pizza oven! Talk about easy to make but delicious food here! <br><br>Love the description of the Gashouse Egg aka Toad in hole aka Egg-in-the-bread-with-the-hole-in-the-middle ($10). It&#39;s more of a snack I feel. I really do have a monster appetite for breakfast food. The dish is really simple, they really do just make a hole in the fluffy brioche, crack an egg in, top with cheese and into the oven it goes. Almost a croque madame.<br><br>Really there&#39;s no need to be fancy for brekkie when the ingredients are good (hello ooooozy yolk). What&#39;s special is that bacon jam which is smoky, meaty and sweet. I could do with a thick layer of that in the toast anytime. Satisfying flavors, a little dry on the edges, not so satisfying portion but that helps save space for other food. <br><br>The Broiche French Toast ($10) is another popular item and it looked freaking amazing with the homemade berry compote, candied walnuts and fresh cream. Of course the dust of sugary white completes the instagram worthy picture. <br><br>OMC is a great alternative to the super packed Habitat Coffee which I failed to visit TWICE! Well I guess I&#39;ll just have to explore the rest of the Thomson cafés until Habitat becomes less crowded. Anyhoo, great vibe at One Man Coffee but do go early or be prepared to wait as well due to the extremely small space.

I came here a couple months back with a friend and boy do they really need to improve on service. Seating done by a list is not extremely effective if you have a maitre&#39;d who is easily pushed around. Granted it was a Saturday afternoon and from what I&#39;ve heard (they&#39;re always packed), I felt that it should have been made clear that there was a waiting list for seating. Numerous parties after me all sat down at the same seats and were told of their policy and had to get up soon after. Would slapping a reserve sign on the table be so hard? <br><br>On to coffee, we had a cappuccino and long black, the milk wasn&#39;t frothed well, and the long black was just the darkest point of my life to say the least. <br><br>Last but not least, everyone around was ordering the french toast, so maybe you might have better luck with that than the coffee?

I stay really nearby and have heard of it before so I decided to try today. This coffee shop&#39;s name should be Wobble coffee instead. The tables outside are all wobbling. The wooden plate of food is also wobbling. The Big Breakie is not that fantastic. I like the one slide of bread though. Havent tried the coffee yet ( ya i know. It&#39;s such a shame)  I will come back just for the coffee one day

text: This place has some interesting takes on breakfast. But their interpretations are quite delicious! Many contrasting flavors create some wonderful meals. The grilled cheese was good, the Gashouse breakfast was awesome, as is the breakfast burger. My only negative was that their coffee was pretty average and their breakfasts need bacon strips!

text: Friendly barista with a good qualify coffee. Nice ambiance and relaxing atmosphere (I&#39;m there at 330pm). The cakes look tempting but I&#39;ll keep them for another visit

Sorry... I&#39;ve had to dock a star. I enjoyed this place for coffee and went back to try a brunch on a Saturday. It was crowded, and the staff weren&#39;t very on the ball when it came to seating waiting customers. Tables were cleared but waiting customers were still left waiting... Tried the Big Brekkie and it was OK. The eggs were purportedly 60 degree eggs but I&#39;m pretty sure mine were over cooked and too firm.

Good news for all! This year, York Hotel Singapore is back to celebrate the 30th Anniversary for their renowned Penang Hawkers&#39; Fare Buffet, held at their White Rose Cafe, Level 1.<br><br>They brought in 12 stalls this year and 3 sessions throughout 2016:<br>- March 11 to March 27, 2016<br>- Sept 2 to Sept 18, 2016<br>- Dec 16 to Jan 1st, 2017<br><br>Response was really good and NO RESERVATIONS entertained, walk-in-only. Lunch 12noon to 2.30pm / Dinner 6.30pm to 10pm.<br><br>Weekday Priced at $29++ Adult / $20++ Child below 12 / Weekends Priced at $33++ Adult / $20++ Child below 12 <br><br>If any of you interested to learn how to make their prawn noodles, assam laksa and ban chang kueh, last chance on 19 March 2016. Limited seats, call 68301156 to register now.<br><br>Here were some highlights from their Penang hawkers&#39; fare buffet:<br><br>(1) Penang Assam Laksa<br><br>- Assam laksa, the best item I had that night. A bowl of thick bee hoon (rice noodles), soaked in pipin&#39; hot broth made from fish and tamarind. Sourish, full of flavours, so SHIOK! Topped with pineapple slices, chilli buddy, shredded cucumber, torch ginger and complete with a small spoonful of prawn paste. I can have this everyday! Rating 5/5<br><br>(2) Prawn Noodles<br><br>- This bowl of &#34;hae mee&#34; (prawn noodles) wasn&#39;t as impressive as the laksa but was definitely comfort food. As told by the hawker chef, broth was made from piles of prawn heads, pork ribs and shells to obtain this robust consistency but I wished the taste was much stronger. Prawns given were really tiny, pork slices too dry but the rewarding part? Lotsa crispy pork lard! Rating 3/5<br><br>(3) Lor Bak<br><br>- A snack resembling our local fried prawn fritters (五香虾饼), this Penang version came with only 4 items; deep fried prawn, sweet potato, tau gua (fried beancurd) and handmade five-spiced meat roll. I love the meat rolls most while the other three were rather common. They were well marinated with good amount of chinese spices, not overpowering, while the meat was firm and juicy. Rating 3/5<br><br>(4) Penang Rojak<br><br>- This interesting plate of &#34;chinese salad&#34; caught my attention because of the ingredients used. Instead of the usual tau pok (fried beancurd skin) and dough fritters we had in our rojak, Penang version had jambu and green mango in it. Love the crunchiness of the fruits mixed in with the thick flavourful rojak sauce (prawn paste) and fragrant grounded peanuts. Not everybody could accept the pungent smell of prawn paste but I can and I quite like it. Rating 4/5<br><br>(5) Char Kway Teow<br><br>- Longest queues were found infront of this char kway teow stall. Everyone patiently waited, just to get their hands on this Penang&#39;s renowned char kway teow. A small plate of fried flat rice noodles in soya sauce, loaded with bean sprouts, spring onions, cockles, egg and prawn. Fragrant, savoury, semi sweet and least oily! It&#39;s a waste that my plate of CKT doesn&#39;t carry that smokey &#34;wok hei&#34; taste otherwise it would be perfect! Rating 4/5<br><br>(6) Kway Teow<br><br>- An ordinary looking bowl of dry kway teow with fishballs and shredded chicken. But the base sauce for tossing the kway teow was so yum! A mixture of Penang sweet sauce, dark soya sauce plus sesame oil, these sauces&#39; combination seems so simple yet delicious and satisfying. Rating 3/5<br><br>(7) Pasembur<br><br>- This year&#39;s new item. A mixture of shredded cucumber pile, potato chunks, fried beancurd, Egg slice and thin crispy dough biscuits. Special? Yes, the sauce! The orange-coloured sauce on top was made from sweet potato! Sweet and slight grainy, interesting fusion taste when consume with the ingredients. Rating 3/5<br><br>(8) Ban Chang Kueh<br><br>- Crispy, sweet, buttery, loaded with lotsa grounded peanuts, so yummy so IRRESISTABLE! Nuff said :) Rating 5/5<br><br>(9) Chendol<br><br>- Personally, I felt this chendol wasn&#39;t as authentic as those I tried before, especially these greeny pandan jellies (If you know what I meant). Kidney beans were nicely done and not mushy, the thick caramelized  gula melaka was a highlight too but I prefer the portion to be more. Rating 4/5<br><br>Other stalls&#39; delicacies include Nasi Lemak with Nonya Chicken Kapitan which had very fragrant coconut rice and nicely done ikan billis chilli, Oyster omelette which lack crispiness, Cuttlefish Kangkong and dessert Ice Kacang.<br><br>** The whole dining experience was really good, especially when dine with good friends. On site situation was crowded, even on a weekday Tuesday night, but all customers were really discipline and queued politely. Despite the long queues and busy nights, the hawkers cooking at individual stations were all smiles throughout. They were also kind enough to tell us more about the food recipes when asked upon. Thumbs up! Although each dish came in small portions but you could queue again, repeatedly, for your favourite choices, it&#39;s buffet anyway!!<br>For the price of $29++ on weekdays and $33++ on weekends, this deal was definitely worth! Hurry down before this fare ends on 27 March 2016. **

text: PENANG HAWKER FARE <br>So the York Hotel coffee house does this thing called Penang Hawkers Fare where it invites 22 famous hawkers food chef from Penang, Malaysia to cook up their famous dishes. Overall there are a dozen different dishes like Penang Laksa, Penang Char keoy  teow, Penang prawn noodle, Penang loh bak, Penang rojak etc.<br>All of them are very good and worth the price instead of going to Penang. <br>The dishes are served in small servings so you can try all of the dishes. Several if not all deserves a second or third round.<br>Just make sure you leave room for the Chendol dessert.

text: I was at Ogopogo last night and at first I found the name a bit of a mouthful to pronounce but all these were set aside after the staff at the cafe greeted me with a big cheery &#34;HELLO!&#34; <br><br>The ambiance of the place was quite 1970-80 ish. People like me who were born during that era will find it a fair bit nostalgic with their quirky chairs and toys on display.. they have those 10 cents lollipops I used to buy in Primary School sold straight from the jar. <br><br>Their menu which arrived in the form of a jotterbook, which according to the staff, each and every book was painstakingly handwritten (so don&#39;t go spilling drinks or food on the jotterbook since it was someone&#39;s blood, sweat and tears!). They have coffee, lattes, beers, ciders, sodas and smoothies. They also have a range of cakes available and a little shisha place at the back where unlike other places, you don&#39;t have to smoking by the street side with the cars zooming by and people staring at you. It&#39;s a nice private enclosed open space at the back where other than the distant sounds from the other stores around Ogopogo, you can pretty much smoke in peace. <br><br>If you are hungry, feel free to ask the owners for their food menu. They have an arabian food menu and an italian menu where once you order, the staff will run to the stores next door and place your order for you. <br><br>I really like the ambiance of this place as it&#39;s very laidback, the staff are very friendly and the drinks are delicious! Will definitely come back for more here!

text: The new concept cafe on the block is called Ogopogo, refering to a mythical &#34;caffiend&#34; monster that lives in the pipes that run along the walls of the whole interior. Cute little place that&#39;s an undiscovered gem.. For now.<br><br>It&#39;s kind of funky and retro at the same time. Tv sets, tin carriers and other old school paraphernalia sets the mood. The mad mix of mismatching chairs also adds to the charm of the place. <br><br>Come here for the coffee! Using beans from Toby&#39;s estate, the coffee is well balanced and easy to drink, and does not even require sugar!<br><br>Other than coffee, thy also have chai lattes, craft beers and ciders available all day. Check out the Japanese Hitachino Nest flavours - the one that caught my eye was the espresso stout! Definitely an interesting taste to it! :)<br><br>Lovely desserts and cakes here, ad I really enjoyed the cookies and the mango passion fruit cake there too. It went perfectly with my coffee!<br><br>Because its so new, they haven&#39;t really gotten a full menu set up yet. However they have partnered up with other nearby restaurants, so you can go there and enjoy a variety of cuisines such as Italian and middle eastern! But that&#39;s for another review.<br><br>Lastly, there&#39;s a cute little outdoor area one can smoke shisha in. Really loved the entire feel and ambience of the place, and the friendly, attentive staff on duty there.<br><br>Am keen to see what else Ogopogo comes up with! I&#39;ll definitely be back! I&#39;ve also just found out that if u call in advance, they will prepare your order and run out for a drive by takeaway! Perfect for those on the go, especially since parking can be a little tricky around that area!<br><br>And I love the fact that the name is a palindrome. Make sure you check out their handwritten exercise book menus - they&#39;re super cute and fun!

We had the mushrooms, fries, bouillabaisse, shepherd pie, carbonara, cream of mussels and gula melaka cake this time. <br><br>The mushrooms were delicious, consistent with my previous visit. The carbonara was decent but not a must have. The bouillabaisse and shepherd pie were a little disappointing, considering they were the chef&#39;s special. The portions were small and did not taste what I expected of a bouillabaisse and shepherd pie. The gula melaka cake is what made this review a 4 instead of 3 - it was a little sweet but would have been perfect with a coffee. <br><br>I would still recommend coming if you need a halal restaurant and am in the area.

text: This Muslim-owned bistro has moved from its original location from Bali Lane to a spacier lot at Telok Ayer. Located right across the historic Thiam Hock Keng temple, along a cram street... you should be able to spot it.<br><br>Perhaps this place is just too new as it just opened for service mid last month; hence word of mouth is still not spread around much. It was lunch time and the place was still quite vacant. Only two tables were occupied; one was the owners and probably their acquaintances. Regretted being so paranoid of taking the trouble of reserving a table. It was only about 1pm++ did we notice more and more people coming in, but there were still a lot of tables available.<br><br>We were a group of 4 colleagues, lunching out together. Most of the food ordered were shared, just so we could have a bite of everything purchased. Opinions shared amongst us obviously varied. And oh! Do note that not all the photos posted here were taken by me. Haha! We shared our snaps. *giggles*<br><br>We got ourselves &#39;Nacho Lover&#39;, &#39;Fried Mushroom&#39;, &#39;Crispy Wings&#39; and &#39;Signature Prawn &amp; Crayfish Pasta&#39;. For drinks and desserts, we ordered &#39;Mango Creme Brulee&#39;, &#39;Affogato&#39;, &#39;Iced Lemon Tea&#39; and... &#39;Halal Champagne&#39;. Yes, you read right. &#39;Halal Champagne&#39;: non-alcoholic. They even have &#39;Halal Red Wine&#39;. Two of us have never touched alcohol before, so we asked one who had and she confirmed that the taste was exactly the same as a genuine champagne. It tasted like an extreme Apple Zapple to me. *shrugs* <br><br>Nachos were served with 3 different dips: cheese sauce, salsa and guacamole. Okay! Not too overpowering. Fried truffle mushrooms were a bit too soft to our liking. Then again, I dislike mushrooms. The pasta was nice but those chicken wings... Wow! Loved them! We didn&#39;t share the Affogato though. But my colleague who got it did say it was good. <br><br>Coming to the creme brulee though, I&#39;ve tasted Chempedak and even Durian flavoured ones before, but this was the first time I had a Mango flavoured creme brulee. I absolutely loved it. My colleague however found it too sweet... Oh well! I have a sweet tooth. Hence the reason why I guess my Iced Lemon Tea was a bit too bland.<br><br>Oh! Getting here is best via public transport. We took a cab here. Parking is almost impossible in this area. Most did illegal parking. Even then, there were no more spots.

text: This very popular stalk serves up not only your traditional coffee (kopi) &amp; tea (teh), but also some modern fusion versions. Milo dinosaur (iced milo with a scoop of milo powder on top) is a popular item, together with teh cino (iced tea with milk). <br><br>Go early if you want to get a seat. A lot of people just buy &amp; takeaway, usually after their meals.

A place so local, that when I ordered with my thick American accent the uncle told me, &#34;Welcome to Singapore!&#34; after serving my drinks!<br><br>Despite it&#39;s central location in Far East Square, the price for a kopi or teh are still very affordable at under $2. Even if you go a little more fancier and order their pricier drinks, you&#39;d still pay less than $5. I bought a round for 7 folks and I paid less than $20. WIN!<br><br>They are located in the non-air conditioned part of Far East Square, so be prepared to sweat it out on a hot day. If you&#39;ve never been here before, you&#39;ll find them closer to Telok Ayer Street. Enjoy your morning or mid-day drinks!

text: Mr Teh Tarik is very popular with the lunch and tea break crowd because the service is fast and their drinks come in pretty large cups. As you line up and place your order with the auntie, the uncles behind are already mixing up your drink. I&#39;ve tried the lime juice and ice lime tea and both are very refreshing. Colleagues who have ordered the teh tarik say that it&#39;s quite good.<br><br>There are a few tables lined outside the shop for people to sip and chat but I have almost never been able to get a seat during lunch hour. Perhaps I need to get more aggressive with my tissue choping after all. I suggest taking away your drink and walking around the corner outdoors to sit near the bamboo plants. Compared with other nearby coffee/tea chains, I&#39;d rate Mr Teh Tarik as one of the better spots given their competitive prices, portions and speed.

A great place as any in the CBD to get your teh tarik fix. But they have such a wide range that you should try out.<br><br>I personally like their Teh Cino, it&#39;s super milky and leaves such an awesome after taste in your mouth after you gulp it down. Their ice lime tea is also a great refresher especially on a hot stuffy afternoon.<br><br>You&#39;ll fine executives chilling here at all times of the day as people come here not only for their after-lunch tea fix but also tea break and whatnot. It&#39;s a great place to have meetings away from the office once in a while, and they have snacks like curry puffs to complement your tea break.

text: Its alot harder than I would expect to find a decent cup of tea in the CBD area. Mr Teh Tarik was introduced to me on my first day of work at my current company by my manager, who relies on their signature Iced Lime Teas to get her through a scorching and stifling afternoon in the office. <br><br>Aside from the usual Teh Tariks and Kopi-Os, Mr Teh Tarik serves up a wide range of beverages that are not only interesting and a fresh change, but super yummy! I&#39;ve even compiled a list of &#39;what to drink for what situation&#39;: <br><br>1. Its hot, its sticky, and your&#39;re falling asleep: Iced Lime Tea (you can opt to have additional sugar syrup at the cost of the aunty in cute pigtails nagging at how high sugar levels are bad for health) a great balance between sweet iced tea with the tang of lime - without the face-screwing sourness!<br><br>2. Its cold, wet and you&#39;re STILL falling asleep: Kopi-O - its thick, creamy and leaves a pleasant after taste of coffee, none of that nasty instant stuff! <br><br>3. Gearing up for an afternoon meeting after a heavy lunch: Kopi-cino - a great sweeter alternative for coffee lovers, looks pretty as well! Half a cup of cream milk with thick kopi-o poured over. Topped with ice cubes and a generous coating of MILO POWDER. Sugar rush and caffeine all in one, POWER SEH! <br><br>4. You&#39;re cramping (that monthly pesky thing), bloated and just feel like something sickly and weak: Hot Ginger Milk Tea - Like what mum makes for us, but better! This tastes  a lot more palatable with the milkiness and added sweetness. It cures a morning sinus in a flash, soothes cramps and gets rid of any gas! <br><br>The branch at Far East Square is by far the best - we suspect it&#39;s because the adorable pigtailed aunty is really the boss of the franchise, but she keeps denying it! Protesting too much.....?

Fast service, delicious iced Teh Tarik and humongous take-away cups. The fact that its called the Mr. Teh Tarik Cartel is curious but the prices don&#39;t seem inflated despite the allusion to monopolistic price fixing.

text: The kaya toast is pretty good value.<br><br>Overheard the next table of customers, the older man telling his touristy friends that &#34;the tea here is the best, and coffee is number 2 compared to ABC.&#34;<br><br>I don&#39;t drink coffee so I have to take those words for what&#39;s its worth, free.  But my friends say the tea is very good. So there might some truth to it.

text: An above average &#34;traditional&#34; style coffee stall because of the ultra fast service. There&#39;s ample community seating in the basement floor of the Chevron House. Music is always pounding out of Guzman y Gomez next door, so sitting close by may not be conducive to your multi-billion dollar contract talks. Plus not offering espressos, lattes, Americanos, and the like could be a deal breaker.

text: It&#39;s always awesome to stumble upon a pretty cool spot that takes its business seriously. This cafe was a very pleasant surprise and a nice venue to have a great quality cup of coffee, people watch in the hustle of the CBD, wait for your next meeting, or have a quick pow wow with your colleague or client.<br><br>It was awesome to see Americano on the menu. I had the iced Americano and thoroughly enjoyed my drink to the last drop. <br><br>Good coffee is always welcome, other cafes can learn a thing or two from 6oz (I&#39;m talking to you TOM N TOM&#39;S!!!)

text: 6oz really hit the spot after a short 10 minute stroll from our hotel we found this cafe sitting just out of view at the edge of one of the business districts; I am a firm believer that no work can take place without good coffee so we checked it out.<br><br>The staff were friendly, since we got in at midnight and slept the entire morning I grabbed one of their bacon and egg rolls; the egg was still just soft inside and there was the option of adding hot salsa (yes please), the bread was crusty and it was very nice.<br><br>The coffee I order was really good hitting the balance of hot and string without going overboard.

At the entrance floor of an office building in the CBD this little oasis with great coffee is located. They have very pleasant outdoor seating in a tranquil environment. The coffee here is really excellent, the baristas can really make great espresso based beverages. To make things better they are also very friendly and always up for some talking and joking around.<br><br>The teas offered are actually also nice so not only for coffee drinkers. The also serve up some really nice sandwiches both for breakfast and for lunch.

text: This is my favorite coffee in Singapore. I get the iced mocha for $6. Service is great--friendly and responsive. Such a joy in this city. Good sandwiches, nice cakes. Ambience is not fantastic but at least it is always clean and because the place is in the atrium behind the escalators, the space is very open. Outside though, so be prepared to be hot.

text: My favorite milk tea place in Singapore! In addition to tea, Woobbee has coffee and yogurt drinks. I personally enjoy the simple Oolong Green Frothy Milk Tea and the Honey Mint Milk Tea. You have the option of adding pearls, grass jelly, or pudding! The pudding became so popular that they are selling them alone in little containers (like soy bean pudding!) and in three flavors: egg, chocolate, and taro. <br><br>For the health nut, you can customize your sugar level to no sugar, or 50% if you&#39;re a bit wild...I&#39;m crazy *nods* so I go for the 0% or 30%. <br><br>Prices range from $3-5 for most teas.

I love Woobbee!<br><br>This, together with Gong Cha and Koi, might be the top 3 bubble tea shops in Singapore for me. Woobbee stands out because of its cheerful and cute designs, high quality bubble tea and the range of flavors they have. The TJPG branch is the first one - and there will be a long queue every lunch time because of how refreshing and delicious their teas are. They have a second branch at Shaw Towers which is equally cool.<br><br>My favorite is the hazelnut milk tea with silken grass jelly (so good!) or the black tea with lychee (there is really a lychee inside). Otherwise a honey lemon with aloe for a warm day.<br><br>Whatever you pick, you can be sure you&#39;re gonna get a really good cup of Woobbee.

text: Decent coffee, ample and spacious seating, free and fast wifi (+power points for those who need them)... can&#39;t ask for much more! Add in the Korean music playing in the background, including familiar osts from the likes of Goblin... I guess that&#39;s why I&#39;ve found myself going back there a couple of times :) <br><br>Dal.komm has a good selection of cakes, none of which I&#39;ve really tried so I can&#39;t give an honest opinion, but the coffee is pretty good. Their sweet drinks (such as their matcha latte) can be too sweet though for some...

text: The coffee chain was very well known in Korea, and appeared in various TV drama. Recently it opened its first outlet in Singapore.  Besides coffee drinks, it was known for its bingsu and cube series drink. However the signature items were mostly not available when I visited the store on Monday. <br><br>Strawberry cube (S$8.50)<br>The drink was iced blended strawberries with milk. A tab sour but tasted not bad.<br><br>Iced Sweet Potato Latte (S$7.50)<br>The drink tasted although it was a tab powdery at the bottom.

text: Ok. Pastry is fresh. Warm and crispy. Espresso is good, not the best but good enough. They allow you to choose which beans you want. Ok the piece de resistance is that there&#39;s ton of space, plugs and a blinding fast internet. 34mbps down 54 up. Yikes<br>Would I come from here for bingsu? Haven&#39;t tried but probably ice lab is better and it&#39;s across the street. <br>Wifi pass is dalkomm2016

They serve pretty decent coffee and I liked the idea of coffee beans choices. They actually exceeded my expectation with their coffee and cakes selections, definitely better than many gimmicky cafe out there! <br><br>Definitely a good hangout place because the cafe is spacious and I like their quirky furniture too.

the one thing on the menu that brings great joy to me is the sweet potato latte.<br>i always loved this drink when i was living in Seoul so it was awesome to have it available in Singapore. the cafe atmosphere was cosy with a variety of seating options. the menu comes with food. Great for those who may want more than a drink. i bought the credit top up card and whenever you use that, you&#39;ll get a 10% discount on your bill. Definitely would return to try their other items on the menu.

text: It&#39;s 5 star pricing for 1 star service and portion size. <br><br>You pay a high price in service fees but everything is self service including menus, water, salt pepper and condiments. <br><br>Good taste was quite good but still hungry after the one piece of toast for $14. <br><br>My friend had the bagel which was double size for $5. She said her coffee was great and enjoyed her bagel.

text: A quiet cafe amongst the many cafes at South Beach. Power points and free wi-fi is available.<br><br>While pleasantly quiet and spacious, caffe vergnano fails to stand out from the various other options at South Beach. The beverages include standard machine coffee that lack the sincerity of the handmade cuppas in nearby cafes and the cakes failed to impress. I had the earl grey lavender cake ($8.50++) which had too much cream for my liking and only a hint of earl grey notes. My partner had the peanut butter cheesecake which was average.<br><br>That being said, one may still consider dropping by to get done work done or have some time alone to get away from the bustling city life on a busy afternoon.

I like this Jewel, it&#39;s on my walk to the office, and depending on what time you catch them the line is easy enough to get in and get out of without spending 15 getting your coffee (i&#39;m looking at you Starbucks)  They&#39;re still fairly new so every now and they do good specials like $4 lattes or $7 latte and crossiants.  Service is quick and with a smile.

Was relatively empty when we went on a Saturday lunchtime. <br><br>Heaps to choose room - I had difficulty deciding - everything sounded delicious. Ended up ordering waffles. The waffles themselves were really yummy, though the ice-cream was icy and therefore not very good. The coffees were ok.

text: Food was nice, but both my partner and I wanted waffles and they only had enough waffles on hand to make one meal. So I changed my order to French toast. My partner got her waffles bought out first and by the time she had finished eating, my own meal still hadn&#39;t been bought out.
Husband said toast was good. However, prices steep and service is slow considering the number of tables occupied. I would not recommend.

Came here on a Sunday morning and was positively surprised with the food and coffee. (Most of the restaurants on Robertson Quay are popular only because of the location and not the food). The staff is also attentive and friendly.

text: Lunch session Part 2<br><br>My bro suggested this Characters Cafe. I would never go or ask anyone to go to a character themed cafe. <br><br>One has to preorder the meals and each meal cost $29.90 (all inclusive include tax and service charge). <br><br>This is going to be one expensive lunch and of cos the two adults did not expect much from the food. <br><br>When we arrived at the cafe, it was not opened. My brother was surprised cos he even came here personally a couple of days ago and made the payment. He walked over to another store which probably are related and the girl quickly went to open the cafe.<br><br>The staff showed us to our table. The cafe is tiny, very tiny. I am glad I don&#39;t weigh 300 lbs. There are cute plushies everywhere. It is 100% kawaii!!<br>She also turned on this humongous tv which probably is over 70&#34; and it started playing Kungfu Panda 3. We looked around and snapped some pictures. The staff asked if we would like to have our lunch served and we said sure. I was a little puzzled; were we supposed to play with the plushies and when hungry, asked for our food? Note: the female staff was extremely friendly and nice. The kind who I probably can go sbux with.<br><br>After a very very long time, the food came. The stew or soup was nice with generous chunks of potatoes and carrots. The gyozas tasted like chinese dumplings in dim sum places. The meal also came with a beverage and a snack.<br><br>The meal definitely not worth the $29.90 each pax but hey at least there was the Rila Kuji ticket which was a sure win &#34;scratch &amp; win&#34; ticket.

Constantly finding a place to drink a cup of coffee while relaxing, I went to The Marshmallow Tree. Situated in a HDB block below Telok Blangah, this place is well-decorated with different types of seatings and to the young at heart.<br> <br>Initially I thought the Bandung Latte was a caffeinated drink, until the server told me it wasn&#39;t. Still, this was a very nice drink. With the correct amount of steamed milk, vanilla and rose syrup added, it feels sweet and milky enough. The only downside to this is that I felt that it was rather pricey.<br> <br>The Macaron S&#39;mores is also something unique to order here. The smores, which is essentially a marshmallow in between 2 macaron shells and smothered with the sauce of your liking (I chose Nutella). The smores burst upon the first mouthful. The marshmallows were soft and the Nutella made it feel more enriching. The shells were rather hard to chew on though.<br> <br>If you live nearby Telok Blangah, why not give this place a visit? I will find myself being here if I&#39;m around the area again (I feel like trying the waffles!)

text: Super small cafe, not advisable for a large group. Nothing much to choose from the menu too. Salad sauce too sour for me. But like the complimentary marshmallow for each drink ordered.<br>Slow service too but hope you enjoy taking photos of the nice garden decor.

Posted this in the Da Paolo Pizzabar by accident. That&#39;s a different outlet. Refer to my other review below - those items were better!<br><br>Blackforest cake ($8.80) - 3.5 stars<br>The alcohol taste is strong but pretty flavorless - enough to give me a hint of headache for nothing. I liked the cherries, but there&#39;s too much cream and too little cake - and it&#39;s the sort of cream that&#39;s tasteless and greasy. Not many cherries inside.<br><br>Tiramisu - 4 stars<br><br>Vegetable salad ($12) - 3.5 stars<br>Good.<br><br>Vegetable lasagna ($11.50) - 3.5 stars<br>Good!<br><br>Smoked salmon pizza ($8) - 1 star<br>Way too salty!

text: I have been looking for a nice cafe to read books on the weekends, and feel like I have found a perfect spot. Gastronomic offers a wide selection of drinks, pastries, and food with plenty of comfortable seating both inside and out. I would definitely come back again!

I was recommended the roast beef sandwich, got half and it&#39;s quite huge. Got a latte. Delish. Show you pics :)

text: Gastronomia has been a mainstay at Chip Bee for awhile and recently went through a minor revamp. It used to be solely focused on take aways but they now offer seating space with an extended menu to choose from for a simple, fast meal. Cafe plus takeaways! And it&#39;s never crowded, and a nice place to sit with a book, a friend, or just a cup of coffee. A surprising fact is their breakfast offerings (which goes on all-day). Very inexpensive, and huge portions. Scrambled eggs are creamy and good, and their egg sets can come with smoked salmon, sausages, according to your choice. Huge portions for around 10 - 15 bucks. They also offer soup + pizza combinations, and I think some sandwiches (haven&#39;t tried this). Get your breakfast cravings here and be more satisfied than elsewhere at Holland Village. I&#39;m very happy about their revamp.

text: Part of the Da Paolo group, this bistro is located on a quiet street in a residential area. It&#39;s more relaxing than the main holland village stretch, and quiet idyllic.<br><br>I had a sandwich and a cottage pie. Everything was freshly baked on the day itself, and my sandwich came stuffed full of goodness. The bread was crisp on the outside an still warm, while the cottage pie was very hearty and tasty. Still, it wasn&#39;t anything to shout about. Like it&#39;s coffee. And I&#39;d have to be really hard pressed to make my way all the way here just for pizzas or breads.<br><br>Ambience wise, it&#39;s nothing really special. The chairs aren&#39;t too comfortable and it&#39;s got a very limited seating capacity. Definitely no good for large groups. Still it&#39;s clean and cheerful, ad the glass front lets in the afternoon sun.<br><br>The large colourful meringues caught my eye but I did not get any as I was stuffed from my &#34;snack&#34;. I&#39;ll definitely be back to try them if I&#39;m in the neighbourhood!

I am an incredibly regular consumer of desserts at this Da Paolo. If you&#39;ve never had a dessert box (in the self-serve fridge), I suggest you don&#39;t. Everything in that fridge is delicious, made of high quality ingredients, relatively good value on a $/g basis and packed in a convenient albeit non-environmentally friendly container.<br><br>Despite attempts to contain my greed, my partner and I religiously eat 2 desserts every week. I like all the chocolate cake permutations, especially the giant $8 slice of chocolate &amp; vanilla sponge. I also love the lemon tart sans the sweet frosting on top. He likes the dragon role and tiramisu (if you want to prevent addiction, DON&#39;T touch this pick me up!).<br><br>If you live in the area and need a quality dessert fix to go with your video ez DVD rental for the night, Da Paolo is it.

Needed dinner, couldn&#39;t walk after a busy day, and sent partner in here to &#34;grab something, anything&#34; so there you go! Starved but not for long! He picked up the veggie lasagna which was bursting with every veggie and lots of flavor. He had the beef lasagna and loved that as well. Both takeaways were big slabs of lasagna, easy to nuke in the microwave and then gobble down. He also got the baked cheesecake and that was also very nice. Of course this place has happy hour with good specials we&#39;ll have to try next time.

I&#39;ve been coming here for years to buy the slices of pizza or pre-cooked food (that you can just take home and heat up, like the lasagnas). <br><br>In a now competitive deli scene, it now stands out as being okay. But not great. There&#39;s also gelato. Which is also okay. <br><br>The Da Paolo group really needs to step it up, they&#39;re no longer in the prime position they were at, at their peak!

This is my cheat sheet when I need to prepare dinner and I have no time or energy to muster. Located in the tranquil neighborhood of Chip Bee Gardens, Gastronomia has a decent selection of pasta sauces, antipasto, mains and pizzas that you can just grab and go. Probably won&#39;t be the meal of a lifetime and isn&#39;t exactly the most economical solution to your laziness but one has to make do with shortfalls. <br><br>The salmon pizza with pesto is a great choice to accompany beers during game night. If you are have about 15 minutes to spare and put in a tad more &#39;effort&#39;, get some tagliatelle and arrabaitta sauce to put together in the kitchen later on. Sauces tend to have little ingredients though, so stop by the Cold Storage across the road to grab something to spice it up if you will. If it is a hot day out there, have a scoop of gelato before you make your way home - it&#39;s nice enough to put you in a better mood.

text: I give this place 4 stars, cos it&#39;s always there when I need it :) Croissants, donuts for breakfast, delicious sandwhiches for lunch and pre-cooked food for dinner. They have a whole fridge stacked with choclate desserts, my favorite the flourless chocolate cake and the peanut chocolate cake which is basically the same as eating 15 snickers. Staff is very friendly as well. Coffee is a bit watery so i always get the capucino or espresso.

Gastronomia is a solid location for a quiet peaceful lunch spot in the Holland Village area for a nice sandwich. I have definitely come here for a peaceful solitary lunch on more than a few occasions. My favorite is the sausages with caramelized onions on crispy ciabatta bread. Its delicious. I always get the half sandwich because the portion is huge. My mother is a fan of their chocolate cakes.

Best ciabatta in town, hands down. This upmarket Italian deli is very consistent and I have come to rely on them for last minute dinner party details often rushing in for some grilled veggies and cheeses. The desserts in the fridge might look modest in their little plastic tubs but don&#39;t be fooled by appearances. The hazelnut crunch cake is perfection and they do a damn fine tiramisu. Skip the cupcakes. They store them open air with the air con blowing over them so they are dry dry dry. If you get there first thing in the morning have a fresh doughnut or croissant and an espresso.

text: Whenever I&#39;m asked by friends about where should they go to get good desserts, I always recommend them to go to Da Paolo Gastronomia. I have seriously liked everything that came out of their cake cooler so far and I can&#39;t decide which is the second best after the Tiramisu because they are all so darn good.

This place is a life-saver, especially their ciabatta, marinated artichokes, and pesto sauce. I think it is also one of the cheaper places to buy Parmegiano Reggiano, although nothing in Singapore beats stuffing an entire checked bag with groceries in Rome.

text: Unlike other Starbucks Café, this one is very comfy and cozy. I absolutely love the sofa benches and the interior is very clean bright and open! There are booths with big tables which is good for big groups. The best part is that it&#39;s not overly crowded here.

text: Stopped by here for a quick meal while visiting the Orchard mall. One of the main reasons I picked this place as opposed to one of the other stores in the food court was because this place looked very clean and had a fairly simple menu. <br><br>We ordered Laksa (which has seafood) and chicken curry with rice. Also, ordered the Singaporean coffee just because its so yum. We sat behind the counter by the window which was peaceful and had a great view.<br><br>Food was served very quick and portions were quite huge. Loved the laksa, and the coffee. They do not give napkins which seems to be a thing in most Singaporean places, so you might want to carry some. Staff was very friendly and helped me with my order when I wasn&#39;t sure on some of the ingredients on the order.

Toastbox is popping up all around Asia I have seen it in Singapore and Malaysia and have tried it in both locations. But I did hear that it started all in Singapore first. So I wanted to try it out here and enjoy a cup or coffee. <br><br>So they can make your coffee any way you want it. With milk, with or without sugar. They also have a few items of snacks that you can order with your coffee if you want but during this time I just really wanted a black cup of coffee. <br><br>Seating area is a little small but don&#39;t worry it&#39;s in a good court so if the side of Toastbox is full you can literally walk a few steps and get a table. <br><br>Service is very fast the ladies here are always rushing and they take their jobs pretty serious. So look over the menu and see what they have to offer.

text: Had breakfast here sunday morning and the line was long.  Took a good 20 min to order our food.  But depending on the time you come, its hit or miss with the wait times.  We ordered the Laksa which people said is a must try Singaporean dish.  It tasted like the thai version of tom kha kai or thrir coconut based soup.  I was confused with the &#34;noodles.&#34;  When you can eat noodles with a spoon are they really noodles?  The heat on it though is formidible, definitely not for those who can&#39;t handle the heat.  Its not as thick as the thai version which made me actually want the thai version instead.  The lady working the counter tho was rude and abrupt.  <br>What gets me though is that we ordeeed 2 othee things as well, but they didnt have it to order.   If you dont have it then dont put it on the menu, or put a sign signifying your out of it.  Instead of just rudely saying were out ot it!!!  <br>But the Singaporean coffee tho is legit. Strong and sweet!!!  Food did come out fast and theres double the seating because you can sit across the aisle at another seating area which was nice.  Im glad i tried the Laksa tho while i was in Singapore.

Chinese New Year cup', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Chinese New Year cup'}]
text: As with any other toastbox, they serve very nice local coffee. This outlet however is slightly pricier. They do have a two tier pricing I realize, $2.20 for kopi o at premium outlets like this (another example would be MBS) and $1.70 for heartland outlets. I am fine with this since they probably have higher rental to pay and the price is still cheaper than your western coffee. Will leave this review as a short and sharp one.

I believe this is the location in the Somerset Food Republic? In any case, I love Toastbox. Their coffee rocks, they serve great basic Singaporean food, and they&#39;re clean and organized and well branded. This location, however, has pretty bad service and long waits. <br><br>Advice for travelers - Singapore serves a kaya toast set that usually includes toast with kaya spread (google it) and soft boiled eggs. By soft boiled, think one step away from raw. If that isn&#39;t your thing, ask for the egg to be cooked longer. It&#39;s delicious! Make sure you get the coffee. It&#39;s served with evaporated milk and is well-sweetened. It&#39;s dark and strong and delicious!

Nice place to get some work done. There&#39;s a long library-style table in the middle of the seating area with plenty of central outlets and ample lighting. The mall is also usually pretty quiet, but not dead silent, which helps to focus. Free wifi using MilleniaWalk or Kith wifi with speeds of ~1.8mbps down / 2.5mpbs up, which is good enough. <br><br>Got the bacon, cheese, and egg grilled sandwich and a flat white for a quick pick-me-up and they definitely hit the spot. Kith kopi also looked pretty legit if condensed milk is your thing. <br><br>Bonus points for free flow carafes of water and a button to press to call waitstaff over for refills :) <br><br>Recommend if you&#39;re looking for a chill working space!

text: Opened 3 weeks ago, staff is still bouncy and chirpy and the manager is marshaling everyone around, including the new dude that had been standing in front of the cold water tanks for the last 15 min.  When I asked the manager about what he is doing, apparently this is pet of the training to be social.... He is very social with the water bottles for sure! :)<br><br>The 4 shot latté is very good and had the right effect.  Croissant was warm and buttery, they get it from the Swiss something (kitchen? Cottage?...), very good.<br><br>The open face omelette is a little lethargic even though I asked for it to be made with 3 eggs, it is normally made with &#34;about&#34; 2 eggs... Qual eggs perhaps?...  Lots of good mushroom, cherry tomatoes, beans, a generous serving of cheese and topped with a bunch of fresh spinach leaves.

text: Good quality sandwiches<br><br>Smoke duck sandwich comes with sourdough, green apple slices, Japanese cucumber, balsamic reduction - yummy!<br><br>Bacon sandwich - crispy bacon, tomato, lettuce, avocado, poached egg (which we mistook for mozzarella), Japanese mayonnaise on sourdough - lots of bacon! Very nice.<br><br>Sourdough bread is very nice.

Service was very poor. Once we were seated we we waited a while and then had to flag someone down to order. The long black was fresh and hot. The chocolate croissant was fine but the lemon blueberry pound cake didn&#39;t taste of lemon at all. They must&#39;ve tried to warm it because the slice was half luke-warm and half cold.

text: The food is great! <br><br>However the service is amongst the worst in Singapore. Every, single time we have been there, we&#39;ve walked away frustrated with the overall experience. Stay are very slow and don&#39;t have much knowledge of the menu, time frames and how to handle complaints. <br><br>One time I received my latte, which has sour milk and had curdled. I told the server who didn&#39;t seem to believe me, begrudgingly took and back and returned it with another(or the same?!) cup of curdled coffee! There have been orders which just never came, we&#39;ve had to wait 20 mins for a baby chino (which is just frothed milk!)<br><br>Massive shame. Food delicious but would really not recommend based on overall experience

Excellent cafe with lots of Gluten Free choices. I had the salmon steak, was very good salmon and loved the fresh spinach salad. They had gluten free cookies for dessert, lovely with coffee. A must try if you&#39;re Gluten Free.

I expected a lot more based on what my friends were telling me. This place was meh, nice outdoor seating, not too busy. Service was decent, prices were high.

text: This is a banana leaf oriented place. That means you go in and choose what type of thali you want. You can choose a mix of veggies with a meat of your choice. The quantity of rice given to you is a bit too much. You will fatten up if you eat here too much. It&#39;s a very south indian sort of a meal. They have some nice vadais as well and a really lovely coffee. It&#39;s a good 4 pm snack place for the coffee and vadai. The inside of this place looks like a school canteen. The service is pretty decent and the waiters always have a smile. Beware this is a heavy meal.

Tea accessories decor and seating.', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Tea accessories decor and seating.'}]
text: Afternoon tea has been a timeless English tradition and it&#39;s becoming a popular past time in Singapore as well. <br><br>Nestled in the lobby of a luxurious hotel, Swissotel The Stamford provides an elegant and chic ambiance surrounded by orchids and vibrant tea accessories makes for the perfect backdrop and further impressing guests with their impeccable service.<br><br>An exquisite selection of teas, pastries, finger sandwiches, decadent desserts and more are on offer to be enjoyed by your nearest and dearest. <br><br>All TWG staffs are required to be &#34;connoisseurs&#34; and have an extensive knowledge of their products as to provide top notch service to guests on the search for a certain aroma or flavor. <br><br>There are two options for the afternoon tea experience. The &#34;Fortune &#34; and &#34;Parisian&#34;. The Fortune is the way to go for those wanting something lighter. It features a three-tiered platter served with finger sandwiches, pastries and macarons, all of which comes with a few options that you can choose from. Hot or Iced tea included for $40. $11 supplement for tea for each additional person. <br><br>We opted for the pastrami sandwich, chocolate/strawberry/tiramisu macarons and finished off with a chocolate coffee cake that was just heavenly with a chocolate covered pop-rock candies giving it a whimsical texture in every bite. All were delightful and the strawberry vanilla infused tea as well as the classic green tea were both a deliciously sophisticated pairings. <br><br>The perfect spot for afternoon tea with friends.

text: This place makes Cold Storage seem sad and basic.<br><br>It isn&#39;t very big, but just one turn around the store took forever because I was essentially fascinated with every single item. Also I&#39;m quite sure this has the highest density of items labeled &#34;organic&#34; in all of Singapore. <br><br>So fear not River Valley. Whether it&#39;s truffle mayo, fresh squid ink spaghetti, salted cucumber soda, or rosemary-thyme-vanilla oil you&#39;re running low on (and I&#39;m really just scraping the organic iceberg with these items), Little Farms has got your back.

text: A new cafe in the west.. Not much to shout about. Coffee was a little over priced at $5.80 for a flat white that was slightly burnt. The marble cheesecake made up for it though, rich and creamy with a good base.  Service was average, the staff seemed a little untrained. Most tables even though empty was left dirty with crumbs from the previous diner. Would recommend a visit only if you happen to be in the building.

text: On Sunday 8 April, we went to Coffeenowhere, West Coast Plaza at 7.15pm For dinner. As I tried the braised pork belly rice last Monday and it was good, so I recommended it to my husband. We ordered 2 sets and a carbonara. After waiting for 15 min, the Carbonara came and a further 5 minutes, the pork belly rice came. The mixed vegetables (corn, peas, carrots) were sour in both bowls! They were obviously stale. We informed the staff. She asked us if we wanted 2 new sets and we said yes but without the vegetables. After waiting for 15min, the new bowls came. This time round we found that the braised eggs were not only unusually hard but sour too! Before I left, I feedback to the counter staff. She asked me if the eggs were really sour. I said yes and they should try it and that we had a very experience dining there. I asked her how could the restaurant sell stale food. She just said sorry sorry. That&#39;s all! <br><br>P/s: The table was not clean with crumbs leftover by previous diners.

A dead ant on the lettuce', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'A dead ant on the lettuce'}]
text: Flock or Flop?<br><br>Had wanted to have lunch Hua Bee Restaurant but had unfortunately got there too late. <br><br>Deciding that it was way too hot and we were way too hungry to look elsewhere, we decided to give Flock Cafe a try, seeing how popular it was. <br><br>Flock&#39;s Scrambled Eggs and Toast($7.50 + $2.50 for a side of baked beans) <br>I have to admit, the scrambled eggs were pretty decent. Good texture, not over cooked. The sautéed mushrooms were forgettable, baked beans were.... well.... tasted canned and the sourdough was unfortunately pretty hard and crunchy (almost like a crouton). <br><br>Scrambled Eggs &amp; Croissant w/ Crispy Bacon ($15.90)<br><br>Scrambled Eggs, consistent with mine so that&#39;s a good sign. The croissant was pretty buttery and was nice and flakey. Bacons were fried nice and crispy (although I&#39;m more of the juicy tender bacon person than the crispy sort).<br>The salad was an after though and came looking a bit limp and old. The most disappointing? The salad wasn&#39;t washed clean. The wife was just about to take a bit and suddenly noticed a dead ant on one of the lettuce leaves. Tsk tsk. Big disappointment. <br><br>Overall, while the Eggs were pretty good but everything else seemed like an after though. Definitely not a place we&#39;re chose to come back to.

text: Cute cafe tucked away in the estates (feels like the middle of nowhere but there are a few really nice cafés and book shops nearby). They are mainly a coffee and cake kind of place but do offer a limited set of meals. The banoffee cake (banana and toffee) was really nice and recommended as their iconic cake of choice by the staff. The coffee sadly is very average.<br><br>There were a lot of design types working away on laptops when I was there and I get the impression it&#39;s that kind of place. I loved their selection of street presses and alternative media. I would say go visit just so you can visit the great bookshop around the corner.

text: This is my safe brunch place, when we can&#39;t quite make up our minds where to go, we always end up here. The coffee is from liberty and so I enjoy their lattes and cappuccinos. My husband swears by their French toast with bananas and bacon, which comes with two nice thick slices of eggy fried brioche, sliced bananas, crispy bacon all drenched in maple syrup! The sweet and savory combo wins him over. <br><br>For me I always end up with the pork cheek sandwich. I agree with Marcus L, a little bit more toasted would be great. But once Ive sunk my teeth into that porky, cheesy, oily goodness I forget all about it. The small salad that comes with it lets me delude myself of it being pretty healthy. <br><br>Not managed to try much else at this cafe, I like that the seats are reasonably spaced out and I always manage somehow to get a table. So just based on that sandwich and French toast, will keep Flock cafe as my default place to go.

They could have freshen up the plate with a small handful of fresh berries, buttermilk cream and icing sugar instead of using pre- made stuff.The pancake is dry and too thick. Don&#39;t order.. <br><br>Actually I&#39;m not even coming back here for breakfast because there are loads of fabulous places around.

text: Just around the Neighbourhood if Tiong Bahru. There are many cafes around here. <br><br>Flock cafe would be one of the nicer interior compared to other. I would say that this cafe around Tiong Bahru has a good atmosphere with many of the customers are mix of locals and foreigners. <br><br>The food wise the price doesn&#39;t match their quality of food. I would recommend that they change their food portion as it seems smaller than usual. <br><br>But since it&#39;s a Neighbourhood cafe we got to be realistic in this. It&#39;s a business.

text: Flock Cafe has hit a tender spot in my heart. <br><br>Their coffee is consistently good, food is always freshly made and baked goods are absolutely divine. The beans from Liberty Roaster, paired with a lovely chocolate cake or orange cake go beyond the daily treat. I enjoy the space very much as it is vibrant yet quiet. The staffs are joyful and have a wide grind on the face. <br><br>The only complain a typical student/cafe frequenter would have is no wifi. But, to me, that makes Flock Cafe a better place for social interactions. The neighbourhood is a lovely place, with Book Actually and Strangelets around the corner, one can take a walk after a good coffee stop. <br><br>Keep up the great service and food!

Solid coffee! I had a good flat white and Americano, but my eggs on toast was just average. The sourdough was fresh and well toasted, but the eggs were runny and bland. The extra sausage I added looked like German weisswurst, but sadly didn&#39;t have much flavor, adding to the blandness.<br><br>The prices are cheaper than more hipster options like Group Therapy, but it&#39;s still pricey for the quality and portions. SGD 15-20 for most breakfast options.<br><br>Cash only, unless you&#39;ve got a NETS card.

text: Good reviews and being in the area brought my family here for lunch.<br><br>We ordered:<br>1) Breakfast Set with Sausage - scrambled eggs are nicely done and their bread is fragrant and tasty! Sausage is nice but nothing to rave about.<br><br>2) Pulled pork Sandwich - hubby liked it enough because of the bread though he found the sauce a tad too sweet<br><br>3) Mushroom Sandwich - I enjoyed mine very much! Thick slices of portobello mushrooms between fragrant bread slices.<br><br>4) Quiche Lorraine - daughter liked it though I thought it pretty ordinary. Ordinary nice, having said that.<br><br>The interior decor is very cool, both in ambience and in temperature too. It&#39;s a nice reprieve from the hot weather. Having said that, there are also many such arty-farty cafe around the area to check out.

text: The cakes here are delicious and yet not too sweet for my taste bud! There is a lot of seating and it&#39;s comfortably spaced out :) so it&#39;s a great place to hang out in groups of 4 or less. The prices are okay coffees are around $5 a cup. The cakes are $7 a piece! And I have to come back here to try more desserts!!! :)

text: Pretty cool cafe in the midst of many in Tiong Bahru. With both indoor and outdoor seating, this place is usually full with both locals and expats especially on weekends. Personally, I was not overly impressed with their breakfast poached eggs, though I did frequent here for coffee and their lunch specials (most often chicken katsu over rice) which was delicious. Aside from the lunch specials the prices aren&#39;t cheap but no brunch cafe in Tiong Bahru really is, plus the atmosphere and the friendly staff are well worth it. This isn&#39;t my go-to brunch place but will definitely come back here again!
