Beans sourced from Liberty Coffee Roasters.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Beans sourced from Liberty Coffee Roasters.'}]
text: Flock Café is one of the more unassuming players in the thriving Tiong Bahru cafe scene. Somehow it feels genuine and laid-back, which can hardly be said for nearby establishments like Forty Hands and Open Door Policy, both of which have amassed loyal cult followings (quite deservedly) and lost their chill factor in the process. Well I suppose crowds are a good thing for cafes to have, though it would be nice to be able to have a meal without feeling like I&#39;m in someone else&#39;s way all the time.<br><br>These crowds were absent from Flock when we visited one Saturday afternoon for tea. Bit of a welcome change from having to wait in the sweltering heat for a table. It wasn&#39;t that the eatery was devoid of people - there was a steady trickle of customers, and the staff looked hard at work.<br><br>Portobello, mozzarella &amp; rocket sandwich, $13.50 - Since this was supposed to be tea we ordered one of their sandwiches to share. T&#39;was a pricey sandwich, but I liked that the juicy portobello shroom was so big it occupied the entire pocket of ciabatta. This was quite delicious and would have made a substantial lunch for one, though y&#39;know, the pig in me wishes they had fries on the side.<br><br>They have other interesting offerings on their sandwich list like prawn and avocado, as well as pork cheek and gruyere.<br><br>Orange bundt cake, $5.00 - Having had a disappointing encounter with a bundt cake the week before, we decided to give the orange bundt cake here a shot. I thought it had a nice citrusy fragrance and crumbled quite satisfactorily, but the others found it to be a little too dry.<br><br>Mocha, $6.00 - Flock sources its beans from the ever-reliable Liberty Coffee, which pretty much ensures quality coffee brews. The mocha we had was frothy, chocolatey and every sip was laced with a pleasant hint of bitterness.<br><br>In line with their philosophy of providing a &#34;deliberately relaxed&#34; ambiance conducive for weekend catch up sessions between friends, Flock was modestly, yet comfortably furnished and I loved the warm lighting. The food here is above average, and it&#39;s a lovely place to spend a lazy day, as all my weekends tend to be. Wouldn&#39;t mind coming back at all.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/EvuVyLzNl-ArVZCyo0_-6w/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/flock-caf%C3%A9-singapore?reviewid=cgWXHpFnj44dLrxKtKBv0Q&select=EvuVyLzNl-ArVZCyo0_-6w', 'altText': 'Photo of Flock Café - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: The latest addition to Tiong Bahru&#39;s coffee offering, Flock serves up good coffee and delightful sandwiches alongside salads that will tickle your taste buds. <br><br>A little bird tells us that the meals have been devised by Singaporean master chef Jimmy Chok so that should give them additional foodie cred.  I love the fact that it&#39;s staffed by Singaporeans as well, unlike some of the joints in the area :)<br><br>Worth a shot and yes, don&#39;t miss their cakes and baked goods. I have a soft spot for their pecan pie muffin!

I don&#39;t drink coffee. <br><br>Therefore, it is not surprising that I&#39;ve yet to visit the  coffee-centric hipster joints. Nope, not  Chye Seng Huat or 40 Hands or 3 Hands or no hands (in fact when we drove out of the carpark at Moh Guan terrace I only realized that 40 hands was around the corner from Flock). <br><br>We decided on Flock because the dude wanted AM brunch and we try to explore new places on the fly. Flock has all the elements of a coffee-centric hipster joint (this kind of sounds like I&#39;m describing the Manic Pixie Dream Girl): Gentrified neighborhood, check. <br>Bare concrete or exposed ceilings/fixtures, check. <br>Food sources labelled (albeit in this it&#39;s ba/cakeries not farms), check.<br>Prices that make me double take, check. <br>Servers that look like my brother&#39;s friends, check.<br>Kids in clothes that are like &#34;This? oh I had this ol&#39; Cambridge satchel at the back of my closet&#34;, check.<br><br>We ordered a scrambled eggs &amp; bacon croissant-wich and the croque monsieur. The first sandwich kind of worked but the chef needs more practice doing a scramble (heat control dude!). Parts of my eggs were fully cooked and parts were liquid. Without jumping in the kitchen, I&#39;d say go have the big breakfast at Food For Thought to see what I mean by a good, even scramble. The rashes of bacon seemed to be lifted straight out of a packet into the pan because they were all stuck together. The croque monsieur was again, passable but kind of eh compared to the mother of all ham sandwiches at Choupinette.<br><br>Decent meal delivered fairly quickly. Chilled out environs. The coffee-centric hipster joint experience.

Lovely café located in the midst of the older HDB flats in Tiong Bahru. My colleagues find this place extremely overpriced, but what trendy place in Tiong Bahru isn&#39;t?<br><br>I&#39;ve only stopped by once for a small meal. I tried their quiche and cappuccino. The quiche wasn&#39;t life changing or Yelpworthy, but it was served warm and was perfectly portioned for my not-so-hungry stomach that day. The cappuccino met my standards (taste-wise) and was quite pretty, latte art-wise!<br><br>I love the ambiance here; for some reason, I didn&#39;t find it as cramped as 40 Hands, around the corner. The natural lighting (my favourite!) is great, and they also have covered outdoor seating, which is perfect for a rainy day.<br><br>Overall, another great spot for enjoying a bite to eat, a latte to drink, and perhaps an occasional Instagram selfie (as much as I hate them, it&#39;s amazing how natural lighting + a filter works wonders for a tired face!)

text: Very tasty flat white here, almost chocolaty in flavor! They also have some food options, but I didn&#39;t try any. Cozy digs, but with plenty of seating given that it appears to be very under the radar. Basically had the cafe to myself in the morning. Great for working in, as wifi speeds were very fast at 52u/55d, and well placed, obvious outlets near tables. Chill and friendly owner; he mentioned that he roasts his own beans, a blend coming from South America. Love the dark roast here, and I hope to try some of his other preparations another day.

text: I really wanted to like this place. I really did. Cos the guy running it is really nice. Very warm and all round nice guy. <br>Decor is welcoming and not so hipster it makes your teeth ache. The vibe is cosy and relaxed. <br>We sat down and ordered breakfast. We were the only ones in the cafe. <br>Dude running the place recommended the breakfast set - $12 for coffee and kaya toast with scrambled eggs. Sounded good so I ordered that. The BF went for hot dog. <br>So we waited. And waited. <br>6 mins later the coffee came. <br>We waited and waited. <br>Dude went out to chat with cabbie friend. <br>20 minutes later, my kaya toast came. 2 slices of mass produced bread. Scant kaya on one slice. Scrambled eggs was fluffy and moist. But I can make this at home with better toast and more kaya. <br>The hot dog took another 10 minutes. Probably cos he had to chop cabbage for the salad. <br>Verdict : coffee is ok but the food is overpriced and meh. <br>Can hang out for coffee. But the area has better food elsewhere. Sleepy neighbourhood joint is fine and good but this is too sleepy for my taste.

text: Went with my girlfriends last saturday. Having to look at instagram posts and menu, we noticed that they are popular for their black ink dishes. So we decided to order 黑 Rice, Black Sea, Crab Roll and Truffle fries to share.<br><br>All of us love the 黑 Rice. From its presentation, decent proportion of the rice and the fried chicken as well as the egg. The rice tasted like Kampong Fried Rice with rich flavour. However, was quite confused as I didn&#39;t taste the black ink and it was just for the rice appearance. Overall, its a must order whenever anyone visit there, with the black ink taste or not. <br><br>The crab roll was satisfactory as well. There was a lot of filling and the bun was crispy outside and soft inside, it was perfectly baked. <br><br>The least favourite dish of the day was the Black Sea. Although I can taste the black ink in the pasta, however the seafood was undercooked as so it was tough to eat. The flavour was only decent and the portion size is very small. <br><br>Truffle fries was great. Unlike most of the truffle fries out there, we can really smell and taste the truffle. <br><br>In conclusion, the winner of the day is the 黑 Rice and I would gladly recommend it to my friends. While the crab roll was satisfactory, i think both the roll and black sea portion need to be improved as we are playing quite a lot for the dishes. At the end of the day I can only remember I was full because of the fries.<br><br>Serving was good and the waitresses were attentive and full of smiles.

text: After getting completely lost looking for this place, we were surprised to find a super cute cafe in the middle of (almost) nowhere. It&#39;s discreetly hidden amongst a row of shophouses so it&#39;s really cute.<br><br>The service was a bit choppy - some servers were great and others were confused. I think if everyone had been a little more on top of things, I&#39;d be a much happier customer!<br><br>We got 3 things to share:<br>1. Cauliflower fritters - decent with a nice dipping sauce but was a little too over fried, I think the cauliflower would have done equally well roasted and would have been even better and healthier<br>2. Black rice with steak - really loved the texture of the rice which was bouncy and chewy and delicious with the Japanese mayo and tobiko! The steak was surprisingly juicy and not overcooked.<br>3. Buccatini with thick cut bacon - this was disappointing, the sauce had no flavor (squid ink) and the bacon was really salty. The bacon however, did balance out the pasta which had no flavor. We agreed that this would have done better with udon rather than using a pasta.<br><br>We had tea and coffee as well, all of which were fine but nothing stood out. I would go back if I lived/worked in the area, but wouldn&#39;t make a special trip.

Paddy Hills offers unique dishes in a hip environment on the West side of Singapore. It can get very crowded on weekends, so I would recommend coming here for lunch during the week if you work on the west side!<br><br>The unique spin on dishes here is definitely what makes Paddy Hills special. The Tonkatsu Ricotta, Salmon Dish, and Fish w/Potatoes were a few of my fav dishes. I am personally not a huge fan of potatoes but was very delighted to find theirs come in stringed shape, almost like noodles (see pic)<br><br>Menu items I didn&#39;t like as much: <br>- The Berry Hotcakes are also quite popular here, serving a generous portion of berries. The Hotcakes are very thick and filling however, and best for sharing among a group of 5-8 people (definitely not for one person). <br>- The Pink Pasta was quite thick/creamy and small in portion size. I personally am not a huge fan of creamy pastas however so I may be biased here. <br>- I also got to try the Garlic Fries as a side item, and found it to be the most mediocre item on the menu (among many exceptional items). <br><br>Additional factors:<br>- Location is a bit out of the way (need to taxi)<br>- You pay the price. I went as a group of 3, ordering 3 mains, 1 side, and 2 coffees. The bill came out to $105 (and this was over lunch)!<br><br>I definitely want to come back to try their other items. Overall a great ambiance with light wood, freshly roasted coffee, and friendly staff. Strongly recommend, if it wasn&#39;t for the price tag!

text: Located after the windy road off S. Buona Vista (nearer to Pasir Panjang) is this hipster cafe. There will be a row of shophouses and it is next to the intersection of Lorong Sarhad.<br><br>Came here on a Monday around 1.30pm for my cousin&#39;s birthday party. Since my mother and I were the last one to arrive, some dishes are laid on the long dining table and we could taste some of the leftovers.<br><br>Tried the risotto. Since it has been out for awhile before I arrive, the taste was not too great. We also tried the hot chick (fried &#34;popcorn&#34; chicken). Pretty well done as it was served after we arrived. The homemade chilli on the side did pair well with the chicken bites. The chicken skin was crunchy and the meat itself was juicy when served.<br><br>My aunt then decided to order Kimchi Fried Rice for both my mother and I. We did not wait for long for it. When it arrived, it came in a bigger portion than expected (serves up to 2 or 3 pax). The lighting at the longest table was not that great hence I had to snap a quick photo before tasting the dish.<br><br>For this dish, I love the steak slices. I ordered medium well and it turned out chewy and juicy to my likings. The kimchi portion for this dish was small. Would prefer it to be slightly more. The steaks definitely overpowered the flavors in the dish. For the rice, it was well-fried. The color of the fried rice were constant throughout the dish and the flavors linger in the mouth. Definitely one of the recommended dish here.<br><br>I managed to try the &#34;famous and instagramable&#34; Berry Ricotta hotcakes. The berries were sweet and well-spread around the hotcakes. But the hotcakes itself was a little dry for me. <br><br>Service was not bad either. The staffs approached quickly when you raised your hand. Price wise, it would be better if it is slightly cheaper. Will be back to try out other dishes.

text: Went on a Sunday at noon and thankfully got seated quite promptly. (There was a long line when we left at 1pm). <br><br>Ambience was great - we were seated at the bar so we could watch the baristas in action. Service was also prompt. <br><br>The quinoa salmon was well-executed, with the quinoa providing a satisfying crunch. The salmon was moist and flavorful. Portion&#39;s not very big though. <br><br>Was hoping to order the squid ink pasta but it wasn&#39;t on the menu anymore. Ordered the uni tagliatelle and wasn&#39;t disappointed. The prawn was fresh and the pasta creamy with uni. Highly recommended. <br><br>Ordered the berry hotcake due to the rave reviews I&#39;ve seen on social media. It came extremely prettily plated, and there was a good assortment of berries. The cake itself though, was slightly too dry for my liking, though spots of cream in the cake was a nice tough. The cake itself wasn&#39;t too sweet, which was good, but I wouldn&#39;t come here just for this. <br><br>It&#39;s a slightly pricey place for brunch. The above 3 dishes + a latte came up to $70+, though on the whole one of my preferred cafes in Singapore.

text: This place is worth the trip down! Went on Sunday noon and there was a queue, but got a seat with my 3 friends after awhile. Quality in the food and friendly staff, felt that the food quality was almost restaurant standard, definitely exceed the usual cafe standards in Singapore!<br><br>The pink pasta and kimchi fried rice was so goooooood, everyone ordered a different main and really liked all the dishes after we shared them. Highly recommended to try out this place.

text: New-kid-on-the-block, Paddy Hills&#39;s location is not new to us. What used to be the familiar Lim Seng Lee Duck Rice shop has now become a hip, Instagram-able café. If you&#39;re an adventurous food-lover, you will love Paddy Hills for their creative Australian-Japanese International Fusion Food and specialty coffee. Try their Golden Man Tou with Truffle Fries for an appetizing bite or Hao Da De Ji for sharing if you&#39;re with a big group.<br><br>A coffee bar occupies the centre space of the café where one can opt to sit at the bar to observe the skilful baristas at work. Psst, we spied the Slayer Espresso machine AKA the &#34;Ferrari&#34; of coffee machines.<br><br>If you&#39;re looking for a spacious place with good Wi-Fi (it&#39;s the Neon Pink words on the wall outside!) and a soothing ambience to get some work done, drop by Paddy Hills on a weekday. We visited on a weekday and the crowd was gleefully minimal although we heard that it can get really crowded on weekends.<br>Touted as a café in the day and a tapas bar at night, we will be sure to stop by in the evening for our next visit.

text: Eclectic fusion finger food served while you lounge on vintage chairs.<br><br>This very recently opened restaurant/drinks spot is located where the famous Lim Seng Lee Duck Rice Eating House once stood. The large windows, industrial-chic looking interior, differently textured walls of concrete, plywood and neon lighting already scream hipster before you enter. <br><br>It&#39;s rather comfortable inside as you settle down and start looking at the menu. Some items are meant for sharing and the rest were noodle or yakitori dishes. I was very intrigued by the fusion dishes and proceeded to order the fried man tou sliders and toasted spicy rice cakes.<br><br>Six fried man tou sliders arrived arranged on a large plate with two different sauces and a side of truffle fries. I was more impressed with the pork belly sliders than the lamb sliders, which I felt were too lean and dry. The korean rice cakes (Tteokbokki) arrived with a suitably crispy and slightly charred exterior with a spicy sauce mixed with a raw egg, salmon roe (ikura) and some pork slices. Although I enjoyed the juxtaposition of textures and flavors, the sauce was too salty for my liking.<br><br>The coffee, however, is decently good. I saw the USD$21,000 Slayer(tm) machine sitting on the counter. I also think they get their beans from a local roaster. Earlier, I observed staff members at the bar fiddle with the Slayer(tm) espresso machine and attempt to coax it to deliver the right consistency of caffeine shot.<br><br>Prices are much higher to compensate for not levying a service charge. I&#39;m a little on the fence as the food is interesting but being a week old meant they still had a lot of kinks to iron out. <br><br>Their wait staff were still rather new and confused on procedure, and the kitchen took a really long time (45 mins) to churn out the dishes before running out of food and closing early at 8:45pm. I saw a couple of angry (and hungry) customers exchanging words with the service staff. The repeated adjustment, tweaking and fiddling with the espresso machine also didn&#39;t give me much confidence.<br><br>As I left, I&#39;m reminded again of the good coffee as I saw the crate that the Slayer machine arrived in, displayed outside and used as a bench or table. Duck rice fans, you will have to head over to Little India. There&#39;s no duck on the menu here.

text: Came in here a second time in 7 days as I had not the opportunity to try the coffee the last time. Was the second customer of the day and ordered the latte and items from the breakfast menu. <br>Wow!! Love the coffee (99-1 blend). Chocolately and creamy. Love the full bodied layers despite the milk in the latte. Ordered the small breakfast and berry ricotta hotcake. Great stuff again!! Small breakfast was polenta and a runny egg on toast, with the morning-welcome fragance of mushrooms and truffle. Hotcake was fantastic despite the 30-minute wait - great on the palatte and the eyes. Great for breakfast. The food quantity is actually good enuf for 2 persons to share so order accordingly. What a difference from my last brunch visit. Niceee

Totally worth the trip out for a Saturday brunch.<br><br>Cool and chill cafe with an interesting menu and sizable portions. I ordered the kimchi fried rice and totally devoured it in a few bites. The fried rice is prepared in such a way that it doesn&#39;t feel like you are eating typical Chinese fried rice, it feels like actual quality in every bite. It comes with some steak slices and an egg that you mix to add a bit more flavor. Totally recommend getting this plate.<br><br>I also ordered the cauliflower fritters (didn&#39;t expect it to be such a large portion) and the Paradise Shake(?) (the one with coconut and torched pineapple). So so so good, the shake didn&#39;t even feel heavy.<br><br>My girlfriend ordered the berry ricotta pancakes which were also really good.<br><br>Highly recommend checking this place out. Service is excellent with a happy and smiling young bunch of staff. Will be coming back!

text: Been here twice already and both times there were more hits than misses for all the dishes ordered. Service staff were friendly, polite and prompt. Food quality is better than most cafes out there, almost restaurant standard. Coffee is decent and they offer brew coffee too which is great! Only downside is that location-wise it&#39;s not as convenient but definitely worth a trip if you&#39;re nearby the area! Oh and I&#39;ve never had to wait for a table because I went slightly after peak hours about 1.30pm.

Pretty solid fare at a steep price. Pink pasta with scallop (singular) and prawn (also singular) was tasty but I would&#39;ve appreciated more seafood for a $30 dish! The kimchi fried rice was also quite scrumptious and came with a good portion of medium rare steak, alas the steak was of middling quality. <br><br>The real winner here were actually the cocktails (white sangria to be specific). At $18 a piece they aren&#39;t cheap but if you want to splurge it&#39;s worth it! It feels like you&#39;re paying for the vibe, which is fair given the dearth of hip places like this in Singapore, but I froze my butt off with the AC cranked up and they couldn&#39;t move us because of a lack of available tables.

text: Great brunch with frens. Ordered mutton meatball, big breakfast and berries ricotta pancake. For drinks, we had 2 ounce white coffee and yuzu drink. Nice ambience and great food!
Paddy Hills is a must-go for brunch. The Green Scramble &amp; Bacon - house cured bacon chop, walnut pesto crushed potatoes &amp; mustard dressing - is certainly worth the $23. Service is good too.

userinfo: {'link': '/user_details?userid=tieQ1FQ3BdXO7PjShPE28g', 'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/assets/srv0/yelp_styleguide/514f6997a318/assets/img/default_avatars/user_60_square.png', 'srcSet': None, 'markupDisplayName': 'Bern T.', 'displayLocation': 'Singapore, Singapore', 'altText': 'Bern T.', 'userUrl': '/user_details?userid=tieQ1FQ3BdXO7PjShPE28g', 'partnerAlias': None, 'friendCount': 1, 'photoCount': None, 'reviewCount': 80, 'eliteYear': None}
text: Food-wise, it was a hit-and-miss averaging on decent, and occasionally bordering on so-so. Methinks Paddy Hills would make a pretty worthwhile option if you&#39;re in the area, but I don&#39;t think the food was excellent enough to warrant travelling from afar.<br><br>The bistro is run by a lean workforce, but, for a place that doesn&#39;t have any service charge, service was fantastic - smiley and efficient. Another perk, no GST either! <br><br>That said, my grouse was mainly regarding the menu, it tended towards unnecessary and wasted pretense. If a menu requires Dr Google&#39;s assistance to make an informed decision, that&#39;s far too much posturing. I mean, how many regular people know what bagna cauda is? Or even how to pronounce it?! <br><br>Also, a girlfriend took issue with the mispresentation on the menu. What was named &#39;Hash Hash&#39; with a description of &#34;sauteed beef, mushroom, chorizo, doughstick and sous vide egg&#34; turned out to be a beef bak kut teh. Calling a dish &#34;hash&#34;, she said, and I quite agree, implies that the whole jin-gang is sauteed, as you would a breakfast hash. A soupy bak kut teh IS NOT a hash. Strip away the pretense, I think, and re-direct the effort to the food. That&#39;s what draws in the crowds anyway.<br><br>We had:<br><br>1) Berry Ricotta Hotcake ($23) adorned with blueberry sugar, pinenuts, raspberries, strawberries, blueberries, yuzu gel, and maple syrup: Very pretty, and it tasted as good as it looked. Thick, dense, but fluffy, these were the best pancakes I&#39;ve had for as long as I can remember.<br><br>2) Quesadillas ($20) stuffed with pulled duck and pickles, served with charred baby capsicum and sweet corn, and sided by a garlic aioli and guacamole: The quesadillas, in addition to being laced with parsley, were mediocre. My parsley-loving friend, who had this, said to give this a hard pass.<br><br>3) Hash Hash ($24): Misleading description aside, this was a reasonably commendable and very comforting bowl of beef bak kut teh. Meltingly soft and wonderfully fatty, the luscious hunks of meat could have passed off as pork if I hadn&#39;t been informed otherwise. I particularly liked the western twist of the sous vide egg, arugula leaves, and chickpeas.<br><br>4) Kimchi Fried Rice ($20): much touted, but turned out middling, even with the perfectly wobbly sous vide egg, and medium-well tender steak. I&#39;ve had better<br><br>Pictures are at <a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Fthehungrybunnie.blogspot.sg%2F2015%2F11%2Fpaddy-hills.html&amp;s=4185622fedc7f15b249b9f865f4dac815bb5a3ed3d64ab62579a0c1182b2a0d3" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">thehungrybunnie.blogspot…</a>

text: Four stars for having push pop cake. This one was the tiramisu and it was tasty. It&#39;s grossly overpriced but it gave me a good laugh and the cake wasn&#39;t horrible.<br><br>The venue itself is very clean, modern, yet quaint and cozy.<br><br>There&#39;s also a little section where you can buy unique gift items like piggy banks, picture frames, tiny flowers, all really cool stuff that you don&#39;t see at normal stores. Very artsy cool like something you&#39;d find in the lobby shop of a modern art museum.<br><br>This place is hidden on Duxton Road but worth a visit for coffee/dessert after a meal.

text: Met a friend for coffee and since I hadn&#39;t had lunch decided to try their lunch menu. They actually have lunch and tea sets which are good deals for weekdays. Unfortunately I missed the timing for lunch. But they still serve all day so I had the Big Plate at $19 which had sausage, bacon, sautéed mushrooms, eggs of your choice and toast of your choice. With a generous serving of rocket on the side. The latte was all right but for $5 it&#39;s a tad expensive

GTC is probably the best cafe in this side of town. I have been trying different things on each of my visits and have been delighted with each of my orders. Highly recommended for a breezy brunch with friends on the weekend. The location is indoors but the ambiance and reasonable pricing makes up for the lack of views

text: This is my favourite cafe! No qualms about this. It is so underrated. They sell food with a heart. It is moderately priced but the portions are good. Non pretentious and honestly tasty food. I love the handmade granola bowl and warm oats with fresh fruits. I was also once addicted to their bacon aglio olio. The caramel cappucino and roasted almond latte literally soothe your soul. The Katong branch is rather quiet during weekday evenings and exceptionally crowded on weekends. But this place is an AWESOME gem.

text: Was searching for cafe with airconditioning in Katong and this was one of those that came up. <br><br>Great ambience, good coffee, delicious waffles, fabulous airconditioning. <br><br>Came across their shop name in some coffee/food guide online and realized this was a branch of the original shop in Duxton. <br><br>It&#39;s located in a relatively new Hotel cum tiny Mall. Katong area is known for its tough/painful parking experience. Was really surprised to find many parking lots in the mall/hotel outdoor parking. Major plus point. Another mall slightly further up, 112 Katong, parking is a complete pain. <br><br>Ordered a Latte, Mocha, Almond Roasted Latte, Orange Juice and two waffles for about $50. Pretty pricey but definitely not a deterrence to many. The shop was running full for the two hours that we were there. <br><br>The coffee were fragrant and absolutely delicious, the strength of coffee and balance of milk is awesome. The waffles were really good too.<br><br>Would definitely recommend this place for all the factors (coffee, food, aircon, parking). One star short for the high price tag.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/vRUX0HcJqr73jevcRehPOA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/group-therapy-cafe-singapore?reviewid=XO8Ov_FHmnNobOrqxF4kkA&select=vRUX0HcJqr73jevcRehPOA', 'altText': 'Photo of Group Therapy Cafe - Singapore, Singapore. Great coffee. Pity the wings', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Great coffee. Pity the wings'}]
text: The cafe smelled amazing. All you could smell walking into the cafe was truffle oil. Me - truffle fan - was overjoyed. The menu was pretty enticing too. Lots of great brunch choices. The sour-faced cashier took our order not too willingly. <br>Coffee we got were flat whites. Can&#39;t go wrong with them. They were made pretty well except that it was served in a cup slightly bigger than an expresso cup. Size wise, disappointing for the $5 price tag. <br>The food arrived pretty soon after. I had the croque madame, a sunny side up on top of two dry and thick pieces of bread with ham bacon and a measly amount of cheese. This is not how you do a croque Madame. No way. The cheese was pathetic, they were so stingy with it that it didn&#39;t even ooze out. Usually a croque Madame would have some béchamel sauce and cheese melted on it. Nope. This was dry, tasteless and not worth $16. The sarnies I make (and I don&#39;t cook much) are way better. Really not cool to disappoint someone who wanted great brunch. <br>My friend had the poached eggs with smoked salmon and hollandaise sauce. The sauce was not too bad but the eggs were overcooked. No runny egg yolks oozing out when you cut them. Well, isn&#39;t the runnier texture the point of poached eggs? <br>We got the chicken wings too. These were just battered wings that were deep fried without any seasoning. It was a what the... moment when we bit into the chicken. Unforgivable. <br><br>My take: if you want to be a coffee joint, then stick to it. Don&#39;t offer food you don&#39;t know or can&#39;t make well. The coffee here, yes. The food, never again. The cashier could do with a smile on her face too.

Nice cosy cafe to chill out. Relatively quiet as the mall is away from the main buzz. Love the wooden and rustic / industrial look. Coffee was good and a good selection of cakes and eats. Prices are reasonable as well.

text: Rather small indoor setting at one glance, but the ambiance is pretty nice. Eclectic crowd on a Sunday morning. Enjoyed my cuppa, and lovely Hollandaise sauce to go with the Eggs Benedict - very creamy. Generous portion of smoked salmon on the brioche.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/OAgXJeNcdHjyNVNg911mYg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/group-therapy-cafe-singapore?reviewid=2BNWhjr5bQ3una5U8cIMLg&select=OAgXJeNcdHjyNVNg911mYg', 'altText': 'Photo of Group Therapy Cafe - Singapore, Singapore. Carbonara', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Carbonara'}]
text: The eastern branch of their original outlet at Duxton, this outlet does not disappoint. Generous portions, great breads and I do love a good homemade hollandaise sauce. They are also very accommodating in customizing my orders, which is great.<br><br>Love their coffees too, which is rich, robust and full-bodied. None of that tannic aftertaste. On lucky days, you may also get homemade yummy baked goods from the owner&#39;s mum secret recipe. <br><br>The only thing gripe I have about this place is that it is located within a mall, which takes away a lot of its personality, unlike its sister outlet at Duxton. You&#39;ll be surprised how busy it gets with the expat crowd who lives in the east every morning, even on weekdays.

Nice cosy cafe to chill out. Relatively quiet as the mall is away from the main buzz. Love the wooden and rustic / industrial look. Coffee was good and a good selection of cakes and eats. Prices are reasonable as well.

text: For a college cafe, it&#39;s pretty great.  For a Singapore cafe, it&#39;s hipster vibes with OK drinks and food options.  The high ceilings, tucked away couches, and shared tables make it an easy place to grab a bite and relax, read, or work.  Service is pretty low-key with the order at the counter style service.  Music is medium volume during the day- looks like they can host live music or DJ events.  They take pretty much all forms of payment to accommodate accounts from all over the world- so that&#39;s a bonus.

Food is ok average here but the biggest draw is the bouncy castle they have set up during the weekends. <br><br>I love the part of the bouncy castle being INSIDE the aircon cafe where parents are chill over makan while the children have fun wasting their energy. <br><br>They have ample parking and table seats so we don&#39;t feel bad just sitting there and nursing our drinks while waiting for the kids to come back to the table for water and more food. <br><br>A definite come-to place for parents chillax and children playing time.

text: A very cool place. High ceilings with lots of glass. It is definitely a comfortable place to go and relax over food and coffee. It&#39;s in the La Salle Art College Campus. <br><br>I heard that this cafe recently introduced some Mexican dishes. I&#39;m always a bit skeptical because there are VERY little options for Mexican in Singapore. I was surprised to find affordable prices but even more surprised to find such a hearty portion. I had the chipotle chicken taco and it was really good. <br><br>Iced cafe latte: $5.5<br>Chipotle chicken taco: $5.5<br>Ambiance: modern, open<br>Recommended: Yes! Try the Mexican.

I always loved 15 Minutes and to see if close down was a sad moment as it was a great place to chill and hangout. However out with the old and in with the new. <br><br>Overall atmosphere of this place was comfy and it has a very organic theme to the place. Plenty of seats and a stage for performances. Overall I loved the atmosphere. <br><br>Food is not too bad as well, however I do have to point out I was here for lunch and all I had was the Dory Fish dipped with Beer Batter and the Carbonara. The Carbonara was lovely as it was not drowned in sauce like how a lot of places does it. It was however a little more to the dry side and I did wish for just a tiny bit more sauce. This fish was by far my favorite, golden crunch on the outside and moist on the inside. Definitely would recommend it.<br><br>Will definitely come back here a second time and will update this review as I get to try out more of their food.

On the outside, this cafe/restaurant looks great. Hip decor, nice touches and an overall comfy, cheery feel. The sort of place you would really want to hang out in with a bunch of friends.<br><br>Which made me want to like it that much more.<br><br>And which made my actual experience of it that much more disappointing. In short - the food was just no good.<br><br>I went for lunch and had a grilled chicken with salad for $8.90. Sounded promising. The chicken was a chicken chop (thigh, whole piece) - and was just passable, and not very different from the sort of chicken chop you get from a western food stall in the hawker centre. It came with a small side salad that was lettuce greens and tomatoes. The chicken was covered with a cheesy (I think) sauce. It was just meh. I would not go back for this food.<br><br>One other thing - when our food was served, my friend asked the wait staff what the sauce was (as it was not indicated on the menu). She just smiled and said she was &#34;not sure&#34;. That was it. Not sure. Didn&#39;t bother to find out either.<br><br>Nice try, won&#39;t go back. Sorry. A damn shame because I really, really liked the previous cafe that used to be at this location - 15 Minutes Cafe. I shall mourn its demise.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/2KsxhXRq1ot3beDgrEEx6Q/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/mays-kafe-singapore-2?reviewid=awHvm225xiklqR7GBk9MYA&select=2KsxhXRq1ot3beDgrEEx6Q', 'altText': "Photo of May's Kafe - Singapore, Singapore", 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: YAY! This place has won me over! Really. I always visit the open air, horribly ventilated hawker centre upstairs during my work lunch. One of the days during CNY week that the hawker centre was closed and we tried to eat at May&#39;s Kafe, it turned out to be not so bad afterall! I actually think that the curry chicken with rice beat the usual coffee chain like Toast Box and Killiney. <br><br>So, my colleagues and I came back a few more times and tried a few other dishes. They are all pretty good &amp; the local coffee and other beverages do not disappoint. <br><br>One day if you happen to be at Beauty World, just come to May&#39;s Kafe and sit at the air conditioned basement area and take in the beauty of time-stopping in this 1970s mall and appreciate how time flies by in Singapore and this mall still retains the beauty of yesteryears.
Located at void deck next to b1 lift lobby. Compare to the smoky &amp; stuffy food stalks at roof top, I prefer to have my morning coffee and toast here.

text: Two years later, tried again. Bumping up to 5 stars because they are still in business, service is still great (although empty on a Sumday), and their tea set remains the same price. <br><br>Had the vegetable curry set, comes with a nice side salad and a drink. Yum yum. Loved it.

text: It has been a while since I last visited Okada Coffee and I finally got to try its signature Mont Blanc ($9), made with the premium chestnuts from its hometown Kumamoto. The patterned layers of Mont Blanc set it apart from the usual &#34;noodle strand&#34; chestnut cakes, with a meringue heart that gave a good measure of crunch. <br><br>The Creme de marron was full of chestnut goodness but the Creme Chantily was in short supply and I wished it could be significantly less sweet. <br><br>Fortunately, it&#39;s another chestnut sweet, the Okada Roll ($8), was rational on sugar. The core was pumped up with light chestnut cream and one could inhale whiffs of eggy aroma in the pillowy sponge. <br><br>The Matcha Cake is a simple construction of green tea mousse, azuki beans and sponge. Nothing much fanciful.

text: This place is a great venue around lunchtime, aka for those who are too hungry to queue. This happens to me. A lot. <br><br>Tucked behind Simply Wrapps, Okada Coffee is a great alternative to Ya Kun Kaya Toast, which is on the 2nd Floor of 100 AM. The specialty is the Japanese curry. All the curry bases are the same with different toppings, ie beef, katsu, etc..The curry here isn&#39;t my favorite in Singapore, but it is indeed made in house. The desserts also look quite appetizing though I have yet to try them. Similar to Ricky S., I hope this place stays around for a while. It&#39;s a good alternative to the different joints around the area. <br><br>Lunch specials are $17 and include a salad, tea/coffee, and a plate of curry. Okada is a homey place

text: In my family, Weekends always mean family togetherness! How I always look forward to the family bonding over a good meal. This weekend we decided to check out the Bakery &amp; Bar St Marc at Greenland Park (new section at East coast park). We absolutely loved the vibe and the area surrounding of the restaurant. In front of the restaurant is a green field facing the sea. It&#39;s definitely a place for family to bring kids. <br><br>Also, Interestingly I think this might be the first St Marc outlet to offer food, other than just breads, pastries and desserts. Inside, The restaurant is rather spacious and can cater for big groups. <br><br>Once seated we asked for cold water for the family. We were then told 1 jug of water was $1. What?! It could have been tap water for all we know and it&#39;s $1?! Are we paying for their utility bills or what?! Seriously... Anyway no choice we took 3 skinny jugs for our family of 8. <br><br>Our order include:<br>1. Kids fish &amp; chips (2 tiny pieces with tiny shoe string fries)<br>2. Spaghetti bolognese<br>3. Prawn aglio olio<br>4. Seafood spaghetti<br>5. Wagyu beef burger (served with tiny shoe string fries) <br><br>When the food arrived, To be honest, the portions were all rather small even by a lady&#39;s standard. The nephew who ate the wagyu beef burger enjoyed it, he said the beef was cooked just right and was juicy and delicious. The rest of us had only a phrase to describe our seafood/prawn pasta - &#34;it&#39;s like hokkien mee&#34;. Ok don&#39;t get us wrong, the pastas were tasty. The sauce for the seafood pasta had a good broth base that made it very flavorful.  The seafood and prawns used were very fresh. But the style of pasta, the execution is more Japanese than Italian. <br><br>What&#39;s also surprising was that they don&#39;t charge service charge or GST. Hmmm... That sort of appeased our frustrations with having to pay for ice water. :)<br><br>On the whole I think this is an ok and versatile place where one can have the flexibility of having tea to actual meal, whilst having the space outside for the kids to run and play. <br><br>Ps. Greenland park is situated at East Coast Park, car park area C1. Parking may be quite difficult to get over the weekend.

All round pretty good Aussie food. Pleasant setting although road noise is a little loud.  $6 for a flat white is steep considering the small small cup.  Great area for kids to run and play. Recommend for brunch.

Had come here with a big group for desserts. Got the chocolate lava cake, creme brûlée and bunch of coffees. Was average in terms of the desserts. Have tasted better. Good place to hang out with a group of friends. one of the few places in Singapore where you can actually sit outside without too much discomfort.

text: $40 for a tasteless Reuben Sandwich &amp; frozen margarita - ouch!  Corned beef should be pinky red - not a dirty grey btw....the sauerkraut should be tart &amp; crisp not soggy and bland.  Very disappointed.

Standard has dropped a lot over the years. <br><br>Ordered the pancakes during a not so busy time of 4pm and they were pretty obviously microwaved and not freshly made. How do I know? Arrived almost instantly, with steam blazing hot coming out of the pancakes and a horrible texture that can only be achieved with microwaved-old-food. <br><br>Tasted pretty horrible and the garnish of half a sliced banana was just sad. Was served with what tasted like cheap syrup rather than a maple sauce or anything remotely nice. <br><br>Had the rosti as well. Did not add salt at all and the &#34;poached&#34; eggs were kinda hard boiled. Nothing was seasoned properly. Kinda disappointing because this was in my memory a great place to eat at. <br><br>Prices are still high. Ordering system was good and efficient but poorly planned on some tables. The iPad was placed in the middle of 2 diners eating which to me was pretty poor thinking. The floor around me was wet and had food all around telling me that the servers were pretty oblivious to things going on around the restaurant. <br><br>Pretty sure this does not happen that often here but this particular experience was exceptionally poor. For their prices &amp; the amount of people that were there while I was there at 4pm, they really should have some sort of consistency towards their cooking with a full team of chefs in the kitchen.

text: I&#39;m a bit of a snob when it comes to salads. I know what that sounds like, but it&#39;s true. Unfortunately, Cafe Melba doesn&#39;t cater to salad snobs. <br>I went to their new Mediapolis location on a Saturday. It wasn&#39;t crowded at all. The decor was fresh with an Australian vibe so quite pretty. However, I don&#39;t like the idea of ordering on iPads. There is always some confusion about whether an order was confirmed or not.<br>We ordered a Greek salad and sweet potato fries.<br>The salad too bad at all, perhaps the dressing was a little on the sweet side and there wasn&#39;t enough feta to counteract it. I was just disappointed with the choices -very limited. <br>On the other hand, the sweet potato fries came in a generous helping and were pretty tasty.<br>Overall, it was okay. Nothing special.

Porcini Mushroom Ravioli ($18 before GST) - 2.5 stars<br>Arrabbiata sauce, mushroom fricassee, cheese, and crushed hazelnuts<br>I was really disappointed with this dish because it sounded, and looked, so promising. Unfortunately, it tasted very much like American-Italian - in this case I suppose it&#39;d be Australian-Italian although I haven&#39;t had Italian food in Australia. It&#39;d probably be the equivalent of having pasta at Buca Di Beppo in California. I liked that the flavours were strong, but what I enjoyed about the dish ended there. It wasn&#39;t refined at all - it tasted heavy and cloying, and not in a good way the way comfort food can be. The ravioli skins were far too thick - imagine fat floury soggy dumpling wrappers - and were stuffed with cheese that was the wrong texture. The hazelnuts also ended up adding to the density of the dish as well, when I could&#39;ve used some herbs or greens to lighten and freshen the dish.<br><br>I&#39;m giving it three stars overall because I&#39;d try some of the other (probably non-pasta) dishes if I do go back. Ambience overall was cute, though I can see why another reviewer said it leaned toward ramshackle rather than rustic.

text: Dropped by on a quiet Tuesday afternoon and they had 1-for-1 promotion for pizza going on so we took full advantage of that. We got two half&amp;halfs - Chilli Crab and Pepperoni as well as Forest Mushroom and Parma Ham with Rocket. The pizzas are the thin crust variety which is perfect for when you&#39;re feeling peckish and not wanting to feel too full too quickly. I&#39;d really recommend the Chilli Crab, my Favorite among the lot we chose. Truffle fries were decent, as with the flat whites. Spotted their promotion on margaritas when I was in the Ladies midway through our meal and decided to get a carafe of Strawberry Margarita to ease into the evening. Frozen margarita was a good idea; tangy refreshing and very much welcomed on the palate after too much carbs between two girls. A word of caution for the slow sipper though, frozen beverages doesn&#39;t take too kindly to our harsh humid weather so it didn&#39;t take too long till we had a quarter of our carafe left with unattractive slush floating on lukewarm pink liquid - and we were seated indoors! Service was attentive and laid back and I wouldn&#39;t mind coming around again to try other items off their extensive menu

Cafe melba is located in the arts centre in kallang and they have a nice atmosphere and good food. I had the fish and chips which was not bad but nothing spectacular. The service staff was pretty responsive when I asked why my order took 45 minutes to arrive for a fish and chips. And they serve all the food together, including light snacks and starters. Kitchen size is too small to accommodate capacity. You are also unable to make a reservation in advance so come early especially on weekends.<br><br>Severely overrated

text: I&#39;ve been eagerly anticipating cafe melba&#39;s opening, and I was not disappointed. The coffee here is the best in the east side of town and is pretty near my place. Happiness!<br><br>I prefer ordering a piccolo as its stronger and more aromatic. The glasses for the latte are a little big, so the coffee gets quite weak and diluted. <br><br>I&#39;ve got to say, the service here is pretty good! The waitresses seemed a little hesitant and inexperienced, but yet were friendly and polite.<br><br>Also, when I asked about the latte tasting weak, the barista came over and recommended the piccolo. After that I noticed they only charged me for my first order. When I brought this up, they said the piccolo was on the house as I was unsatisfied with the latte. :)<br><br>The food here is of good quality! Ive tried the breakfast menu and was very satisfied with the eggs Benedict and big breakfast. Prices are a little steep but take advantage of the promotions on at the moment!<br><br>Weekday mains charged at 25% off, while on weekends, you get a free coffee when you order a brunch main before 4pm! Not sure when the promo ends but i was just there last week and it was still on!<br><br>The rib eye sandwich and chicken pesto sandwich were both lovely, nestled inside very yummy bread. However the buns for the Melba burger were a bit too doughy for me, though the ingredients inside we&#39;re fresh and the beef patty was cooked to a perfect medium rare juicy delight.<br><br>Great ambience and it&#39;s great for families as there&#39;s a large field out front, and I&#39;ve seen an inflatable bouncy castle on weekends!

text: This Australian bistro is a little gem hidden away in the Goodman Arts Centre (GAC) - it opens up to a green field, and combined with the high ceilings, glass panels and wooden decor give it a warm and inviting feeling where you feel you can sit and chill out the entire afternoon.<br><br>The menu is quite extensive - there&#39;s all-day breakfasts, along with your requisite starters, main courses, pizzas, sarnies (that&#39;s sandwiches for the non-aussies). My table had the Eggs Benedict with bacon or salmon (both yum), the portobello mushroom stack with a pasta side (also good), and a 12-inch personal pizza baked in their on-site wood fire kiln! My favourite bit would be desserts, which are not on the menu but displayed on the counter for you to pick. That day we had a lovely decadent chocolate cake that came with additional berries and cream... super rich and awesome! <br><br>For the thirsty, the caffeine addicts in my group pronounced the Cafe Melba cuppa good, and there&#39;s quite a long list of alcoholic drinks for you to sip and wind down to at the end of the day. All in all this bistro is a welcome addition to GAC, and makes a great option when one is a little too lazy or the weather is too insane to head out to the hawker centres nearby.<br><br>P/S: Cafe Melba has a special Neighbours card with discounts and perks for its fellow tenants at GAC... check with the staff to find out more!

I wanted to like the place because it does look promisingly chill. BUT the rude service put me off completely. For one, you do not ask your customers condescendingly what they are taking pictures for. I believe the actual words were &#39;What is that for?&#39; While i do not expect special privileges as a food reviewer, basic friendliness should apply to any customer. <br><br>Plus, the prices are pretty high and this is coming from someone who is willing to pay for brunch. Would i pay this price for food at a restaurant with mediocre ambience and terrible service? Hell no. You shouldn&#39;t either.

text: Had pretty high expectations going in, but unfortunately left feeling disappointed.<br><br>My brunch that I ordered felt like everything had been pre-cooked, including my poached eggs!! All of the plate was cold and the toast even tasted stale or perhaps it was because it was served cold.  Anyway it tasted terrible and I only got through 2 mouthfuls.  For $16, what a waste.<br><br>Also I ordered a babycino for my toddler.  It came out piping hot!! Way too hot for a kid to drink. And  it was actually a full size cup of heated milk??!! The babycinos that I normally receive are just the frothed milk/foam in a small cup..<br><br>I wouldn&#39;t go back unfortunately.

Food was good, but not great. Curried pumpkin soup was lovely -- great texture, lots of flavour. The naan bread it came with was okay, but didn&#39;t feel like &#34;proper&#34; naan. Truffle fries were delish -- we devoured them once they finally arrived... <br><br>... which leads me to why the 3 stars. Service is TERRIBLE. Terrible! Our server couldn&#39;t remember our orders. When they arrived, they came at widely different times. One got left off completely, and we had to wait another 20 minutes for it. It was a gong show. <br><br>Great wine list. We had lots of that. :)<br><br>The atmosphere is lovely -- being able to sit outside with fans, in front of a green space, and listen to music wafting in from nearby studios -- all really comfortable and relaxed.<br><br>I just wish the service wasn&#39;t so relaxed. It&#39;s the one thing that needs a kick in the pants.

text: I LOVE brunch! And I think I have found my go to brunch place! For starters, the atmosphere is super chill, perfect for a relaxing brunch. I ordered the eggs benedict and it was super yum! The eggs were free range eggs and they were perfectly poached with a runny yolk. The hollandaise was just how I liked it, accenting the eggs but not overwhemingly heavy. Last but not least, I tried the iced long black coffee and I think its one of the best iced coffees I&#39;ve had in Singapore. Defintely a place to revisit!

Service was attentive and laid back and I wouldn&#39;t mind coming around again to try other items off their extensive menu

A surprising find.<br><br>We were here on a Friday evening and it was surprisingly not crazy busy. Love the chill-out ambience. We were a big group and had no problem finding a table.<br><br>We only had pizza and truffle fries. Pizza were super thin crust and great for sharing. Think skinny pizza. But if you&#39;re a fan of neopolitan style like I am, then this is good but not great.<br><br>Great relaxing place to hang out with friends. They seem to do great brunches. So maybe I will be back to try that next time.

The brunch here is one of the better ones I&#39;ve had in Singapore for the longest time. <br><br>The ambience here is great and you can spot many other like minded individuals and families here having coffee and enjoying the food.<br><br>It&#39;s shaded from the sun, thanks to a large awning and there&#39;s ample smoking area. the fans provide just the right amount of breeze should you choose to sit outside, or you can sit in air-conditioned comfort inside and watch the chefs prepare your meal, thanks to an open kitchen concept.

Ambiance 100%<br><br>This is the immediate impression when we stepped in to this charming cafe right in the middle of no where one rainy afternoon after lunch. It is so idyllic and very quiet when we were there. We absolutely adored the decor! It felt like someone&#39;s open kitchen, filled with delicious things on the shelves.<br><br>We only tried their coffees since we already had lunch, but seems like I need to go back again to try the food. I&#39;m already sold on the ambiance, so the food won&#39;t be a big problem. Now, how to get there without driving is the challenge...
Nice place but the food is not good at all. Too bad for a place with such nice ambiance...

okayish australian brunch food hidden away in the goodman arts centre. this place has drawn mixed reviews since opening this year - and I&#39;m about to toss my own undecided judgement into the mix, just so you have as difficult a time as I did of deciding if it&#39;s worth visiting.<br><br>on second thought, perhaps that&#39;s not the best strategy for ingratiating myself into your favor. so here&#39;s it straight up: this place has great potential, but the food and service are in firm not-travel-worthy-but-I&#39;ll-have-it-if-it&#39;s-there territory. or more succinctly, meh.<br><br>I admit to wanting to come here for the longest time, despite those reviews: I had seen photos of the gorgeous space in design blogs, and there&#39;s just something incredibly appealing about good lighting for photography.<br><br>but the place doesn&#39;t look nearly this good (one day I will learn to stop trusting photos) in the daytime - and there was this slight ramshackle shabbiness about it, like they hadn&#39;t bothered to take care of what should be a well-curated space.<br><br>the pizzas fared the best that day, hands down. we had the chili crab, mushroom and a trifecta of meat products on the three little pigs. these were well-cooked in a wood-fired oven, with a crust that verged between cracker and thin-crust (nothing nearly as flavorful as the famed mozza - but good in its way), and the ingredients were suitably piled on.<br><br>the other dishes were less interesting: a burger was stacked high and pretty - and so were the pile of pancakes I ordered, which came in a healthy stack of four and drizzled with compote - and the full melba cooked breakfast was a generous plateful of food. but these suffered from bimboticism, having mastered the art of looking good without much substance.<br><br>so really, if you&#39;re here - head for the pizzas. the other stuff isn&#39;t bad, and actually perhaps on par with some hipsterish cafes, but I don&#39;t think it&#39;s worth traveling for. there is just this pervading sense of unfulfilled potential rather perpetuated also by the sheer nothing-outstanding-ness of both service and food. much better food elsewhere, really.

text: I&#39;ve been eagerly anticipating cafe melba&#39;s opening, and I was not disappointed. The coffee here is the best in the east side of town and is pretty near my place. Happiness!<br><br>I prefer ordering a piccolo as its stronger and more aromatic. The glasses for the latte are a little big, so the coffee gets quite weak and diluted. <br><br>I&#39;ve got to say, the service here is pretty good! The waitresses seemed a little hesitant and inexperienced, but yet were friendly and polite.<br><br>Also, when I asked about the latte tasting weak, the barista came over and recommended the piccolo. After that I noticed they only charged me for my first order. When I brought this up, they said the piccolo was on the house as I was unsatisfied with the latte. :)<br><br>The food here is of good quality! Ive tried the breakfast menu and was very satisfied with the eggs Benedict and big breakfast. Prices are a little steep but take advantage of the promotions on at the moment!<br><br>Weekday mains charged at 25% off, while on weekends, you get a free coffee when you order a brunch main before 4pm! Not sure when the promo ends but i was just there last week and it was still on!<br><br>The rib eye sandwich and chicken pesto sandwich were both lovely, nestled inside very yummy bread. However the buns for the Melba burger were a bit too doughy for me, though the ingredients inside we&#39;re fresh and the beef patty was cooked to a perfect medium rare juicy delight.<br><br>Great ambience and it&#39;s great for families as there&#39;s a large field out front, and I&#39;ve seen an inflatable bouncy castle on weekends!

text: I am currently in the midst of preparing to record an album at the Goodman arts centre and there aren&#39;t too many options for food in the centre. However i did manage to try a bit of food at Cafe Melba. I had what can be described as a type of pizza basket. It&#39;s clean slices of flour and dough with some meat, vegetable and cheese toppings on it. These pizzas are extremely thin and you may eat them with a choice of 3 sauces that are given to you - pesto, olive and chick peas sauce. The price range is a bit high. The quality of service is pretty good. And the ambience is the best part of the place. They have a very cool outdoor space seating area with wooden benches and tables. They also have pretty excellent coffee. It&#39;s a chillout sunday sort of a place for me.

text: This Australian bistro is a little gem hidden away in the Goodman Arts Centre (GAC) - it opens up to a green field, and combined with the high ceilings, glass panels and wooden decor give it a warm and inviting feeling where you feel you can sit and chill out the entire afternoon.<br><br>The menu is quite extensive - there&#39;s all-day breakfasts, along with your requisite starters, main courses, pizzas, sarnies (that&#39;s sandwiches for the non-aussies). My table had the Eggs Benedict with bacon or salmon (both yum), the portobello mushroom stack with a pasta side (also good), and a 12-inch personal pizza baked in their on-site wood fire kiln! My favourite bit would be desserts, which are not on the menu but displayed on the counter for you to pick. That day we had a lovely decadent chocolate cake that came with additional berries and cream... super rich and awesome! <br><br>For the thirsty, the caffeine addicts in my group pronounced the Cafe Melba cuppa good, and there&#39;s quite a long list of alcoholic drinks for you to sip and wind down to at the end of the day. All in all this bistro is a welcome addition to GAC, and makes a great option when one is a little too lazy or the weather is too insane to head out to the hawker centres nearby.<br><br>P/S: Cafe Melba has a special Neighbours card with discounts and perks for its fellow tenants at GAC... check with the staff to find out more!

text: So I bookmarked this place when I was last in Singapore four months ago and completely forgot to stop by. Luckily, I had another chance on my current trip and am so happy I finally did. <br><br>I&#39;ve never tried Putu Piring before today and to be honest, wasn&#39;t even all that sure what to expect. They&#39;re flat discs of coconut filled with a concoction of palm sugar then steamed and served with banana leaf. <br><br>They&#39;re soft, fluffy, slightly sweet and served warm. It was unlike anything I&#39;ve eaten before and was super delicious served alongside grated coconut. <br><br>They&#39;re made fresh on the spot so expect a small wait. Cost is so cheap, $2 for 5 (considered one serve). Totally worth giving a try and now one of my favorite places for cheap eats in Singapore.

text: Craving putu piring today and went to this local stall  inside of a food court. Such a pleasurable treat! Not too sweet and comes with very generous sprinkles of coconut.<br>My advice: GET AT LEAST TWO BOXES

Worth every penny I spent. First time went to this chain and it totally blown my mind. Those makciks definitely know how to make their putu piring to perfection even to the last bite. It was served in a brown wrapper piping hot. The putu piring was fluffy with a hint of sweetness with its palm sugar that melt in your mouth and a good portion of fresh grated coconut for you to eat with. Definitely my kind of dessert. I had to have another serving cause one wasn&#39;t enough. It&#39;s that good.

I guess it alright. I bookmark this place when travel to Singapore. Get to tried out the food stand here. The dessert are ok but the portion is small. It super hot in this eateries with a lot of fans on the ceiling but it doesn&#39;t help to relief the heat at all. I was sitting eating the foods but sweat like I just got out of the stream room.

There is always a line at all hours of the day, but unless you are stuck behind someone who is buying 100 packets, the line usually moves quite fast.<br><br>Everything is made upon order! You can&#39;t get anything fresher than that!

text: A hidden and lost ethnic pastry found within Mr Teh Tarik coffeeshop. This award-winning stall has and will definitely bring delight and childhood memories to many who have outlived the 60s to 80s. <br><br>Manned by a group of muslim ladies dressed in white and adorned with gold jewelry, one can&#39;t help but to be amused by the apparent contrast in perceived value between gold and the simple and inexpensive pastry. <br><br>Flour filled with gula melaka (sweet brown sugar) and accompanied with coconut shavings, this tasty treat is made on the spot and best served hot. <br><br>Get ready to join in the queue!

A nice piece of food heritage! I&#39;ve always being a fan of the &#34;Chinese&#34; tutu kueh but this brings me even greater satisfaction. The fluffy rice flour cake with a delicious gula melaka filing and sprinkled generously with fresh shredded coconut  and pandan leaves - a taste of heaven and still very reasonably price!

Fantastic! Freshly made on the spot. Traditional taste you can trust. The skin is soft and the filling generous and explosive. These are the real deals not those you see in Pasar Malam. Price is also very reasonable for the size and number of pieces you get. Downside is it is not very near the train station but still walkable. Singaporeans walk anywhere for good food right?

Ordered a chai tea and banana bread toast.  Toast was good, and tea made a few cups but I went there to work and realized after I got there that WiFi is only limited to 10 customers. That ruined my whole visit. Gosh--get with the modern day ages of having free WiFi...for all customers.

text: Bread &amp; Hearth is the new coffee / pastry shop in the heart of Katong V mall. I&#39;m so glad that this pastry shop filled the space once occupied by a dull furniture shop.<br><br>In my opinion the big draw of B&amp;H are the pastries. The Pain Au Chocolat, croissants, French apple turnovers are all pretty solid. I particularly love the buttery crust of the Pain Au Chocolat. It&#39;s especially good after being heated (on request).<br><br>Unfortunately, the selection at B&amp;H, particularly the main courses, is limited to just quiche and a few select sandwiches: Bacon egg mayo, tuna sandwich, etc. yikes, not good because I hate sandwiches.<br><br>Fortunately, this lack of selection is made up by a decent cup of Joe, in my case, a flat white. <br><br>Given this limited selection, I can only give this place three stars. Group Therapy located a few steps away still reigns supreme in my eyes. The coffee selection is far superior and offers a full selection of high quality mains.<br><br>Would I come back? Yes, but just for the $3 Pastries and free water. :-)

Located inside the relatively quiet Katong Village, this cafe offers a nice place to escape the mad rush and bustle of the nearby Joo Chiat and Katong area. The prices are not that wallet friendly especially when compared to nearby Group Therapy and Penny University Cafe. Still, they have a good selection of breads and good coffee. This place is definitely worth a try if you like the open concept cafes.

Two words: Turkish Eggs<br><br>It&#39;s hard to find Turkish food in the east, and though Penny University isn&#39;t a Turkish cafe by any means, they still make a mean Turkish Eggs!<br><br>There are usually 3-4 poached eggs hidden underneath a big bowl of greek yogurt. The harissa    (sauce? paste? oil?) adds some spice, and when you mix it all together with the toast they give you, it&#39;s so yum! Perfect if you&#39;re looking for a light meal. I just wish they could give more bread.<br><br>On a whim, I tried their peach iced tea (not on the menu) and though it was just canned peaches mixed with tea, it reminded me so much of being back in the southern US. Very refreshing.<br><br>They also have bottles of water that are free for all to access. Solid cafe!

text: Got to give it to them coffee was indeed above average.  However if i compared it to Tolido.....hmmm......<br><br>Now the kicker would be the food.  We were the first in the Cafe as it open. But boy....did it take long to get it on our table.  Taste wise it was alright.  Nothing to be wowed.  We had the Turkish egg and French Toast.  <br><br>Think they should spend a little time to clean up the Cafe.  Seeing spider web at the corner where the speakers are just don&#39;t give you the cozy feeling.  <br><br>So some reason the waitress were very conscious about their looks?  Flipping their hairs more often then focusing on their jobs?

text: Having visited Penny University for brunch, I decided to head back there to try their offerings for dinner!<br>As crowded as this looks, it&#39;s actually alot more empty compared to brunch! Alot of customers were getting cakes to go.<br>And this was the end results, hardly any cakes left, compared to what I saw earlier in the day.<br>Pretty much 50% of their menu were also sold out!<br><br>1. Earl Grey Tea Cake $5<br>I decided to quickly grab the last two slices of cake in the display and it was definitely worth my while. This was more like a pound cake that tasted like tea, with a hard sugary top coating. It was quite dense and great to share amongst two people.<br><br>2. Tropical Earl Grey $6<br>So moist and so good! Best cake ever!This is by far, my favourite cake. Do not like the layers of cream intimidate you, the cream isn&#39;t sweet, the cake is super moist and I even got two more slices to take home with me. Even with the cakes sitting in the fridge for 1-2 days, the cake remained moist! The tea flavour was present in every bite, and you can even smell it!<br><br>3. Peppermint Iced ChocolatePeppermint Iced Chocolate $5.50<br>This literally tasted like an &#34;After-Eight&#34; chocolate in a liquid form, the peppermint flavour wasn&#39;t too overpowering and the chocolate was very real and not too heaty. My friend and I enjoyed this so much!<br><br>4. Salmon Guacamole $9.50<br>I feel that for $9.50, this was worth every penny! There was so much salmon, I couldn&#39;t find enough bread to eat it with the salmon! The salmon tasted great and the bread was very crispy and toasty. It stayed crispy even after 10-15 minutes.<br><br>5. Affogato $7<br>One dose of Affogato at noon wasn&#39;t enough, I needed a second dose! Ice cream, coffee and gula melaka! It&#39;s heavenly, I will definitely be ordering this every single time I step into Penny University! The smell of the caffeine, just wakes you up!<br>Cakes and the Salmon Guacamole, a perfect dinner time treat, along with the Affogato, even though almost the entire kitchen was wiped out of food and we couldn&#39;t order anything else, I was still a very happy customer. <br><br>Great Cakes, Great Service and Great Coffee = Happy Customers like Me :)

text: Went there for after dinner boost. The bottled coffee is good and I tried their afogato with coconut ice cream paired with gula melaka. The coffee are fantastic. Earl Grey cheesecake is good, but I am not a big fans of cheese so I am not going to judge about it. However, I could tell by looking at the queue which mostly came for the cakes. We went there around 8.30pm and were told that the kitchen was already closed. Will go there again for coffee, the ambience is good for gathering.

text: What I would come here for - their amazing coffee, the mouthwatering cakes and tarts, their sourdough.<br><br>However, poached eggs are hit/miss. My poached eggs yesterday were cooked through, the yolks didn&#39;t ooze a single bit (making for a sad clarey!). <br><br>Still, good coffee is good coffee &amp; this place is a must try.

The event didn&#39;t start out that well with the Café still closed 15 minutes after the opening time, this was followed by a series of bad service and bad events.<br>I had expected better as the place is so highly rated.<br><br>Customer Service - 1 (it appears everyone there hates their job)<br>Ambience - 4 for using crazy furniture<br>Menu - 4 pretty standard and simple <br>Cost - 7 reasonable prices for Singapore<br>Coffee - 5 although two coffee&#39;s were delivered 5 mins apart <br>Food - 4 pretty plan items and eggs were not cooked properly <br><br>Dishes dumped on table, cutlery dumped on table. <br>Salt and Pepper shakers empty and I took some of all tables<br><br>All in all, I wont&#39; visit here again and the customer service factor alone is appalling

text: Ate here with my wife for brunch on a Sunday. Was pretty crowded but we didn&#39;t have to wait log to get a table. I had the eggs Benedict with smoked salmon and my wife had the English breakfast. Both dishes were pretty good. I would give a higher rating, but I feel like the food was average. The smoked salmon could have been a bit more flavorful, and the sausages in my wife&#39;s dish weren&#39;t anything special. I&#39;ll visit again sometime in the future because their espresso was good.

Aww Penny needs more love.<br><br>I&#39;m not sure why the ratings are so low. The food perhaps. Never tried the food here. But, THIS IS A COFFEE JOINT!<br><br>The cappuccino here was very competent. And in fact might be one of the best I&#39;ve had in Singapore. (For calibration, highland, dept of caffeine, refinery are others that rank on my list. CSHH not so much.)<br><br>Hooray for good coffee in the east!

text: Pretty much espresso based drinks for coffee and that is good. They are pretty specialized in their coffee selection but that is no turn off. The coffee is very nicely roasted and the coffee art is not bad (not that the art matters). Nice place to chill out and have a cuppa. Only thing is the space is not big so if you have a big group, it may be a problem. Other than that I&#39;d say the coffee is eorth the trip though it is slightly more on the pricey side.

text: Finally, a decent coffee joint in the east!<br><br>Mous has spent a lot of time getting stuff to be awesome, from the interior, to the coffee, and it is for both reasons that I now really like coming here. It doesn&#39;t hurt that he&#39;s a pretty cool guy to talk to as well.<br><br>He&#39;s spoken to local roasters Nylon Coffee as well, and they&#39;ve come on board as one of his suppliers, along with Oriole as well - supporting the locals is yet another reason to love this place.<br><br>Some stuff they&#39;ve got on the menu include sweet treats from Windowsill Pies, and today I had some pretty awesome turkish eggs too! Poached to perfection, and spiced with harissa, they were just begging to be mopped up with some tasty sourdough, which they cleverly included. <br><br>Heck, I loved that sourdough so dang much I ordered an extra portion with earl grey+fig jam, and finished that too.<br><br>Closing thoughts? <br><br>Cool joint, good coffee, a bike rack outside? HECK YES. Plus I love that he&#39;s got a little window right next to the espresso machine - perfect for takeaway coffees!

I even had brunch here once in spite of the usual coffee runs. The turkish eggs were good,  but boy is the sourdough and jam a rockstar!<br>Yay to east siders and lazy coffee days.

text: 1. cheese toasties <br>- poached eggs &amp; marmite <br>- the poach egges were perfect! the soughdough was awesome too! toasted to perfection. <br>- the cheese (not sure what type they used) were unfortunately it was way too salty for me :( <br><br>2. turkish eggs<br>- 2 poach eggs with whipped yogurt &amp; hot chili butter served with soughdough<br>- interesting dish but probably would not order again. it tasted like a spicy sour cream dip with poached eggs. interesting, edible but not my favorite thing. (even though the staff recommend this. hm.) maybe I am not a turkish breakfast person. just a simple american breakfast person. <br><br>3. cafe latte (7 ounce, double shot) <br>- strong! <br>- we initially asked for an extra shot because the staff told us 7 ounce will be &#34;diluted with milk&#34; and we wanted to start the day with a good coffee. I guess 2 shot was overkill? the kind of bitter only diehard coffee lovers can love. I am more a mainstream coffee person. <br><br>4. smore tart <br>- THE BEST!!! seriously, based on this item alone the place is worth a visit. the chocolate melts in your mouth! <br><br>Total: $27<br><br>Ambiance: nice vintage coffee joint :) great selection of magazines and books to read too (which is the perfect place to catchup on some reading on a lazy afternoon or during the late evenings when there aren&#39;t too many people. mornings tend to get crowded.) <br><br>Cons: <br>(which could have, but did not, make me give them 3 star. i believe in this place!!! it&#39;s definitely a raising start despite a few initial shortcomings... :) <br>- cash payment only. <br>- limited selection of brunch food (basically toast and eggs? both of which they do very well but I need something more substantial to start the day) I heard they are working on more dishes soon? can&#39;t wait to see what&#39;s installed. if it&#39;s anything like their perfect poached eggs and sourdough toast then it could potentially be a 5 star joint!

text: They are going to open next week (I believe Oct 15th, 2012), and today I walked by this place with a friend wanting to have a couple cups of coffee. Wanted to go for kopi, and saw this place opened, and noticed the two bicycles outside of this Penny University. So we went in to check it out.<br>The manager was very friendly, told us about the drinks and food that you offer. And he happily took our orders. The food were brought to us, and drinks followed a little bit later. The coffee drinks were great. The cupcakes were good. Since this is pre-openning, there is no charge. Tips were welcomed.<br><br>This is  a clean contemporary English decorated coffeehouse, attracts young people to hang up. <br>I believe this place opens early like 8:00am serving breakfast and closes at 9:00pm weekdays, and 10:00pm weekends.<br><br>I didn&#39;t check if they have free WIFI. I will ask them the next time I go there, it is walk distance to my house on Telok Kurau Road.

text: Discovered Penny Uni by chance when visiting my usual fried hokkien mee place - Geylang Lor 29 FHM, highly-recommended.<br><br>I love the decor here, especially the lighting. Not sure why they decided to waste some space on the &#34;porch&#34;, resulting in less space inside.<br><br>My first visit, I opted for a flat white in the bigger cup (forgot what the size is called), felt it was too thin, like I was drinking milk instead of coffee. Subsequently opted for the smaller cup and the mix was just nice.<br><br>They&#39;re reasonably near where I stay, although not the nearest coffee shop (that&#39;d be Loysel&#39;s Toy). But I&#39;ll definitely be back, as I&#39;m regularly in the area.<br><br>Parking can be quite limited especially during lunch and dinner hours, be prepared to scout/camp for lots.

text: cute place that&#39;s conveniently located in the &#39;hood. sometimes, u just want a cup of artisan coffee that doesn&#39;t require a train ride to the city. expect a wait on the weekends because it&#39;s pretty small and popular. there are a few seats outside but i prefer the ambiance inside. kind of looks like a library with the amount of books lining the shelves, and it&#39;s common to see artsy-types on their macbooks scattered throughout the place. <br><br>the coffee is alright. i&#39;ve had better, but it&#39;s decent. the offer all-day breakfast/brunch as well as sandwiches. i&#39;ve tried the turkey sandwich ($8), smoked chicken breast sandwich ($8) and turkish eggs ($8)... all good, but prefer the sandwiches. i think the desserts were even better. the grasshopper pie ($8 i think) is all sorts of yum if you like the mint + chocolate combo. also, they put orange slices in the water, which is a nice touch. <br><br>i mean, this isn&#39;t the place you&#39;d trek to if you don&#39;t live in the east, but for the easties, i&#39;m glad it exists.

Coffee - probably best in East Coast area.<br><br>Breakfast - Poached eggs on toast is good but isn&#39;t consistent. Flavours tend to drift towards the more savoury and sometimes this can be overpowering. Stay away from the scrambled eggs. It left the impression that we were eating something like oatmeal. Too much milk or butter or both.<br><br>Cakes - great selection of cakes. Goes well with their coffee.<br><br>In summary, if you live on the east coast and Tanjong Katong, this is probably one of the better coffee joints around.
Really nice ambience. The turkish eggs were okay, if not uniquely spectacular. Coffee was good.
