Sourdough toasts', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Sourdough toasts'}]
text: Far from granting academic degrees, least associated with research intensive facilities but this exclusive &#34;Institution&#34; - Penny University could make it to the highest coffee bar ranking in near future, if the sector ever have an achieving U15 or U21 group or alike. We are incapable of fore-speaking the future, the same goes to any economist and policy makers, hence we are in no way to crystal-ball their success, until perseverance turned fruitful.<br><br>Peculiar name it has. A coffee shop - deck out interestingly in modern lighting fixtures, serving you in its customized bar and counter table tops using recycled railroad ties (by THE RAIL LIFE CO.), with a raw finishing - polished cement flooring. I walked in and find myself a table seat, adjacent to the communal table. I wish I had a chance to the booth seat for a more enclosed space or that little couch corner for a homely feel, still I had a wonderful time just people watching in the open area. I returned to the counter for my orders. The menu clip on a wooden board is not long, making your choice is a lot more easier. Serving a small range of breakfast and a few selection of tea/coffee, the friendly young lady took the orders on her electronic portable tablet. While I am charmed by the catchy wood-cut coffee menu pinned on the wall, I find the old rustic-looking cash register very striking. I don&#39;t seem to spot any functioning one (no receipts-paperless &amp; they accept only Cash), how cool.<br><br>Seconds after I made payment, I find myself honing after some treats. The see-through display shelved some mouth-watering cakes, pies, tarts (supplied by other home-grown bakeries, by Fluff Bakery, Windowsillpies)  Surely I have missed the pop-up cookies store - my lovebites on their Salted caramel butter biscuits but still managed to try a piece of  that crunchy earl grey tea almond ones.<br><br>A bit nosy I confessed. I have to bring myself to ask why Penny University and not any others? Mouss - the barista &amp; owner, was busy brewing his delicate Brazilian blend, from Oriole Coffee &amp; Nylon Coffee Roaster. The guy who spent time learning from teachers at the London BRAT, find me hard to ignore as I was standing right in front of this World Barista champ weapon - La Marzocco. Speaking in a soft tone, he lyrically described the coffee beans used, the history behind the store name et cetra. And so, I came to know that Penny University is a term coiled in London during the 18-century - a coffeehouse where people of ALL levels are charged a penny to enter and have free access to coffee, company, latest news from reporters (&#34;runners&#34;), gossips, newspapers and bulletins. Many more coffee shops over the world then, were named &#34;Penny University&#34;. How interesting to know that&#39;s how social networking came about and its evolution, wasn&#39;t it?<br><br>I learn to appreciate how things fall into place, how each new start-up was conceptualized &amp; established. The process was lengthy but each baby steps were taken painstakingly with great passion. Likewise, the 7-ounce of simply coffee and water bond together brilliantly with careful brewing method - a clean &amp; creamy mouth-feel, less harsh. Honestly, I&#39;d prefer this to the one using Papa Palheta roast.<br><br>The breakfast toasties definitely amp up my lazy morning. I opted for a single toast instead of two but regretted as the marmite spreading the toast was marvelous. I used to make myself a slice at home but hardly these days, so when I saw them on the menu, I just know this it it! A deliberate amount is used so no worries about being overly-salted. The taste was made even more paramount when paired with cheese, supremely good! Then comes the poached eggs and a handful of rocket leaves salad to wrap up your morning - what an awakening!<br><br><a href="http://www.yelp.com.sg/biz_photos/penny-university-singapore?select=6z8a_uFhtyaYUh1KpH0bkg#3Vb5GfwUpBEDeYQrk0gtkg">yelp.com.sg/biz_photos/p…</a><br><br>If you find the marmite extract too acquiring, they offer sourdough toast with butter, marmalade &amp; fig condiments. I like the amount of heat that browned each round slices but I didn&#39;t seem to be able to locate its tangy taste. It needed a greater dose of levain. Of course, they have a few more options available.<br><br><a href="http://www.yelp.com.sg/biz_photos/penny-university-singapore?select=6z8a_uFhtyaYUh1KpH0bkg#6z8a_uFhtyaYUh1KpH0bkg">yelp.com.sg/biz_photos/p…</a><br><br>The Rock Cake makes a fabulous teatime treat. The Great Britain first had them during the WWII as one of the rationed food item. Quintessentially, a fruit cake with a jagged contour but minute-sized. Scone-alike, this fruit bun is somewhat moist and crumbly. The candied jumbo-sized dried cranberry &amp; raisin fruits complement the cake which has been baked universally less sweet. Accompanied by a cup of brew - unmistakable. Enjoying this classics of British food, I can now claim to be part of the Harry Potter&#39;s gang.<br><br>I know many dwellers in the east will make this their second home, sipping a minimal 3-ounce and engaged in a chitter-chatter.

text: Based on the pies offering here, it has earned another star! The grasshopper pie is awesome!

I enjoy their coffee especially the cold muddy coffee with milk. Queue is rather horrible during the weekends though and there&#39;s no where proper to wait. Prices are very attractive especially for food. Most cafes charge at least 1.5x. Food is nothing extraordinary but simple and satisfying. The pies and cakes are also very good. :)

The good:  After visiting a plethora of other cafes around Singapore, this one starts to stand out more and more (I almost bumped it to 3 stars).  They did well with the space, given that it&#39;s a mid height basic rectangle along a strip of stores - once you enter, it looks sleek.  I ordered the eggs, toast and tea...and everything was above average (especially the eggs).  They also have a help yourself water station and every time I got up to get something someone was there asking if I needed help (staff was super friendly, great job!).  The biggest plus was pricing, cheap compared to the rest.  That alone is almost worth a full star.    <br><br>The bad:  Not a lot of breakfast items and in my opinion it&#39;s sacrilegious to have a sandwich at brunch.  I don&#39;t know what it was, but there were two occasions where something (either in the jam or bread) got caught in my throat.  I was hacking up a lung trying to get it out.  Music was...spotty.  They were battling with the connection for my duration there.  It seems the coffee/espresso menu is on the board behind the counter and not on the menu itself.  Maybe I missed it, but it is a little confusing.  I actually wanted a latte, but didn&#39;t see it on the menu.  A big negative for me is the mismatched furniture.  Like 90% of the cafes in Singapore do this, and I&#39;m making a plea to please stop.  Invest in some quality items (that match), the table I was sitting at was all plywood and nails.  Felt like it was going to crash down at any moment.      <br><br>The ugly:  I know this place just opened, so I&#39;m hoping there will be improvements.  Time will tell, and I&#39;ll definitely be back to give it another try.  My heart is telling me they will improve, but my gut is saying they don&#39;t  need/want to.

Coffee is great, I love the portion sizings available but the food was not that great. Sourdough bread was too tough and seating is tight. Poached eggs are a hit or miss. Not consistent in flavour. Do go for the coffee. It really is better than alot of other cafes.
One of the only cafe in east that have good cuppa, but its not the best

I thought the coffee and desserts were average at best. Parking around the area isnt the easiest to find too.

I love Tarte, and used to go to the outlet at its original first floor location when it was literally a hole in the wall dessert counter. Now it&#39;s moved to a swanky cafe on the 2nd floor of the same building - and what&#39;s better is they serve their own teas and coffees, while also providing comfortable seating. It wasn&#39;t too crowded and I really want it to stay that way.<br><br>My favorite things here are the fruit tarts which differ by season based on whatever fruit is available. The tart crust is like a fantastic butter cookie (sables anyone?), the creme patissiere is light and delicious, and the fruit is always good quality. I am always literally sad when I&#39;m done eating one.<br><br>I also tried the quiche which was excellent - really awesome pastry, super light egg custard, and delicious fillings! I could have done away with the bacon, but the mushroom and onions in there were divine.<br><br>Surprisingly, the tea was of decent quality although I can&#39;t remember the name of it right now. And although it costs $8 a pot (when I was last there), it&#39;s good enough that you can steep the leaves again a couple of times so you get more bang for your buck.<br><br>I would take a star off for the price (which is pretty exorbitant but quite standard for pastry these days) but it&#39;s so good.. I couldn&#39;t bear to.

text: It took me a while before I discovered where it was located. Somehow I kept thinking it was inside Shaw Centre itself.<br><br>Tarte by Cheryl Koh is next to La nestled between La Strada and Caveau Bar along the stretch of Aoki and Bistro Du Vin. It faces Pacific Plaza. <br><br>Inside, the main focus will be the tarts. They look delicious and taste good. Maybe I am not a tart connoisseur but I do not see what is so outstanding about the tarts. They are nice but I do not think it deserves the $9 price tag on the small tart. <br><br>The only good thing is that you can actually have the tart to dine in at Caveau and have a coffee or tea with it.

text: The outlet was one of the many eateries under the Les Amis Group. It was a hole in the wall outlet, located at Shaw House, surrounded by other sister restaurants. Decorated in white, the place was more of a takeaway outlet. Those looking for a dine-in option, can bring the tarts next door to sister-concept Caveau Bar to quench their thirst with an aromatic cup of hot coffee while seated along the glass façade.<br><br>Roussillon White Peach ($9)<br>Seasonal French peach with vanilla cream<br>The white colored peach tart was only available till end of august. It would be replaced by dark peach after that.  The tart was simply melt in the mouth with a not too sweet taste, followed by a hint of coconut in the cream. The fruit was bursting with juice.<br><br>Cavaillon Melon ($11)<br>Melon panna cotta with French Melon<br>Similar to the peach tart, but topped with balls of the juicy sweet melon.<br><br>Mirabelle Plums ($9)<br>Baked plum tart with almond frangipane<br>The crust was a tab harder than the other 2 tarts. The sliced fruit on top of the tart had a kind of soft, caramelised top.<br><br>Overall the service was smooth and fast, as there was no crowd in front of me.  The tarts were yummy and delicious, without been too sweet.

text: New dessert place by Cheryl Koh. Lovely tarts for takeaway or dining in. There is also a wine bar (Caveau Bar) inside with both bar stool seating as well as normal chairs for about 50 people. <br><br>The inconspicuous and industrial looking entrance is easy to miss when driving past on the way to the car park. It is just next to the Caveau bar as they share the same seating area. <br><br>Those arriving by taxi at Shaw Centre can just alight at the taxi stand then walk upwards the slope. The establishment is just a few shops on the left. <br><br>A nice place for a post meal dessert or just hang out &amp; chill with some drinks.

text: These tarts were a gift from a good friend. They must be one of the best tarts I ever had in a while. I love the thin buttery crust and the light fillings in each one. The size was perfect for 1 without feeling overly heavy. Each tart had its distinct taste and the ingredients were fresh. Love them!

I used to come here all the time when I worked in the area for their Iced Honey Lime Tea. It&#39;s a super refreshing drink, and a great take on the usual lemon tea to mix things up a bit. The service here is efficient and there are 2 lines - one for placing an order, one for collecting your drink which gets people through their coffee lines quick. I wouldn&#39;t say this is the best tea you&#39;re ever going to have, but it&#39;s really affordable for the area and its longggg lines at breakfast and post-lunch attest to its popularity.<br><br>Would definitely recommend if you&#39;re in the area, but wouldn&#39;t go out of my way to come here.

text: really cheap and affordable drinks. The drinks comes cold or hot... i definitely suggest going for the cold drinks since its soooo hot in singapore. I tried teh hot ginger tea ... it came with milk (just an fyi in case you didnt know it like me). It has a little spice/kick to me. yummy

text: I really cannot find this shop. I had Sharetea in Bugis and always love it. My favorite bubble tea place! Order the black tea creama, their sea salt creama on top is very tasty, only Sharetea has this one!

If I had to choose between Koi and ShareTea, it&#39;d be a tough fight. I always thought my heart would stay with Koi&#39;s hazelnut milk tea but the day I strayed into the arms of happy family milk tea, I was classified a cheat. It&#39;s hard not to like it. ShareTea is a little on the sweeter side, so 30% sugar level is just bland enough for the pearls and other tea components to work their magic. The happy family is a happy mix of items - pearls, nata de coco and some smooth custardy thing that sinks right to the bottom. The outlet here is never too busy, which is a great thing for me. I&#39;ll usually pick up the happy family and rush up for diving class, and slurp loudly (and happily) on the yummy stuff.

text: Was brought to this place by chance by a friend who works around this area. <br><br>The shopfront is small and there is only 3 tables 6 chairs inside and 1 table with 4 chairs outside.<br><br>On the display cases, there are quite a number of choices of muffins. I was deciding between banana, blueberry or strawberry muffins and hence I picked the latter one. <br><br>They served coffee and tea as well. For the tea (Dilmah), they have varieties as well and I chose mango and strawberry flavored one.<br><br>The muffins are soft and the strawberry jam inside the as not too sweet either. I enjoyed each and every bite of it as the flavors lingered in the mouth for a long time. I&#39;m not really a muffin person but this is extremely good. They were baked to perfection and I also noticed they were in the newspaper articles for at least two times.<br><br>I can&#39;t comment on the price as my friend paid for my so called tea time. The two ladies who served us were friendly and let us think for awhile before purchasing our baked goods. Highly recommended ;)

Friendly staff. Everything baked fresh daily. End of day any unsold baked items are given to a church.<br><br>Had pork sandwich which was good and great for lunch. Had red velvet bundt cake which tastes great.<br><br>Will check out lemon cake next.

text: It should be either Le Bijou or Les Bijoux, but not Le Bijoux. The French may be half-baked, but the bread and cakes are freshly baked, and what&#39;s not sold at the end of the day is given to charities. Sandwiches are good, service is warm and friendly, and prices are very reasonable. But in these days of intense consumerist competition, you must be a real nostalgic to come to this non-aircon place with furniture that is more charming than aesthetic or comfortable. For the food is good, but not sufficiently unique. The owner&#39;s talent and dedication may be better served elsewhere, with bolder ambitions.

text: Tried out the blt. The bread is certainly nice by itself but it&#39;s a bit weird in a sandwich. The crust is chewy while the center is really soft my fingers can go through it holding the sandwich. It&#39;s not a stable construction and a bit hard to eat. The bacon was well down to the point that my brain was shaking when it was crunching in my mouth. There&#39;s also avocado which is a nice touch I think. It&#39;s just not what it could be imo. <br>On the espresso, it&#39;s pretty bad. I&#39;ll have to try the desserts some other time but to go because I like my desserts with a decent coffee.

So little cream cheese that you might as well do without it!', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'So little cream cheese that you might as well do without it!'}]
text: Very disappointed!  We ordered 1 supreme Vegetarian, 1 Smoked Salmon, 2 Cranberry Scones, coffee and tea. In the description for both sandwiches, they included cream cheese. The problem is they just lightly touched the tip of the knife on the bread with cream cheese. When we asked for more cream cheese, they brought a saucer with cream cheese as much as the tip of a finger - it was more like an insult than more cream cheese. My wife asked for more cream cheese and offered to pay for it, and we did. When you charge $19+ for a sandwich and you show much stinginess with all ingredients (not just cream cheese but all ingredients) and additionally, you don&#39;t respect your customers, it doesn&#39;t make for a great experience for them, does it?<br><br>Cranberry scones came warm with  butter and jam. They were ok but don&#39;t go out of your way for it. Earl grey tea was not aromatic. They don&#39;t serve decaf coffee.<br><br>Ambiance is nothing special. And service was disappointing as noted.<br><br>Breads were baked fresh. So, if you want to go there and pick up bread, it is ok. I will not go back for food.<br><br>I will add a picture of cream cheese on the bread sandwich for your reference.

text: Update: since my last review I&#39;ve been back here 4-5 more times.<br><br>Cranberry scones were as good as everyone made it out to be. Worth trying for $2.80<br><br>Smoked salmon sandwich is delicious!<br><br>Their new Pulled pork sandwich could be better, but still decent. The ciabatta was delish. Sauce was a bit too sweet for my liking.<br><br>In terms of sandwiches, my favorite is still BLT with extra hard-boiled egg.<br><br>Had their lunch set today and the soup du jour was disappointing. It was homemade pumpkin soup alright, but I suspect all they did was puree the pumpkin and nothing more. There was not much taste to this soup at all...<br><br>Still my favorite brunch place in the area!

text: I have a hard time deciding. Simply too many choices with a limited gastro-capacity. How much can you stomach each day? After all, I am no Adam Richman of Man vs Food who is all out to conquer the most compelling food that keeps populating without any sign of slowing down. The food scene is getting more electrifying and when it becomes explosive, it will be unimaginable. Positively yet, I enjoy the random pick.<br><br>For 3 years now, it seems to me that there are new breakfast parlors &amp; coffee joints opening every month. All-day-breakfast and coffee tasting (surpassing wine tasting these days) becomes suddenly fashionable. Many are made to rediscover the art of coffee drinking and cultivate the new societal norm of brunching. No one could be spared.<br><br>While some are untroubled by queues, others like myself, gets irk by it. Those that comes with a long line, therefore needs either entice me with real stuff or delude me with some marketing gimmicks which I may fall trap at times. With a bit of luck, one could still find authentic flavourful eatery without having to join the crowd in the bustling street of Orchard - but allow me to echo; &#34;that&#39;s when you are in luck.&#34; Betting at it, I seek out the less congested spot in downtown.         <br><br>Nestling along a quieter lane at Killiney road, this 5 year old deli-bakery shop is a stone away from the signature kaya toast at Killiney Kopitiam. I remembered savouring the optional coconutty kaya jam &amp; that slightly salted slab of butter that cuddle 2 slices of warm French toast and washed down with a cup of old-fashion brewed coffee. And today, I met with Freshly Baked by Le Bijoux for a similar nostalgia experience - no queue absolutely.<br><br>I enjoyed its unpretentious makeup with sturdy wooden dining furnitures, withholding some traditional elements. The well-ventilated shophouse is most welcoming. But more inviting is the lady behind the baking countertop who was once the executive pastry chef at Saint Pierre who struck out on her 5 years ago. This baker - Audrey has tempt patrons with her homemade sweet cinnamon loaf, butter cake, walnut raisin bread. Some make their way there for the affordable breakfast sets (nett prices). I hear them, and so I turn up.<br><br>I was greeted with a firm but friendly tone, the moment I stepped into the shop. The place was empty at 2pm on a Saturday. I quickly pick up the menu placed in an acrylic holder against the wall. Without delay, I went up to the payment counter to make my order and pay for them. The cake choices in the glass shelving were narrow - forget about having any fanciful slices, Audrey bakes traditional confections.<br><br>The burger bap (Brunch B - S$9.50) arrived with a loud bang. The sizeable bun came with an authentic softness with an easy to chew texture and airy interior, nothing more. The salt-cured beef slices didn&#39;t taste too briny but a little too greasy. Instead of assembling them into a à la mode burger, I forked the sunny side-up and get excited watching the yolk exploding in all direction atop the bap. The result was a moist and eggy bread combo. Unimpressed, the baked bean stood motionless on the plate. Though it didn&#39;t wow me greatly, I appreciate the homely bread offered.<br><br>2 slices of thick wholemeal bread helped fix one&#39;s hunger pangs. I feel the crust crackling apart as it revealed large to medium air pockets in the crumbs. I figured that I tasted too many well-baked European breads these days that the ones I had here failed to surprise me further. The set (Brunch A - S$10.90) came with some crisp bacon strips and a pool of moist but bland scrambled egg. The stalk of romaine looked out of place on the plate; too little to call it salad, too bulky on its own - I don&#39;t understand. Still, I am pleased by the customer-oriented gesture here. I feel good not for the cappuccino but the biding good-bye when you make your exit to the door.<br><br>Next time if you are walking down the Killiney lane with a sudden crave for a homemade loaf, Freshly Baked could be your antidote. Unless you are too starved to walk, the brunch could be your saviour. But I will not succumb to any hunger beast to eat my fill, I wouldn&#39;t mind dragging my feet a few inches away. <br><br>With bountiful options, I feel indebted to EDB and have to praise them for shaping Singapore&#39;s economy which includes the food industry, even if they are not the only invisible hand behind it.

text: Friendly hellos greet you as you walk into the shophouse that is filled with baked goodies!<br><br>Like all sweet tooth people I immediately dive for that last crunchy salted caramel tart there was at the counter and the cranberry scone. I literally went to chocolate tart and scone heaven and back.<br><br>A place to just chill with your favourite baked treat - be it a bread, sandwich, tart, cake, scone or macaroon. This place has it all. A good place for a quick sweet treat!

The 5 star is only for the jam! It&#39;s homemade and it&#39;s delicious. Just the perfect level of sweetness and they use real berries hence the fragrance. I would highly recommend the owner to start selling them in jars!<br><br>It&#39;s a shame that I was too full to try their scones, cakes and bread. I would definitely go back very soon.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/hCdO-eJhofsONdE0fT4VuQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/freshly-baked-by-le-bijoux-singapore?reviewid=zE7bOEzNgfXCPShsuMJv-A&select=hCdO-eJhofsONdE0fT4VuQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Freshly Baked by Le Bijoux - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: At the beginning of Killiney Road, opposite the towering Singtel building, is Freshly Baked by Le Bijoux evidently patronized by locals and expatriates alike. This quaint bakery-café has a French-style kopitiam set up, along with the aromatic whiffs of freshly baked bread, cakes and pastries from the kitchen allows customers to immediately find comfort in. This place is best for late morning brunches or afternoon tea. Attracting throngs of office folk, many grab lunch on the go, opting for the gourmet sandwiches and gourmet cakes. <br><br>Alongside the display counter loaded with freshly baked bread, cakes and cookies, is chirpy and welcoming staff, effectively catching the attention of bystanders. Items here are also great for value, as you get great satisfaction at such low prices. Macarons are reasonably priced at $1.50 each and muffins at $1.80 each. You will be immensely surprised to find that all their baked produce have a special homemade flavor that can be difficult to find in commercial cafes out there. I will definitely make this bakery-café a regular eating haunt.

The four star rating is mostly for their cranberry scones. One huge one for $2.80! A steal. Mom and I popped by after lunch and were pondering what bread/cake to get.. and bing! Mom&#39;s brainwave - cranberry scone. I guess the fact that the family before us also ordered it confirmed that it was a good idea. Anyway, it didn&#39;t taste super rich (although, I have no idea about the actual butter content, haha) and was slightly spongey, chockful of cranberries, nice touch of caramelized sugar in the middle of the top, and good crust! <br><br>One of my favourite scones in Singapore so far :) Although granted, I haven&#39;t had that many.. Next to try will be the huge ones from Gastronomia Da Paolo. <br><br>Bf and I tried their chocolate salted caramel tart previously, that was so-so though. I was expecting a crispier/crunchier tart base but this one was soft. I like my buttery tart bases so this one didn&#39;t quite cut it. The crunchy choc balls on top added nice texture though! Also, bf&#39;s complaint was that there wasn&#39;t v much salted caramel (which is true). It was very rich and gooey with choc/caramel filling though.

Freshly Baked does a good quality brunch at a central but yet low key location and at a ridiculously reasonable price. The Bakery Cafe has been opened since late 2007 and it offers a variety of Artisan Breads, cakes and pastries. <br><br>What is really good here is their breads. They are so addictive; they were all i could think about after dining here the first time. I just wanna eat bread all my life if they were this good.<br><br>Sandwiches, breads and cakes are available all day (till they run out and they do run out fast). There are 3 Brunch Sets (S$10.90-12.90).  but i&#39;m not sure what time they end. The most popular order is the deli corned beef from Huber&#39;s Butchery paired with baked beans, a fried egg and burger bag bread. While i was there, i tried the Fresh deli Salami served with Emmental cheese, scrambled eggs and olive oil bread (S$12.90).<br><br>Even though the scrambled egg was more like omelette (and a little bland), the bread was faultless. It&#39;s kinda like an English muffin with the slightly rough exterior but it&#39;s moist and dense on the inside and yet it still maintains the slightly fluffiness. I suppose the salami is also from Huber&#39;s. I tried stuffing all the ingredients into the bun but failed because there&#39;s too much of everything (not complaining)!<br><br>Great place for brunch or a snack.

The desserts and pastry here are sooooooooooo good! I haven&#39;t had the opportunity to sit in here for brunch in the restaurant portion yet, but I did pop by the bakery section in the front to buy some stuff.<br><br>Chocolate Bread:<br>I saw a woman carrying 3 loaves of the chocolate loaf to the counter and wondered how good it was exactly. I chose to pass the bread at that moment because I was already getting too many other things, but luck of all luck I finally got to taste it later on and my god this is HEAVENLY. It&#39;s chocolatey, but not too rich and has a fantastic cake like texture - you could eat this all day and not get sick of it! highly recommended!<br><br>Giant Cookie:<br>it&#39;s face size seriously, nice if you like your cookies crunchy and not so rich. So so for me, I like the pepperidge farm type of soft baked cookies better.<br><br>Crunchy Chocolate Salted Caramel Tart:<br>The name is a mouthful, but thankfully the tart is not that small! It&#39;s a sinfully lovely combination of gooey chocolate with salted caramel and topped off with crunchy chocolate balls in a tart shell. Verdict? AWESOME - for the chocolate lovers!

Daily Bread is a bakery / café that sells fresh bread to-go as well as pastries and delicious sandwiches. It&#39;s located along Killiney Road and is ideal for grabbing a quick bite on Sunday mornings. Apart from sandwiches it also has brunch options such as French toast and American breakfast.<br><br>I usually come here for their sandwiches!<br><br>The sandwiches are a much healthier option than the more oily local cuisine on offer at Killiney Kopitiam (which is two stores down the road). My personal favourite, the Veggie Supreme, consists of arugula, avocado and a cheese spread sandwiched between hearty slices of multi-grain bread.<br><br>I top it off with some black coffee (tastes average) or an unsweetened iced tea on slightly hotter days. In total a meal including a drink costs from $10-$12.      <br>It can get more crowded when the lunch crowd comes, but if you avoid going between 12-2pm on weekdays, it&#39;s quite empty.

text: It&#39;s with super mixed feelings that I am writing this review. On the one hand, I am elated that Marine Cove has reopened after being closed for more than 4 years. On the other hand, this is NOT the same Marine Cove that we know so well. <br><br>Take a look at this website to see how Marine Cove used to look like when it first opened more than 30 years ago in 1982. <a href="/redir?url=https%3A%2F%2Fremembersingapore.org%2F2012%2F03%2F15%2Fmemories-at-marine-cove-mcdonalds%2F&amp;s=ed317c262951d003c2bcf459936a9c1fb25e38ea3ee9cd0d61a86708bbd744ee" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">remembersingapore.org/20…</a> <br><br>I feel super nostalgic and also quite sad looking at the old pictures from this blog. One of my friends summed it up very well: the new Marine Cove is just NOT the old Marine Cove. Sadly, it is true ; (<br><br>My friends and I used to hang out at Marine Cove area very often during our teenage years. The catchphrase then was &#34;meet at McD&#39;s&#34;. We would meet at McD&#39;s, then head out to the beach for our activities - be it BBQing, Cycling, Roller-blading, Strolling along the beach, Watching the sunset, Jogging, Dancing on the beach at night! (YES we did the dancing part lol!), Camping in the Tents and much much more. #sweetmemories<br><br>However, after all the musings and &#34;wiping away the tears&#34; (being drama mama here), I am very happy that Marine Cove has reopened at the exact spot where its predecessor used to be. That&#39;s because the authorities seemed to have other non-F&amp;B related plans for the location when they demolished the original Marine Cove.<br><br>What you can find at the new Marine Cove (opened on 28 June 2016):<br><br>(1) McDonald&#39;s -- Anchor tenant for sure! <br>The business there has been just crazy since it opened on 2 July 2016. I thought of getting a dessert or fillet-o-fish last night (3rd day of operation), but the queues were pretty long, so I will go again another day.<br><br>(2) Coffee Bean &amp; Tea Leaf Cafe - The biggest CBTL in SG to-date<br><br>(3) Other eateries: Babalicious (Local Peranakan Food), Hill Street Coffee Shop (Local Food - local coffee &amp; kaya breads), My Briyani House (Local Malay Food)<br><br>What I like about the new Marine Cove: It is NEW!! It is very functional, with all the eateries housed inside a big squarish building. <br><br>I think what I LOVE most about the new Marine Cove is the very big and interesting 3500sqm playground for the kids! I am fully intending to visit the park often in the days to come, observing how the kids enjoy themselves and maybe take a picture or two #ilovetakingpicsoftoddlerschildren <br><br>Take a visit to Marine Cove - for those of you who remember the old Marine Cove, and the ones who have never been to its well-loved predecessor, I believe both groups would have a good time here. A big incentive to attract you to Marine Cove? Have a nice meal or cuppa, and then head out to the beach thereafter. <br><br>Welcome back Marine Cove! #youhavebeenmissed

Why am I giving this place 5 stars? While many may say that the toast or the eggs are not very special or that the food is expensive but one of the biggest draws for me is the convenience of the drinks to go. They are pretty efficient with the dual counters and dual queue system which enables the crazy, hungry and thirsty crowd at Raffles Place to get their drinks to go.<br><br>The other big plus for me is that the cashier has somehow identified me as a regular and remember what my usual order is (I tend to buy large amounts of honey lemon drinks to go) and she is ever cheerful and helpful, sometimes giving me good recommendation for new drinks I&#39;d like to try.<br><br>The honey lemon here comes with 2 slices of lemon and a very generous amount of honey to sweeten things up. I wouldn&#39;t say they use great honey but when you do try to press the lemons farther before drinking, the sourness from the lemon slices and the sweetness from the honey comes to a nice balance.<br><br>As a few others pointed out, if price is an issue, do go to Golden Shoe for better priced drinks and food. But the service here plus the convenience and pretty good speed of fulfilling their orders would keep the crowds coming.<br><br>As a side note, they do have a main competitor Teahut which also makes excellent honey lemon, but they tend to be a little generous with their honey and lemons.

I will admit I&#39;m not a huge connoisseur of kaya toast and so I can&#39;t really say if Fun Toast has better or worse quality kaya than Ya Kun, Toast Box, or elsewhere.  All I know is that my mom and I were starving for breakfast and it was too hot to walk anywhere, so we stopped into the closest mall next to our hotel (actually the outlet at Liang Court, which doesn&#39;t have a yelp listing for Fun Toast) and we were thoroughly satisfied with our meal.  <br><br>Set meal of two half boiled eggs, kaya toast, and whichever drink we wanted, of which they had a huge number of choices.  Fun choices!  I had teh c peng with grass jelly, while my mom had cold barley with lemon and ginger.  They also had otah otah, which was a nice breakfast treat!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/qHk2vIY60C47CPJfT-h61A/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/fun-toast-singapore?reviewid=KJeasp3XgtCsME5LcUVjFw&select=qHk2vIY60C47CPJfT-h61A', 'altText': 'Photo of Fun Toast - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: We got the set which included a coffee, toast and two eggs for less than $5. We also got their coconut rice wrapped in a banana leaf.<br><br>If you want to get the same food for half the price, go to a hawker spot. If not, enjoy this chain haha. It&#39;s the same taste wise and in a nice, air conditioned mall!
They are very good for breakfast. Also love the friendly staff who always remember what I order.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/ZkfRZ_HE8ZYLwIWkKx764g/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/fun-toast-singapore?reviewid=YrxudlIT5Aa43-h8G8_Khg&select=ZkfRZ_HE8ZYLwIWkKx764g', 'altText': 'Photo of Fun Toast - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: The long lines that form past this little place every morning is testament to the quality of local breakfasts that they offer.  I love this place because regardless of whether there&#39;s a long line, or if I&#39;m the only one being served, the quality of tea/coffee that they prepare is consistent.  <br>In the mornings, they have a take away counter for hot drinks and tuna / egg / sardine sandwiches - I&#39;ve never had to wait more than 5 mins, they really are efficient, and the Aunty that serves at that counter is amazing!! She really keeps the line moving fast, and manages to be friendly and cheerful all at the same time.<br><br>If you would like to sit for breakfast, or want to get hot food such as mee siam, curry chicken etc, you can queue at the line inside the cafe. In fact, sometimes the line inside moves faster than the takeaway line outside :P<br><br>Great place to grab breakfast in the morning - I&#39;m a fan!

text: Fast service even during peak hours. Staff are attentive and get orders right all the time. Food is made fresh and yummy

This place does magical things with vegetables.<br><br>I like salads but I&#39;m not really a *salad person* but everything I had was just really freaking good.<br><br>Like with one bite you suddenly realize how a pasta salad should be prepared and everyone else has just got it wrong, or you eat a avocado cucumber slaw that&#39;s so light and refreshing that you seriously wonder how this isn&#39;t a staple for all humankind.<br><br>I like this place a lot. <br><br>Playlist and garden feels also A+.<br><br>Slight minus for the small space.

Rating is for their coffee &amp; ambience. Ordered a flat white - rich and smooth, definitely one of the better ones I&#39;ve tasted in Singapore &amp; Bangkok. Small but really laid-back place to hang out in the afternoon. With al fresco (aka smoking) area. Don&#39;t miss out exploring Gillman Barracks while you&#39;re at it <br><br>Didn&#39;t get to try their food but heard the Quinoa Goreng is fab, so will definitely be back to try that ;)

The Red Baron&#39;s a small cafe tucked away in a corner of Gillman Barracks. Half the menu was marked off, which left us with breakfast choices for lunch. Would have preferred the Yoghurty Buckwheat Pancakes without the Greek yoghurt, but the meal was satisfactory.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/-8PKrFDLW4-pikGh-N3GBQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/little-wimbly-lu-singapore?reviewid=LC5lCf11T9kXSojhNWxagw&select=-8PKrFDLW4-pikGh-N3GBQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Little Wimbly Lu - Singapore, Singapore. Waffles with ice cream and a latte on a rainy Monday afternoon', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Waffles with ice cream and a latte on a rainy Monday afternoon'}]
text: This is one quaint cafe tucked in the middle of Serangoon Gardens. My friend, who lives nearby, often comes here for his coffee fix. Really limited seating and even slightly cramped but I guess it adds to the charm of the place.<br><br>We shared the waffles with a scoop of cheesecake ice cream and my friend has a latte as well. The waffles were slightly too small for my liking though their soft texture is a matter of personal preference. The latte was nothing to shout about but it isn&#39;t terrible either.<br><br>The place is a nice option for a cafe chillout for folks around the area.

text: Little Wimbly Lu is the sister store of Wimbly Lu. This dessert place is a stone&#39;s throw away from the Chomp Chomp Food Centre and has limited seating (both indoor and outdoor). It was packed on a Monday night.<br><br>I got the waffle with salted caramel ice cream. I had the ice cream served in a separate cup. The waffle came in 2 pieces of a quadrant. The waffle texture was good. Crispy on the outside and soft in the inside. It came with a small cup of maple syrup which gave the waffle most of its taste. Without it, the waffle was pretty bland. The ice cream I got was ok - too buttery for my liking. All in all, it was an ok after dinner experience.

Seats are pretty limited in the indoor. Two tall long tables, three small round tables and that&#39;s it. Came here on a Friday night and I&#39;m not surprised that it is full house inside. Luckily my friends and I didn&#39;t have to wait long for seats. <br><br>So we heard about their waffles and had it with two scoops of ice cream. Waffles are two quadrants. It was slightly overdone on the color but still not bad. The ice cream was okay. They got my order wrong but lazy me didn&#39;t change it. Thought their dark chocolate ice cream is better than Speculoos flavour which is too sweet for me. <br><br>Next up was Earl Grey mousse cake. It was way too sweet to my liking. Each time I reach for the cake, I could only slice a thin small piece with my fork. Thank god this cake is shared. <br><br>They do serve mains. But I don&#39;t think I will be back anytime soon to try other stuffs.

text: Ya Kun Kaya Toast is an extremely popular chain specializing in all things, Toast! <br><br>This fast food joint is known for its iconic breakfast set- - Kaya Toast and Kopi. <br><br>After a quick scan of the menu, we opted for their Kaya Toast set which came with a hot Kopi (subbed for an iced Kopi) and Rendang Chicken. <br><br>KAYA TOAST <br>While the Kaya jam itself was decent, the thin overly-toasted breads were dry and unpleasant. Sure, it&#39;s made extra crispy to be eaten with the runny egg (which I am not keen on) however, a meal should be pleasing as a combo as well as on its own. Needless to say, this was unpalatable. <br><br>RENDANG CHICKEN<br>The concept of stuffing this aromatic and spicy chicken into a pocket of toasted bread was genius and a convenient way to eat this dish however, the flavor of the chicken was not tasty. The curry flavor was subpar making this an underwhelming meal. <br><br>KOPI<br>It leaned more towards a deep bitterness flavor lacking the perfect blend of the sweetened condensed milk. <br><br>While the history of this place is captivating, the food is unimpressive. <br><br>Not a place I&#39;d recommend for a genuine and delicious breakfast spot.

text: Great place to get breakfast or brunch if you:<br><br>1. Can&#39;t eat curry noddles soup for breakfast <br>2. Don&#39;t have cash &amp; only has a credit card ( no-sir-charge)<br>3. Jog by the Marina Bay area<br>4. Can&#39;t decide to eat Chinese or Western Breakfast <br>5. Don&#39;t want to spend $25 for Hotel breakfast <br>6. Wanna see some cool neighborhood <br>7. Wanna go shopping afterward<br>8. Need protein, but can&#39;t find Protein shake<br>9. Only want to spend less than $5 for breakfast <br>10. Want freshly squeezed orange juice (not guarantee)<br><br>So if you Google the most famous/best place/most common place to eat breakfast, YaKun Kaya Toast is probably one of those.<br><br>I particularly like this one because there are many other breakfast restaurants close by and has a freshly-squeezed OJ machine across the street for $2.<br><br>I ordered Set F, Kaya Toast Peanut Butter with Two running eggs, and one milk tea. (Tea is very sweet). This is an alternative if you can&#39;t find protein shake right after your jogging.<br><br>Plus Yakun took credit card and had many hot or cold coffee and tea options. <br><br>Overall, quick, fast, and simple breakfast choices with multiple locations.

great european brunch food at this cosy - and very classy - restaurant hidden away in the singapore national museum. I popped by this place for a brunch with friends and the food is rather innovative, and service very prompt - the menu sounds rather typical, with eggs, french toast and common european fare, but it&#39;s the small details and their interpretation of these dishes that made it such a good meal. it&#39;s become one of my current favorites.<br><br>the place is truly gorgeous, with high ceilings and luxurious finishings. it&#39;s very peaceful, and that bar area at the back looks awfully welcoming. prices were reasonable, portions much larger than you&#39;d expect - and next time I&#39;ll stick to my egg en cocotte, and possibly get a slice of one of those lovely cakes on display.

Wagyu beef rump and truffle', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Wagyu beef rump and truffle'}]
text: Had heard from friends the set lunch is good value for money so thought we&#39;d celebrate a friend&#39;s birthday there, particularly a place with such a lovely ambience.<br><br>Had the wagyu beef rump with truffle, not bad but not as tender as the one at 7ADAM. But those who prefer their beef with a bit more bite would prolly prefer this. Also had the snowball and white peach sorbet which was quite interesting with a very pretty presentation. <br><br>Overall OK but didn&#39;t think it was worth the money.

Made a reservation one day for weekday lunch, but I needn&#39;t have bothered. The place was empty save for another table of two. The decor of Novus is rather posh; veneered fixtures, high ceilings, expensive looking lights and classy mirrors. Service is attentive, and you can tell these folks take pride in their attention to detail. <br><br>The menu is extensive, and I went all out on foie gras anglaise, duck rillet, crispy pork belly, mud crab mac &amp; cheese, a side of asparagus and a couple of bloody marys. The choices are mostly good, but hardly memorable. The mac &amp; cheese didn&#39;t quite hit the spot, and the bloody marys were on the anaemic side. The star of the show had to be the foie gras. It&#39;s different from the usual slab one finds in most restaurant. Instead, it comes in a glass receptacle, all smooth and silky custard with generous slivers of duck confit. The truffle adds a heady dash, and it was the first dish to be inhaled. <br><br>Good for lingering over a drink after a comprehensive day at the museum, though you&#39;d need deep pockets for lunch or dinner.

text: The first time I so-called tried Naomi was when Mel Y. gave me a piece of the green tea with azuki rolls during one of our meetups.<br><br>After wondering where my friend and I should go for lunch, we decided to settle somewhere near to Nex as I decided not to try food chains that are available at other areas.<br><br>Tried the Mango latte. Wasn&#39;t too impressed as it is like a scoop of pureed mango with mango bits and the ice was too much. The latte was milky. Similar to Thai Milk Tea somehow.<br><br>For the food, we decided to order the Tuna Mayo Waffles and Turkey and Ham wrap. Wanted to try the Thai chicken wrap but unfortunately was sold out. <br><br>The portions of salad on the side is extremely generous. For the Tuna Mayo waffles, the mayo was a little too much which made the waffle to be soggy faster. The mayonnaise was given in a generous portion but not the tuna. But.. I love the waffles. Crispy on the top and bottom. <br><br>The wrap had generous portion of meat. I liked the way they toasted the wrap which made some parts crispy. They also sliced it in two so it is much easier to share or hold. The meat was juicy too which made some parts of the wrap to be tender. Was pretty satisfied by this dish.<br><br>My friend and I were the first ones to arrive and crowds started crawling in after 3pm on a Sunday for cakes. This place can only accommodate smaller groups. The rolls are definitely good. :)

text: I&#39;m in love with their swiss rolls from $1.20-$1.40 for the swiss rolls.. they&#39;re fresh and not dry. It was strange that the first time I tried their matcha swiss roll, it tasted dry. But since then, I&#39;ve tried the blackforrest, mango peach and durian swiss rolls, all were moist. The sweetness of the fresh cream was perfect, the texture was smooth and creamy. I loved it, and I also like that they make great tea time snacks for the colleagues. I also noticed new flavours like yam and black sesame which are uncommon for swiss rolls. I can&#39;t wait to try them all!

The only thing it has going for it is the price. No hipster cafes pricing here.<br><br>It is very affordable and the place is bright. <br><br>Swiss rolls seemed to be the main focus and at $1.20 per roll ($1.40 for durian and other premium rolls), it is about the same as Polar Cafe which has cornered the market. <br><br>The rainbow cake looks pretty and is under $7, with other cakes at $4 each. <br><br>Throw in coffee or tea (local kopi and teh style) at $1.20 per cup, it has potential to attract the older folks and those not that into the fancy barista made lattes and espresso.<br><br>Savory items include waffle and pies. They also have the kaya toast and soft boiled eggs with coffee/tea set.<br><br>It is simple fare and a good place for a break with not too sweet old school cake and kopi. <br><br>The swiss rolls (matcha and lychee) I had were nice but a bit on the dry side so I was not sure if they were old stock or that was the norm. <br><br>The service was non-existent and the young chap manning the counter was brusque and surly. Again, not sure if that was the usual or it was a fluke. <br><br>I did see families coming in to order birthday cakes and it made a good alternative to the usual cake shops in the malls. <br><br>I don&#39;t mind coming here again. Just don&#39;t expect a friendly and chirpy staff.

text: Cute little cafe selling cakes and food. Came here for their best selling mango peach roll. Got a slice for $1.2. The cake itself was decent, but not fluffy or notably soft. I thought the powdered sugar atop was a distraction, and they could&#39;ve gone without it. The cream is fluffy and smooth. Love it. The fruits probably came from a can, judging from the texture. It makes for a nice neighborhood bakery cafe, but not worth traveling halfway across Singapore for it, like I did. If you&#39;re in the area, you might want to make your way a little further to The Plain Jane instead for your Swiss roll cake cravings. Ambient may or may not be good for you. The cafe is not crowded, so you can chat here. But when the staff chats in the kitchen, you can totally hear them, again because the space is small.

text: Not much choices but just nice. text: Located at the start of Parkland Green is Pick Me Up Cafe. They overlook the green field which had lots of families with young children playing frisbee and the sea. A great windy location. They have both indoor and outdoor seating with free wifi.<br><br>Pick Me Up Cafe is geared more towards family oriented gatherings with young children, as they have kiddy play section at the entrance. They&#39;re not so much catered to the hipster crowd.<br><br>Pick Me Up Cafe prides itself in serving all day dining breakfast, cold pressed juice, home-made yogurt gelato, coffee and all other hearty delights that&#39;s sure to pick you up!<br>I found a groupon deal that offered a laser tag game for 5 and a family meal. After the laser tag game we were exhausted, sweaty and couldn&#39;t wait to eat dinner!<br><br>1. Caesar Salad<br>All the food pretty much came at the same time which we were appreciated, since we were starving. The caesar salad was okay, but abit too much dressing. Veggies tasted fresh and the portion was good.<br><br>2. Cajun Chicken Pizza<br>We had 2 pizzas and shared amongst 6 people, 3 guys, 3 girls. It was perfect! It was cheesy enough, the meat was tasty, but the crust, was a bit doughy. Could&#39;ve been in the oven for a while longer.<br><br>3. Tutti Frutti <br>This tasted like watermelon juice with fresh coconut jelly in it, it was refreshing and great for us, as we were still trying to cool down from the adrenaline rush from the laser tag!<br><br>4. Family Waffle $22.90+<br>What makes Pick Me Up a healthier choice is their home-made yogurt gelato! The second we walked in, we took turns trying to pick what flavours we wanted, we were getting a waffle with 4 scoops of gelato!<br><br>As it is SG50, they have an interesting variety of local flavours. We decided to try the butter pandan kaya.<br><br>With Taro, Butter Pandan Kaya, Swiss Chocolate, Pistachio, we had our family waffle which was so pretty! There were generous with the toppings! I loved the fruitty pebbles and the waffle itself was crispy on the outside and fluffy like a moist cake on the inside.<br>Perched on top of the family waffle is an caramelized almond bark. The Taro was our favourite as it was very creamy and didn&#39;t taste too artificial. The Butter Pandan Kaya tasted like a sea salt kaya, it was so good! I hope they sell this flavour with their regular offerings! The Pistachio and Swiss Chocolate were good as well.<br><br>I definitely forsee myself coming back to try more gelato flavours.<br><br>They also sell savoury waffles and all day breakfast sets!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/xX0O96LnbMnEnsrvpvYdrw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/arteastiq-singapore-3?reviewid=W27k2cMap44qhOYptMUWXg&select=xX0O96LnbMnEnsrvpvYdrw', 'altText': 'Photo of Arteastiq - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: A full and arty Sunday <br><br>If you&#39;re looking for something to fill your Sunday that offers something a little different yet able to get your creative juices flowing, than why not give Arteastiq a shot! <br><br>Located at the new Plaza Singapura&#39;s new wing (right outside Hemley&#39;s), Arteastiq offers and afternoon of surprisingly good food and an art jamming session. <br><br>Taking advantage of their offer on Groupon (fave), it was really value for money with 1-for1 mains and 1-for-1 art jamming. <br><br>Fairy Sisters - Tri-Colour Pasta ($17.00)<br>A very clean, very tasty and healthy pasta option. Fettuccini, carrot and zucchini ribbons are tossed in a light garlic oil, creating a very light, naturally sweet and tasty dish. <br>I did feel that I could have done with a tiny bit of acidity but apart from that, it was perfect. <br>And in case you need more salt and some protein, there&#39;s always the option to add smoked salmon for an additional $3.00.<br><br>Allegory of Love - Chicken and Waffles ($16.00)<br>What better combination that crispy fried chicken on top of a thick waffle! <br>The chicken was nicely tender and nicely seasoned, with its saltiness and hint of spices complimenting the crispy buttery waffle and maple syrup perfectly. <br>The waffle itself was perfectly made. Crispy on the outside, yet fluffy on the inside. The waffle&#39;s slight sweetness from the batter mixed with the aroma and slight richness from the butter, together with crispy and well seasoned chicken was a recipe for euphoria. <br><br>Overall a very well balanced dish! <br><br>And if you love teas than this is definitely THE PLACE for Teas. Fruit teas, black teas, flora teas, you name it hey have it. <br>Best bit, of you&#39;re in the mood, there&#39;s always the dessert tea option. <br><br>Captain Buntan ($12.00)<br>Pomelo tea with Yuzu Ice Cream <br>This was mind blowingly good. <br>It was the perfect sweetness mixed with a tinge of acidity made this drink intoxicatingly refreshing, hitting all the right notes along the way. <br>A must drink, especially on a hot hot day! <br><br>And when you&#39;ve filled your stomach, it&#39;s fine to let you creativity take over. <br>Simply head next door and paint away!! <br><br>Art Jamming ($48.00, 1-for-1) <br>Canvas, paints, brushes (which you can take home) and aprons are provided for your convenience. All you need to do is to bring your creative flair and paint away. By the way, each jamming session comes with a free drink too!! <br><br>So if you&#39;re looking for an activity that takes up at least the entire afternoon (we arrived at 1.30pm and left at 6.00pm) than this is the place to be!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/ceqKaB9ehP2W7Td_VcUl6g/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/arteastiq-singapore-3?reviewid=IUGygO-rMrg3v6EdVXrAGw&select=ceqKaB9ehP2W7Td_VcUl6g', 'altText': 'Photo of Arteastiq - Singapore, Singapore. interior with plush window seats', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'interior with plush window seats'}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/G-OBxEEQCai9cvrm8V-0Gg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/arteastiq-singapore-3?reviewid=IUGygO-rMrg3v6EdVXrAGw&select=G-OBxEEQCai9cvrm8V-0Gg', 'altText': 'Photo of Arteastiq - Singapore, Singapore. short ribs croque monsieur', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'short ribs croque monsieur'}]
text: I came to this place for dinner with an ominous sense of foreboding...a single 1-star yelp review, equally dubious reviews for the Mandarin Gallery branch, rave but empty reviews from bloggers like ladyironchef...it seemed to be one of those restaurants perfect for Instagram and little else. <br><br>I&#39;m happy to report that it was not as bad as it expected! But very pricey - $20+ per pax for 3 mains even with the Entertainer 1 for 1 deal. Eek. I&#39;ve had more satisfying meals for a tiny fraction of the price. If I had to pay $25++ this would be a 1-star review I think. Tea/desserts were all more than $10 too. <br><br>The part that was decent/passable/made it a two-star was the food. I expected bland, tasteless food, like some cafes where the cooks are really not competent. But food here was actually average, or even quite tasty! I ordered the short ribs croque monsieur. The portion of short ribs was generous and gooey and fatty and yummy. The sweet potato fries were also crispy without being overfried or oily. Although it wasn&#39;t a huge portion, we all agreed they were pretty good. My friends didn&#39;t have any strong objections to their duck confit/salted egg yolk cappellini, but we were not especially wowed either. <br><br>This is a lovely place to dawdle and chill. If you want to catch up with girlfriends or read a magazine slowly, you won&#39;t feel rushed in this half-empty restaurant. It would be even better (maybe 3 stars) if they served iced water...it&#39;s seriously not hard to serve tap water, especially when they have waiters milling about idly, and patrons are paying pretty well for their meals. <br><br>I&#39;m not sure if cafes like this can survive for long in somewhere like P.S. with abundant options. I&#39;d gladly pay at dessert specialists like Lady M, but Arteastiq seems to focus more on the art aspect of their business and can&#39;t claim exceptional desserts or food. Maybe they have good tea, but it&#39;d have to be pretty fabulous to be worth $15.

userinfo: {'link': '/user_details?userid=bTS3MDcJOUEDi70jiAOYfw', 'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/2KJcXcIQXz7dpFj7TGq88w/60s.jpg', 'srcSet': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/2KJcXcIQXz7dpFj7TGq88w/ms.jpg 1.67x,https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/2KJcXcIQXz7dpFj7TGq88w/120s.jpg 2.00x,https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/2KJcXcIQXz7dpFj7TGq88w/90s.jpg 1.50x,https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/2KJcXcIQXz7dpFj7TGq88w/168s.jpg 2.80x,https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/2KJcXcIQXz7dpFj7TGq88w/180s.jpg 3.00x', 'markupDisplayName': 'Greta S.', 'displayLocation': 'Singapore, Singapore', 'altText': 'Greta S.', 'userUrl': '/user_details?userid=bTS3MDcJOUEDi70jiAOYfw', 'partnerAlias': None, 'friendCount': 27, 'photoCount': None, 'reviewCount': 6, 'eliteYear': None}
text: Don&#39;t bother - customer satisfaction is not their priority. Ordered a salmon that comes with lemon butter and asked if instead of butter they could just give me some olive oil, so it wouldn&#39;t by as dry. I can&#39;t take dairy due to my disease. They refused to help me out and just kept saying &#39;cannot&#39; - no alternatives other than no sauce were offered. The menu is not friendly to those, who have food allergies. Not coming back.

Dined in on a Friday night for two. They do not accept reservations on weekends including Fridays. <br>The good: Order was taken promptly. Two entrées, one starter, and a bottle of Perrier. <br>The bad: We were left waiting for more than 40 mins for our entrées. <br>The worst: That was all that came from the kitchen to our table. <br>It was apparent that they were lacking in staff as there were only 2 servers on a Friday night! And the manager who was tending the place was put in charge of the tea and beverages; he seemed unaware of the situation his staff were in. <br>The food that came out was decent, albeit a little over-seasoned and dry (duck confit). Would have been better with a bottle of Perrier (water is chargeable)! <br>We left 35 mins after our food arrived with only having eaten our mains and cancelled the rest of the order in our bill as we had to rush to catch a movie.<br>*Also noticed that the family beside us who came earlier hadn&#39;t even gotten their mains when ours arrived. That kinda pissed them off. I completely empathise.

Nespresso Boutique', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Nespresso Boutique'}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/Vgvnq_YkybcHeKVcNjbyrw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/nespresso-boutique-singapore?reviewid=NuV4yh5S1nTxbIgrmgLLYQ&select=Vgvnq_YkybcHeKVcNjbyrw', 'altText': 'Photo of Nespresso Boutique - Singapore, Singapore. Coffee selection', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Coffee selection'}]
text: I absolutely love the Nespresso Boutique at Ion Orchard. <br><br>For starters, Nespresso coffee is hands down the best mass-produced coffee available on the market at a reasonable cost. Each sleeve costs about $18 for 7 capsules of coffee. They have 10 standard flavors available and are constantly finding new roasts marketing them as &#34;limited additions.&#34; The store has a beautiful selection of machines, ranging from professional to every day at home use. They also have a selection of cups and other accessories to compliment your purchase.<br><br>The best part, of course, is the fact that customers can come in and try out any flavor of coffee, for free! The service is excellent and the staff are very knowledgeable on all the flavors. They prepare your coffee very well, to your tastes, as an expresso or with milk.<br><br>They do not hard sell and let you enjoy the coffee for what it is rather than try and over impose on you.<br><br>Really, a lovely place to come in after a day of shopping and grab a nice cup of joe or  pick up your very own machine

Worse Nespresso Boutique service ever. <br><br>Mr. Q and I were browsing for a birthday gift for his mom. We really enjoyed our Nespresso, so we want to introduce this beautiful machine to his mom as well. <br><br>The store is beautifully presented. <br><br>When I was looking at the newest model, I felt somebody watching me from behind. Suddenly he gets closer to me. He stood right beside me and he zoomed with his eyes on my shopping bag &#34; ZooooOOmm...Topshop(cheapo), ZooOOOoommm...Bershka(Cheapo)...ZoooOOoomm...ZooOOoommm...L&#39;occitane(Idon&#39;t think she can afford the machine)&#34; I could feel his eyes checking my shopping bags and  I thought he was targetting my wallet, So I hold my bag and walk to another machine and he followed me there. &#34; We have the newest model&#34; his nose was about 2 inches from my nose. I was shocked because his face was suddenly in front my face. <br><br>OMG, this dude was analyzed me from my shopping bags to my casual wear whether I can afford their products here. <br><br>I always enjoy Nespresso because of the quality of their coffee, coffee machine, frosting machine and the attentive but not overwhelming service.<br>Unfortunately, this experience proved me otherwise.

userinfo: {'link': '/user_details?userid=mXXwmm1QM88zKCm4pVdlfw', 'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/assets/srv0/yelp_styleguide/514f6997a318/assets/img/default_avatars/user_60_square.png', 'srcSet': None, 'markupDisplayName': 'Aaron W.', 'displayLocation': 'Washington, DC', 'altText': 'Aaron W.', 'userUrl': '/user_details?userid=mXXwmm1QM88zKCm4pVdlfw', 'partnerAlias': None, 'friendCount': 0, 'photoCount': None, 'reviewCount': 4, 'eliteYear': None}
text: While the Nespresso boutique is a nice place, well presented with very good and well trained staff, there are other issues that presented themselves when I first bought my Nespresso in Singapore. To start, the delivery was confusing as once I left the store, I was unable to contact the ION store directly. I am serious, they do not allow calls directly to the store - you must call the toll free Singapore number to coordinate with a Nespresso Rep. <br><br>Once I did get ahold of a central representative, they tried to coordinate the delivery but it took longer than anticipated. <br><br>Even a simple billing question is difficult to answer due to their unnecessary complex structure. <br><br>While I enjoy Nespresso and believe they are the best option for quick, delicious espresso - especially in Singapore, I believe they need to improve their customer service contact process. I should not have to contact a central representative, who then contacts the store, who then figures out the issue, who then calls me back and coordinates from there. The central rep told me they cannot give out the store number directly (and I called the number on the Nespresso Singapore site, and it just rang repeatedly. <br><br>Nespresso has a great product but improved customer service is a must.

Unlike TCC, Nespresso Boutique is the place to go for coffee lovers. <br><br>In this boutique they only do coffee, nothing else. And they do it with style. Hip Nespresso machines brew espresso from coffee capsules, a type of pre-apportioned single-use container of ground coffee and flavorings. They have a standard 10 flavors with every 2 months a Nespresso special, a good reason to visit the store again. <br><br>The Nespresso Aeroccino Milk Frother is just amazing. Put your favorite milk in it, push the button and it creates a froth in half a minute, which is thick, dense and creamy and just perfect!<br><br>The ambiance of the store feels luxurious and modern. The staff is professional, attentive and kind. 10 capsules sell at S$ 9,90.

Well as the name says it, it is nespresso boutique. It sells all thing nespresso there. <br><br>You can pick up the machines, coffee capsules, cups and much more there. Well, it is not like a starbuck or a coffee bean where you can buy your cup of joe but you definitely can sample your coffee here.<br><br>The service is awesome here too.

Teh Halia and sardine curry puff', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Teh Halia and sardine curry puff'}]
text: Come here for teh tarik or teh halia (ginger milk tea) if you are searching for your non-Starbucks or fancy coffee and tea. It is really good, with the typical Indian milky sweetness. Perfect.<br><br>The sardine puff is not as good as the tea though. It is not crispy and the sardine filling is not spicy or sour enough. <br><br>I have yet to try the local Indian muslim food dishes which are available at the adjoining shop. <br><br>This place also sells small snacks and tidbits, like a &#34;mama&#34; shop but with a bigger premise. <br><br>A good no frills place with affordable prices in the Orchard area. You can get a cup of teh or kopi for just $1.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/2Vj3aI2yc8Bpe2dW_uhrJg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/tiong-bahru-yong-tau-foo-singapore?reviewid=xXNpoGu-NwbjSlAauxEaSw&select=2Vj3aI2yc8Bpe2dW_uhrJg', 'altText': 'Photo of Tiong Bahru Yong Tau Foo - Singapore, Singapore. $3 without fishballs', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': '$3 without fishballs'}]
text: This place is my husband&#39;s and my regular breakfast stop before he drops me off at my office. We are so regular that when the coffee shop attendant sees us walking towards them, my usual kopi poh siu dai and my hubby&#39;s kopi O kosong will be on the table shortly after we sat down. <br><br>Not too long later, our usual Yong Tau Foo kosong (means no noodles), and mine without fishballs (i traded my fishballs with their tau foo skin wrapped fish paste), will be served. Talk about fast food!<br><br>They are super friendly, from the 1st time I ate there, till now, without fail I will see them all greet customers. An old lady who is in-charge of setting the chopsticks, spoon and sauce will be the first once you&#39;ve set down, always smiling.<br><br>Simple pleasures....

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/5DO-MZM-UiVRat9tYgT4wQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/tiong-bahru-yong-tau-foo-singapore?reviewid=BicVxLUHSRvXsr_BlVc3vw&select=5DO-MZM-UiVRat9tYgT4wQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Tiong Bahru Yong Tau Foo - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: This is an old coffee shop that at last count boasted four stalls. Viewing the clientele, it&#39;s pretty plain to see that the yong tau foo is by far the most popular option. There&#39;s only four permutations: soup or dry, big ($4) or small ($3). Only bee hoon is used, no other way about it. It&#39;s Hakka style, so you get three kinds of ingredients - fish balls, fish paste wrapped in bean curd skin, and tofu - and the chilli and sweet sauce dip goes with the ingredients nicely. There&#39;s an undeniably homely feel to a piping hot bowl of flavorful, soupy bee hoon with some soy beans nestled at the bottom in the middle of the day. Granted, you&#39;d be drenched in sweat after the lunch hour, but resistance is futile. Come early as some of the items get sold out sooner than others. You wouldn&#39;t want to be faced with the prospect of yong tau foo bee hoon turning into a tofu bee hoon lunch.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/p_WJtec80QK9pWdQaM7foQ/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/drinks-desserts-stall-smith-street-singapore?reviewid=Uq4JhLPy7JqxOw_5HqPxgA&select=p_WJtec80QK9pWdQaM7foQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Drinks/Desserts Stall Smith Street - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': ''}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/vyy3hhtS1hKHF_Gyx2DLPQ/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/drinks-desserts-stall-smith-street-singapore?reviewid=Uq4JhLPy7JqxOw_5HqPxgA&select=vyy3hhtS1hKHF_Gyx2DLPQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Drinks/Desserts Stall Smith Street - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': ''}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/I-228jtrXbJXNQAlM_GYQw/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/drinks-desserts-stall-smith-street-singapore?reviewid=Uq4JhLPy7JqxOw_5HqPxgA&select=I-228jtrXbJXNQAlM_GYQw', 'altText': 'Photo of Drinks/Desserts Stall Smith Street - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': ''}]
text: I love, love, love, love this Drinks/Desserts stall. It&#39;s got really good options - every thing&#39;s fresh, and the varieties are just mind-boggling. They have great local stuff, like Water Chestnut, Coconut Juice and all the yummy local desserts, Cheng Teng, Soursop, Ice Kacang, etc.<br><br>What I Love: It&#39;s at a great location, very accessible. The service is great, and their Coconuts are really fresh and affordable - I think, $3? Which is really pretty okay. I&#39;ve paid $5 in Changi Village - which is definitely kinda pricey. Their other drinks, Water Chestnut, Bandung, and canned options are also pretty affordable and tasty. Gotta try their Desserts - they are really, really, really yummy!! I usually ask them to make my Ice Kacang with just the Gula Melaka (Omg - I feel like having it RIGHT NOW!) and their Soursop, and other cold concoctions are all pretty good.<br><br>What I Don&#39;t Love: Absolutely nothing!! ;D

text: A great place for food drinks (full bar) or coffee.  Great staff and atmosphere. They show all footbal games even early morning or late night.  <br>The Aragosta pasta has awesome lobster type bugs. Super nice and I think only about 18 bucks. Pints are fairly priced at around $14. <br>They also do good Pizza.

text: Located a little off the usual shopping hubs, Cafe Football has lots of space you can hold parties and even wedding receptions! Plenty of parking with added benefit that is also free! <br>Food wise, there&#39;s something for everyone that&#39;s normal as cafe fare. <br>To keep everyone occupied while waiting for food or to relax with your gang, there are games like dart boards and table soccer (of course)

This is a great place for early drinks or a casual meeting. Happy hour starts from 4pm to 7pm with $7 pints. Food is reasonably good and you can catch your football games here. Lots of free parking right in front but gets a bit crowded after 6pm. No many places like this near this area.

text: A random little cafe in Little India. To be very honest, I stopped in for the wifi (which you can just ask the girl behind the counter for), and ended up having the red velvet cake with sea salt caramel drizzle. It hit the spot!<br><br>Would be a great place to meet up with friends for a nice quiet chat.<br><br>Very cutesy decor, with little hanging lights and quotes/sayings on the walls.<br><br>Bathroom is in the back, through a small storage room.

text: One of the first thing that comes to my mind when I see the word &#34;Butterstudio&#34; is butter (not buttermilk). Indeed, this Halal Cafe located in the Jalan Besar has won fans for its cupcakes and other pastries. However, it is also cosy place that offers brunch items like egg benedicts and pancakes. <br><br>The Signature Red Velvet Cake ($7.90/slice) is drizzled with salted caramel for that savoury balance. The cake is moist and tender but the efforts were rendered futile by the intense sweetness evident in both the cake and the cream cheese. These seemed to be the case for the cupcakes and jar cakes, which were a pity because they looked good and stirred my excitement initially.<br><br>However, the Sea Salt Nutella Tart was an instant winner with a crisp shortcrust shell and rich creamy Nutella. The addition of salt magically brought the Nutella to an optimal sweetness. The Belgian Chocolate Tart comes close behind with a 50-60% chocolate cream blended with milk chocolate but the cacao taste did not shine brilliantly that day. <br><br>If you love poached eggs, you will be extremely pleased to know that there is quite a number of dishes to choose from the brunch menu. From the Norwegian Salmon Bagels ($18) to the Classic Egg Florentines in Ciabatta ($13), each one comes with 2 poached eggs and Hollandaise sauce. The classic Morning Benedicts ($12) is still the reliable choice as nothing beats a well-buttered and toasted English muffin layered with chicken ham and turkey bacon. <br><br>Packed with a crispy hash-brown, scrambled eggs and cheese in a tortilla skin, the hangover breakfast wrap ($12) might not be the most delicious cure but it is definitely a nourishing pack to fight the headache and perk you up for the rest of the day.

text: A very nice cafe along a stretch of Jalan Besar more known for its motorcycle accessory shops. Opens till late on Fridays and Saturdays, so you can pop over here for a sit and rest after bustling your way through Little India and Mustafa Shopping Centre.<br><br>They describe their offerings as &#34;not overly fussy&#34; and &#34;served with warmth&#34; and that&#39;s quite an apt description. The baked foods look good with none of that &#34;look at me I&#39;m an exquisite dessert&#34; nonsense and there&#39;s quite a wide variety of product on offer. <br><br>While I haven&#39;t tried most of the food on the menu, I can tell you that the Salted Caramel Nutella Tart is a sweet-tooth-satisfying crunch, the Chicken Ham &amp; Egg Toast Cup is a unexpectedly comforting chomp, and the Muddy Mud Cake is probably the best chocolate cake I&#39;ve had in a cafe. Served warm, the Muddy Mud Cake is a delicious gobble that is just moist enough and the right amount of dense that makes for a toothsome chomp that isn&#39;t pound-cake heavy nor fleetingly airy.<br><br>The Lemonade Jar is a nice refreshing sip but disappointingly, the lemonade doesn&#39;t get served in the jar. It&#39;s poured out into the large glass with ice instead, which is a perfectly acceptable way to enjoy lemonade. But the jars just look so inviting in the counter.  Anyway, there is also a range of coffees and teas and the usual suspects on the drink menu. <br><br>Butter Studio isn&#39;t very large, but it&#39;s a cosy, comforting space. You can chill solo or come with your friends for a quiet chat, or for some board or card games that you can find for free use at the corner of the cafe. They host crafty workshops and performances every once in a while too.

Having relocated from their original store at Changi Airport Terminal 3 (which is only a takeaway store), Butter Studio has now moved to Jalan Besar, where now it has a dine-in space and still offers the same variety as their previous outlet.<br><br>They now have all-day brunch!<br><br>Sweets selection<br><br>And the cupcakes, cakes, tarts and drinks menu!<br><br>The Sea Salt Caramel Nutella Tart ($6.90), which is one of their signature items, is satisfying. The Nutella, mixed with the sea salt caramel and accompanied with walnuts on top, tasted rich. The tart crust is firm and not too crumbly.<br>Yet another option for bakes and cakes within the Jalan Besar area (and it&#39;s also rather convenient since it faces the main road!)

Located in HarborFront on level 3, this place is good to catch up on some local delights as well as Thai food. Plus point - it&#39;s in an air-conditioned mall. The stall ranges from Vegetable Rice, Ban Mian, Roast Meat, Nasi Padang and Thai. I generally come here for the roast meat selection as well as the Ban Mian stall as they carry a Gan Lao Mian which I pretty much like. I will probably take a picture and write a little more about it the next time I am there. Maybe the only little dislike is that the seating is a little tighter and being my size, I naturally felt a bit too squeezy. Hmmmm.... Time to lose weight... But does that mean I need to stop coming here for my foodie??!!
Nice coffee shop right outside Suntec City. They have beans from Jamaica (Kingston) and the coffee tastes good. Nice place to grab a cup if you&#39;re in the area.
