text: This is a much smaller outlet compared to those at Star Vista and Raffles Place and I am guessing it can get real noisy and crowded during the peak hours. <br><br>I went on a Saturday afternoon and it was fairly empty though it got filled up 15 minutes after. Somehow being located &#34;outside&#34;, it tended to get hot in the afternoon. I am guessing the glass walls and door kinda create a greenhouse effect on a sunny day. <br><br>The selection of cakes and salads and ready to go food is considerably smaller than the one at Raffles Place. <br><br>The coffee is still good. So I guess this can be a good spot on quiet days when you want to have a cuppa and watch the traffic and people go by outside.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/5Ccb1AhZyN1wLQ6X8rePQw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/starbucks-singapore-52?reviewid=23GP_vKb0jI6vBqrAGtNKg&select=5Ccb1AhZyN1wLQ6X8rePQw', 'altText': 'Photo of Starbucks - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: Well, I&#39;ve failed you all.<br><br>When I came to Singapore, I told myself that I&#39;d never patronize a Starbucks. There are a ton of local places that have legit coffee and I&#39;d rather support &#34;the little guys&#34;. (Not to mention, I&#39;ve grown to like the basic kopi!)<br><br>However, I had to cave. I was meeting my husband at his office so we could go to the airport together. I arrived early and he wasn&#39;t ready yet. I was already hungry and thirsty, as dragging a 7 kg carry-on luggage through the MRT and Friday rush hour traffic in CBD will do that to you!<br><br>I saw this Starbucks in Lobby A of 1 George Street, and noticed it is now open and functional. With a heavy sigh, I took the FAIL card out of my wallet and proceeded towards this beacon of corporate America. I decided on the fancily named soy apricot muffin and a tall iced latte. Total? $9.40 (eye roll)<br><br>2 stars for the price, but 3 stars for the location, convenience, and assistance in taming my hunger to ensure &#34;Hangry Michelle&#34; doesn&#39;t make an appearance. :)

My wife and I went there for brunch last Sunday. There was no seats left inside so we settled outside. It was noisy as the place is located at a busy corner. The tables are very near to each other and we were in the middle thus we can clearly hear the guests from both sides. It was quite unpleasant. Not the restaurants&#39; fault though. <br><br>The food was OK. I had the hunters&#39; breakfast and my wife has the omelette signature dish. Coffee was OK as well.<br><br>I&#39;d recommend it to anyone in the area but don&#39;t go out of your way for this place.

text: This is one of those rare situations where I disagree with the current Yelp rating.<br><br>I&#39;m new to the &#39;hood, and I decided to give Rabbit Carrot Gun a try as Miguel was raving about their breakfast. When we arrived, we were greeted by Richard, the lovely owner. He was very chatty and made us laugh quite easily, so I had this feeling that a good experience was coming up.<br><br>After perusing the menu, we called Richard over. I had questions about the juices, and he was very honest (&#34;Oh, the second one? That&#39;s just a fancy name for apple juice!&#34;) I ended up choosing the Ruddy and Ready, which is their take on the classic ABC juice.<br><br>I ordered the French toast upon the recommendation of Miguel, while he tried the special, which was an omelet with a local twist. I loved my French toast, as it was light, there was a generous side of maple syrup, and the portion was perfect for me. The berry compote really made the dish! Miguel&#39;s special was a well-executed savoury dish; good to know they can add in local flavours competently.<br><br>As it&#39;s now 2015, I encourage everyone to stop by and check out what they&#39;re doing here. With Richard now managing the restaurant most of the time, the staff here is well trained and his presence just makes the place feel very neighbourhood-y and lovely. If you have the pleasure of meeting Richard when you visit, you&#39;ll know what I mean.

text: I&#39;m seriously calling out all the Yelpers for their reviews of this restaurant. This brunch spot is downright AMAZING! From the food to the ambience to service. All great. <br><br>The Breakfast menu is top-notch. The French Toast served with maple syrup &amp; berry compote was Wow! I like my French Toast a little soft, likely due to slow cooking. However, this French toast was doused with egg cinnamon and dark sugar mix. Who knew French toast could be mixed with anything other than butter. The berry compote is a nice touch, adding that sweetness that so many of us crave in the morning. I know I mentioned that Suprette had an amazing French toast, Rabbit Carrot Gun just may be a little better! <br><br>The other dish worth a try is the omelette with sugar cured prawns and topped with sweet Malaysian Sambal. The owner, Richard, dared me to try this dish and said to me that if I didn&#39;t like it, it would be on the house. Let&#39;s just say, I didn&#39;t get my money back. :D Kudos to Rabbit Carrot Gun for delivering a traditional western meal with an South East Asian twist! I&#39;m dreaming of it already, as I write this review.<br><br>My only knock on this restaurant was the flat white. It was just that, flat... There is some seriously some good competition nearby, ie Group Therapy Cafe etc, so I can&#39;t blame them. <br><br>In terms of ambience, who can beat an open space on the corner of the bustling street of East Coast Road. Best of all, this spot has a neighborhood feel to it, which brings me back to my days of living in Brooklyn, NY. I would argue that this one shop turned the fortunes of Joo Chiat / Katong into the next new hip neighborhood. This resto oozes what this neighborhood can become.<br><br>In terms of service, maybe I was a little spoiled since we were served by the gregarious and welcoming owner, Richard. However, I&#39;ve been here once before on a weekday morning and thought the staff was courteous and prompt.<br><br>Overall, one of my favorite brunch places on the Red Dot, if not my favorite. I can&#39;t speak on behalf of the other reviews, which were written eons ago, but this place has surely improved since those were written. Keep it up guys!

text: Had dinner last night here, after stumbling around the block while waiting for our movie. Finally we decided to dine here, coz ( i think is the owner, a big western guy) come approach to greet us. I had rib eye steak; it was bit too thin and meat bit hard for my taste, the potato gratin also bit dry. Hubby had saussage, it was ok. We had choco lava with ice cream as a dessert, was ok too.<br>Ambience was nice and warm, service good and fast. But i wont come back for their rib eye.

Came in for the Sunday roast. What did I end up getting served was a VERY dry Sunday roast. Veggies were cooked all right, not mushy. However, the beef was very dry and couldn&#39;t even be reconstituted with gravy. Friendly but slow service as well. Definitely would not come back here.

Wanted to feed some of my Brit pals some grub from their home and this place came up in the trawling the internet.<br><br>Many of us had the Sunday Roast (or at least the meal that came closest to that) and it was at best so so only. The meat cut was slightly dry and not very flavourful if not for the sauce. The sides were also ok only. The meal was not cheap thus I thought it was not really value for money. <br><br>Not likely to return though...

text: Had the Beef Wellington which was rather underwhelming, the beef was kind of bland and the puff pastry was raw. <br><br>However, the staff was kind enough to re-bake it for me, but the beef became over done and the pastry was still kind of raw. The staff are attentive and nice, but the food is quite bad.<br><br>My friend had the Beetroot salad and it was extremely blend as well. Wouldn&#39;t suggest it, but the drink menu is comprehensive.

text: Pretty quiet for a Sunday evening dinner much different from a Saturday lunch crowd that we saw.  By quiet I mean really quiet like 20 percent capacity.  Certainly no need for a reservation and I wonder why.  We sort of had cold feet on whether we should even bother going in and tempted do a burger two doors down but braved it anyway.  The food finally came...ordered the salmon, steak and the sausages.  Food was pretty good actually.  For starters they did not over cook the salmon.  The apple sausages were nice with just enough fat and pork.  The mash that came with the salmon and sausage was light and smooth.  They got a medium rare steak right too.  Only issue is on a value for money they get a 2 out of 5.  Certainly a salmon with mash and local naibi will not cost you $28 and another 10 bucks that be at fine dinning level main course.  That is a high profit margin there.  Ambience wise it was a little dimly lit and the Airconditioning has no effect.  I suppose if you want more customers they should brighten the place up perhaps able to attract more customers.  Overall service was not too bad just perhaps things are a little slower so they tend to be slower?  Has the apple crumple and toffe pudding.  Not bad but wish they got more ice cream.  Unfortunately the toffee pudding could not beat the one at pinique at taka.

text: Honestly I&#39;ve never had such bad service in my life. Despite claiming to be family friendly when I went there in a Friday evening with my wife and young son we were made anything but welcome. The owner clearly did not want us there and as soon as we sat down stood over us until we ordered straight away. He clearly took exception to the fact we weren&#39;t ordering wine.<br>The food was ok but service terrible. Had to ask 5 times for water for my son.  When the owner asked how everything was I said my main was very small 3 prawns and 3 tortellini. He took exception to this then went round asking other customers what they thought of their main course. <br>He then came back to the table to tell me no one else thought it was too small and it was clearly my faulty perception that was the issue. He was rude, arrogant and aggressive.<br>Don&#39;t waste your money here. He ruined our night.

text: This is one of those rare situations where I disagree with the current Yelp rating.<br><br>I&#39;m new to the &#39;hood, and I decided to give Rabbit Carrot Gun a try as Miguel was raving about their breakfast. When we arrived, we were greeted by Richard, the lovely owner. He was very chatty and made us laugh quite easily, so I had this feeling that a good experience was coming up.<br><br>After perusing the menu, we called Richard over. I had questions about the juices, and he was very honest (&#34;Oh, the second one? That&#39;s just a fancy name for apple juice!&#34;) I ended up choosing the Ruddy and Ready, which is their take on the classic ABC juice.<br><br>I ordered the French toast upon the recommendation of Miguel, while he tried the special, which was an omelet with a local twist. I loved my French toast, as it was light, there was a generous side of maple syrup, and the portion was perfect for me. The berry compote really made the dish! Miguel&#39;s special was a well-executed savoury dish; good to know they can add in local flavours competently.<br><br>As it&#39;s now 2015, I encourage everyone to stop by and check out what they&#39;re doing here. With Richard now managing the restaurant most of the time, the staff here is well trained and his presence just makes the place feel very neighbourhood-y and lovely. If you have the pleasure of meeting Richard when you visit, you&#39;ll know what I mean.

text: I&#39;m seriously calling out all the Yelpers for their reviews of this restaurant. This brunch spot is downright AMAZING! From the food to the ambience to service. All great. <br><br>The Breakfast menu is top-notch. The French Toast served with maple syrup &amp; berry compote was Wow! I like my French Toast a little soft, likely due to slow cooking. However, this French toast was doused with egg cinnamon and dark sugar mix. Who knew French toast could be mixed with anything other than butter. The berry compote is a nice touch, adding that sweetness that so many of us crave in the morning. I know I mentioned that Suprette had an amazing French toast, Rabbit Carrot Gun just may be a little better! <br><br>The other dish worth a try is the omelette with sugar cured prawns and topped with sweet Malaysian Sambal. The owner, Richard, dared me to try this dish and said to me that if I didn&#39;t like it, it would be on the house. Let&#39;s just say, I didn&#39;t get my money back. :D Kudos to Rabbit Carrot Gun for delivering a traditional western meal with an South East Asian twist! I&#39;m dreaming of it already, as I write this review.<br><br>My only knock on this restaurant was the flat white. It was just that, flat... There is some seriously some good competition nearby, ie Group Therapy Cafe etc, so I can&#39;t blame them. <br><br>In terms of ambience, who can beat an open space on the corner of the bustling street of East Coast Road. Best of all, this spot has a neighborhood feel to it, which brings me back to my days of living in Brooklyn, NY. I would argue that this one shop turned the fortunes of Joo Chiat / Katong into the next new hip neighborhood. This resto oozes what this neighborhood can become.<br><br>In terms of service, maybe I was a little spoiled since we were served by the gregarious and welcoming owner, Richard. However, I&#39;ve been here once before on a weekday morning and thought the staff was courteous and prompt.<br><br>Overall, one of my favorite brunch places on the Red Dot, if not my favorite. I can&#39;t speak on behalf of the other reviews, which were written eons ago, but this place has surely improved since those were written. Keep it up guys!

text: Came on a quiet late Saturday morning as me and wife had often passed this charmingly laid out cafe in our weekend explorations of the Katong/Joo Chiat neighborhood. Sadly, the experience was disappointing. <br><br>Despite a half empty cafe, food was served almost 30 minutes after coffee and juice arrived. The chalkboard advertised pork pie was minuscule and burnt -- the bottom crust was blackened and my knife couldn&#39;t cut through. The eggs Benedict was so-so, which didn&#39;t make the wait worthwhile. <br><br>When I sent back the pork pie, the wait staff didn&#39;t seem surprised. As no one from the kitchen came to apologize, I decided not to accept a replacement and canceled the item. <br><br>The disappointment spilled over to our general appetites and we decided not to finish the flat whites.

Wanted to feed some of my Brit pals some grub from their home and this place came up in the trawling the internet.<br><br>Many of us had the Sunday Roast (or at least the meal that came closest to that) and it was at best so so only. The meat cut was slightly dry and not very flavourful if not for the sauce. The sides were also ok only. The meal was not cheap thus I thought it was not really value for money. <br><br>Not likely to return though...
Service is really very slow, waited 40mins for a simple branch meal. Flood is so not satisfying, total regret for wasting time and calories in this restaurant.

text: Buckwheat ale was the highlight for me. The food wasn&#39;t bad - it was served with honesty and generosity but with a little less finesse than one would have hoped. I am only giving it 3 stars as it feels somewhat overpriced... clearly targetting the expat market.

text: Some friends and I were there recently for a mid-afternoon respite. All I will say is the chocolate-banana cake is the bomb. An unassuming slice it may be, but packed so full of chocolaty flavour you cannot believe. <br><br>Black is very popular with the office crowd, so it was full at 4pm on a Friday. I don&#39;t know if they were understaffed or just disorganized, but it was certainly unpleasant that there was an uncleared table (that because dirty-dishes central from other tables) in the middle of the cafe. Surely it doesn&#39;t take so long to clean that up and free up more space for more customers?

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/KPA_wSei7weDMQcGHthXjA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/black-singapore?reviewid=40ffmRYfylI2dZfSyghghg&select=KPA_wSei7weDMQcGHthXjA', 'altText': 'Photo of Black - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: Another great cafe in Raffles Place that serves excellent coffees and desserts.  Irregardless of the time of day, this place feels chilled and relaxed.  They do breakfast specials of coffee + scones / muffins, and also lunch specials of a coffee and salad / sandwiches. <br>The breakfast is great - their muffins and scones are sinfully buttery but oh so tasty! A real treat in the morning - prepared and served by their cheery staff.  The lunch isn&#39;t so fantastic, very mediocre sandwiches that aren&#39;t warmed up enough even when you ask for it to be toasted, and due to the small kitchen, we waited close to half an hour for the sandwiches to be served.  If you&#39;re in a rush, Black probably isn&#39;t the place to go for lunch, but no complaints otherwise - still one of my favourite cafes to visit around this area.

Another great coffee shop in Bukit Timah. Great selection of brewed and espresso coffee. Hot and cold. They also have two selections of nitro brewed coffee. <br>What is obvious is how much passion has gone into this shop. Take a look at the hardware that they have installed for roasting and brewing. They are very serious about their Joe.

Relatively new coffee place - right next to Rise &amp; Grind. Korean style 3rd wave / specialty coffee, with the usual range of espresso and manual brewing methods. They also roast in the shop - which accounts for the burnt cookie smell that fills the place from time to time. But what drew me into the store was the huge, white EK43 lurking in the corner that signaled the potential for a good pourover. Peeking behind the counter, portafilters locked tight into the group head are always a good sign of a café that knows its shit. <br><br>Ambience is bright and airy, despite the tight confines of the unit, and the staff are friendly and welcoming. <br><br>So, coffee. It&#39;s certainly a step up from the other coffee outlets in the building. They do a tasty cold brew (also done in store), and espresso beverages are well-pulled. <br><br>But of course any self respecting coffeenista will want to know what their hand brew is like. They brew with a Clever at 88 deg C, for about 3 mins. Have tried their Ethiopian and Kenyan beans, and found their hand brew to be a bit over extracted - nonetheless, still tastier than the competition. <br><br>Still, it&#39;s early days and I reckon I&#39;ll drop by often since its in my patch. Staff were open to my feedback on the grind size, so I&#39;m looking forward to some variety in their pourover.

Instagram: @fernanda.esc', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Instagram: @fernanda.esc'}]
text: Real juice, with real fruits and vegetables, at an affordable price! #ImAFan<br><br>Orchard road is filled with so many overpriced coffee shops and restaurants, that is sometimes hard to know where to shop or eat if you are on a budget. I was really happy to find 365 Fruit Juice, because after 2 weeks of only eating ramen, indian food, and lots of rice, I was definitely in some major need of real fruits and vegetable in my diet.<br><br>I would honestly recommend everyone to pay $1 extra to make any juice a pressed juice. I think is worth it and is better for your health.

Rafee&#39;s Corner claims that they sell the best teh halia in Singapore. While the claim might be a little bit OTT, their teh halia tarik and teh tarik really hits the spot for me. For lovers of Mr Tea&#39;s teh tarik, the ones brewed by Mr Rafee (I assume that&#39;s the name of the boss who does the brewing) might not be what they are looking for. But what I love about the tah halia from Rafee&#39;s Corner is the generous amount of ginger they put inside the tea - making the tea tangy and soothing at the same time. For those who prefer not to have ginger, their teh tarik is also very good - smooth and creamy with a very strong, wholesome taste of tea leaves in every sip.

text: Yummy bak chor mee! <br><br>I&#39;ve also had the laksa here which is decent but the star here is the Bak Chor Mee. The dry version is chocked full of porky flavor goodness. Plenty of ingredients between the the minced pork, sliced pork, pork balls, and braised mushrooms combined with the slightly vinegary sauce. The noodles have a nice bite-back texture and the soup to wash it all down is pretty flavorful too. <br><br>As a bonus, they&#39;re open super late so you can fulfill your bak chor mee cravings even at odd hours.

text: What do you do when you are craving local food like mee pok in the wee hours of the night? Head on down to Mengs kitchen! Even at 12mn, I had wait at least 10 minutes to get a table.<br><br>Do not expect air con and a super clean coffee shop, this is your typical coffee shop you find in the heartlands on upper Thomson road. It is quite hot and stuffy and I would recommend you to get a table outside the shop, facing the main road for some fresh air.<br><br>Pay up front at the cashier, starting at $4 for mee pok and $5 for a mini work. It&#39;s still reasonable and the food is served to you rather quickly. They are generous with the seaweed in the soup and you can taste the lard in everything! The soup was quite addictive but it didn&#39;t leave me feeling thirsty so hopefully no MSG? The fish balls had soup in them so be careful when chewing on them! The noodles tasted good and we enjoyed it! Would definitely be back if I have another craving for noodles in the middle of the night!

text: As BCM goes, this is really very good. <br><br>We ordered their Fried Fish Cake to share and the name doesn&#39;t do the side dish justice. It&#39;s homemade fish paste between bean curd skins. Very   <br>crispy when eaten fresh off the fryer. Very yummy indeed!!!<br><br>I like their chill base for their noodles and that makes their noodles awesome! Love how every strain gets coated with the spicy sauce!<br><br>I&#39;m definitely a returning customer!!!

text: Many people love this small humble food spot and I&#39;m one of them. The mainstream mee pok dry bak chor mee is good but I always love the mini wok soup with mee pok on the side... <br><br>I find the broth tastes extremely original with all the juices from boiled pork meats and other goodness...<br><br>Their ngo hiang and fried fish cake are also good as side dishes.<br><br>Hint:<br>Free flow pork lard underneath the sauce tray at the left corner :p

text: It is a decent bowl of bak-chor noodles. But not enough to create any craving. I would eat it if I am in the vicinity or if I am craving bcm in the middle of the night.<br><br>The texture of the noodles is ok, but the flavor is not quite there. Somehow it feels too commercialized. <br><br>And definitely not X-factor shiok like the 45min bowl at Crawford Street.

text: My favourite place for bar chor mee! I&#39;ve tried a few of the famous stalls around Singapore but this is still no. 1 for me. But of course, I could be biased as this is the stall that I frequent the most. Anyhow, if you&#39;re in the Thomson area looking for a cheap and affordable meal, look no further than Meng&#39;s Kitchen! Plus, they are open for 24 hours so you can satisfy your BCM craving at anytime. There&#39;s always a crowd at Meng&#39;s, even before Udders came and made the area even more lively after 11pm.  <br><br>The noodles are springy, the portion of minced meat is generous and the chilli-vinegar combination is just right. The soup&#39;s good too. Other than the BCM, also try the fried fishcakes which are crispy and bouncy. A bowl of this makes a perfect post-drinks meal!

text: One of the best BCM I&#39;ve eaten. Great texture of noodle with hint of vinegar and chili. Couldn&#39;t ask for more than this!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/UwsBMNqs0yEGkwmGJ88z3Q/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/meng-kitchen-singapore?reviewid=G8txrQFS7JA4VoPoOUxhlA&select=UwsBMNqs0yEGkwmGJ88z3Q', 'altText': 'Photo of Meng Kitchen - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: I&#39;ve tried the famous Bak Chor Mee at Hill Street, and a couple more at other &#39;famous&#39; places, and i daresay Meng&#39;s Kitchen at Upper Thomson is still my top favourite. <br><br>The staff are prompt, and their bak chor mee has a good balance of oil and ingredients. The noodle are tangy, and the vinegar is just in the right proportion. Further, the soup that comes with it is most satisfying in the wee hours of the morning when you want to satisfy a food craving. <br><br>Their drinks such as sour plum and teh ping are not bad too. The best part is that it is really affordable. For around $5 or less, you can get a bowl of piping hot noodles with a drink.<br><br>Being open 24/7, it is a popular after-clubbing destination, or if you&#39;re just bored and want to find a place to hang out..

Comfort food that is available 24 hours everyday.<br><br>Must-tries: soup bak chor mee and laksa<br><br>For those driving: Beware, do not park illegally in this area. The LTA officers are very on around here. Take the time to find proper parking or risk eating a $50/$70 meal.

Perhaps I may never figure out why Meng KItchen has found such a place in my heart. It would have been so easy to walk by - barring the garish big MENG KITCHEN sprawled across the signboard above, nothing sets it apart from the other stalls you&#39;ll walk by along the row. The fragrance of vinegar does not particularly invite me in, nor does the very standard, run-of-the-mill interior.<br><br>Yet perhaps I have been charmed by its simplicity and faithfulness to its food. It never messes with me; when I need it it is always there, and when I have it it is always true to its taste. The fact that it is open all round the clock is such a massive draw, yet I have never found the need to relegate this to a midnight craving - I&#39;m happy to rely on this as my staple meal. <br><br>For a reliable bowl of bak chor mee, you could not ask for more. The noodles are done just right, if not a little springy sometimes (but some love this), the amount of vinegar is literally just right and everything always seems catered to your taste, as if it were cooked by a good old friend who knows you well. <br><br>Maybe that&#39;s why Meng Kitchen bak chor mee is my official go-to guy now.

Meng&#39;s has been my regular bar chor mee joint for years. While it used to make a seriously good bowl of noodles comparable to all the famous bak chor mee places out there, standards have sadly been dropping over the years. Sometimes, the noodles and sauce mix can be quite hit or miss. I have on a few occasions now, found my noodles a tad over cooked and under seasoned. However, I do think Meng&#39;s remains one of those reliable BCM places. While it&#39;s not mind blowing and yes, you can probably find better bowls of BCM out there, Meng&#39;s is open 24 hours, it&#39;s quick, and it&#39;s familiar.

Meng Kitchen is one of the more famous bak chor mee stalls around, and being a huge bak chor mee fan, I knew that I had to give this place a spin to find out what all the fuss is about, despite the fact that I don&#39;t even live in the area.<br>I arrived during off peak hours and managed to get my bowl of noodles without having to wait for too long. I opted for mee pok since this is my preferred type of noodles. The noodles came fluffy and sufficiently chewy, and not at all soggy. I really enjoyed the noodles a lot. The base contained vinegar and of course chili sauce, and the combination of the two (with probably some secret ingredients) gave rise to one of the most satisfying bowls of bak chor mee I have ever eaten. The icing on the cake was the very generous portion of minced pork and liver; I have always felt that some stalls tried to make their food seem nicer by limiting the serving size, but apparently that is not the practice. Do come here if you want to taste what a really good bowl of bak chor mee should taste like.

The delightful Burgundy Escargots.', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'The delightful Burgundy Escargots.'}]
text: Well... Isn&#39;t this a surprise?<br><br>Firstly, let me explain why I decided to rate this place, and register the coffee shop as one entity instead of reviewing individual stalls. <br>Salute coffee shop is probably the first coffee shop that takes reservations, despite the stall you&#39;re choosing to eat at. (I apologize for the lack of a contact number as most sites I&#39;ve searched do not provide a reservation number. I will assume that their contact number is 6276 6445, which is Stew Küche&#39;s number as they seem to be the anchor tenant and overall running the &#34;operations&#34; of the coffee shop). <br><br>Secondly, this place has to be experienced as a whole. Though made up of different stalls, the coffee shop is dressed with table cloth (although they&#39;re the plastic checkered kind, but yes, tables are dressed), has a queue line and well.. You&#39;re not just going to eat from one stall here. The variety available is incredible! <br><br>Here&#39;s my review on all the stuff we ate. <br>1) Burgundy Escargots, Immanuel French Kitchen.<br>I had my doubts when I first collected this dish. Personally, I prefer my escargots in the shell as they tend to overcook when removed but this dish was done so perfectly well. The tomato fondue wasn&#39;t over powering and the garlic butter on top added a nice pungent kick to the dish and balances out well with the tomato. Escargots were still soft and tender despite being baked  with the other ingredients. A very tasty dish that went perfectly on the bread they served it in. <br><br>2) Sous Vide chicken breast served with Barley risotto and mushroom Fricassee, Immanuel French Kitchen <br>This... I can&#39;t find the words for this but.. This dish was the star of the night.  It has to be.. By far, one of the best chicken breast dishes I&#39;ve ever had. <br>The beauty of sous videing a dish is that it locks the moisture in, allowing the protein to retain its moisture, locking in the flavours it was mixed with and creating and absolutely, delightfully fragrant dish. <br>This dish was no different. Chicken was beautifully sous vide. A quick sear to crisp up the outside while ensuring that the meat remain most and tender. Served with an amazing Barley Risotto and topped with a mushroom Fricassee to give it and earthy wholesomeness to the dish. <br><br>3) Prawns in Garlic cream sauce, Sea salt. <br>When this dish first arrived, I thought it might be pretty average. Prawns didn&#39;t look particularly bright and vibrant but one taste of the sauce, and my impression changed in a heartbeat. The prawns were perfectly cooked. Tender, juicy and cooked jjjjuuusssttt right. Garlic in the sauce wasn&#39;t over powering and the sauce in general wasn&#39;t too rich. The sweetness of the prawns were still prominent and sauce complimented the prawns perfectly.  <br><br>4) Grilled Fish with Rice <br>A simple dish done well. Rice was very tasty and the sauce complimented the dish perfectly. Not wish was that they gave more sauce! <br><br>5) Laksa Linguine, Mian 面.<br>There have been many variations of this dish out there as some of them were hits... More often than not.. Misses. This one though was an absolute hit!<br><br>Linguine was al Dante. The seafood was cooked to perfection and most importantly... The sauce.. Was perfect! <br>Fragrant and rich, the sauce tasted exactly what a laksa sauce should taste like. Most sauces tend to be diluted or lacking that punch but this laksa sauce had all the fragrances you might find in a bowl of laksa, but concentrates enough without being over powering. A wonderful rendition to an otherwise classic dish. <br><br>6) Caesar Salad, Stew Küche. <br>No this is a Caesar done well. More often than not, vasee salad&#39;s are over dressed and not done properly but this Caesar was done the way a Caesar should be done. <br><br>7) Mushroom soup, Stew Küche. <br>A well made mushroom soup that&#39;s not made of instant powder. Delicious and definately one to have if you love mushroom soups. <br><br>Unfortunately, there was only 4 of us and we didn&#39;t get to try to pork knuckles from Stew Küche and the wings from Two Wings, both which looked amazing and definitely a popular choice for diners. <br>We&#39;ll be back with more updates! <br><br>Overall, the &#34;coffee shop&#34; is definitely pricier than your average under the block coffee shops but with pricing for an entree ranging from $13-$20, it&#39;s difficult finding such a wide variety of cuisines, with such amazing quality, at these prices!

Located at the ground flour of heartland mall. Hidden in this mall lies a small gem called the double spout café. Been here twice because it had good food. <br>Both times I had the beef lasagne and the mixed fruit tea in a jug. <br>The beef lasagne was quite small but it had a generous serving of cheese, tomato sauce and ground beef to make your mouth crave for more. The lasagne had potato wedges and a small serving of garden salad with it. The potato wedges is pretty average but the garden salad is very fresh!<br>The mixed fruit tea is delightfully sweet and has loads of fresh fruits like lychee, apples, oranges and strawberries in it!!!<br>Beef lasagne- 8/10<br>Mixed fruit tea- 9/10

text: A nice western food option in the Kovan neighborhood. surprisingly this outlet was more crowded and had a line of people in waiting compared to the New York New York restaurant right above it. it&#39;s not the best but sufficient for a quick bite. Their lady server (who has a stud embedded in her arm) was really nice and she was very efficient in her service. She made my first experience at the cafe very pleasant.

This cafe is located at the ground floor of heartland mall in Kovan just outside the cold storage. It is of open concept like those modern cafes and kiosks in malls. The menu has a number of food to choose from and i think the cuisine they serve there has a mix of Chinese, western and malay.<br>I think their food are valued for money and really quite tasty, and also they give pretty big portions of each dish. My friend had ordered the fish and chips and the fish was huge, it came along with chunky fries too, nicely fried. I had one of their aglio olio and the side dishes that came along with it were plentiful i was surprised for the price i was paying.<br><br>The boss and staff there were very friendly and they really did their best to provide good service to customers. I would definitely recommend people to dine here as it is a really casual cafe and good service plus food, must try.

Still feel the same about nanyang coffee. But hey there&#39;s one decent dish that is edible here when you&#39;re too lazy to get out of biopolis - chicken cutlet with hainanese sauce! <br><br>The chicken cutlet is relatively crispy, in oddly huge chunks. The rice is boring and of short disintegrating grains but well, the hainanese style tomato sauce is too sweet to go without any carbs. Some frozen peas and carrot cubes to pretend as vegetables on the dish. That&#39;s all you get! For $5.50 with rice, that&#39;s a reasonable price in biopolis. <br><br>Do I crave it? Not really. But at least there&#39;s something edible when I&#39;m forced to head there with colleagues.

Live band music with both English and Chinese songs.<br>We didn&#39;t need to make a reservation on a Friday night so kudos to that. Do check out their Fb page for opening days as certain days may be booked for events or so.<br><br>Overall the location of the place is excellent at Bugis+ and they have a smoking area outside as well.<br><br>Typically you get tapas bites and 1 for 1 offers, great for big groups and intimate gathering for beers! Had their luncheon meat fries and they were fried beautifully with a serving of nancho cheese chips.<br><br>They have dart machines in the bar as well so dart fanatics, dart your night away.<br><br>For fellow Yelpers and Yelp Elites, do write a review and get a free luncheon meat fries on ur next visit. Do check with the staff on this promotion!

text: Like the fact that it is darts machines here and that&#39;s what attracted us here. Overall, experiences was okie. Nice music. But the ginger ale that i ordered was &#39;flat&#39;. The staff was nice enough to change a new one but turned out, it&#39;s the same - still flat. <br>Nonetheless, i love the spam fries with nachos - YUMMY!!! :))

text: If you&#39;re planning to organize your company event here, this place is a one star only.<br><br>Food - good and sufficient for the flow<br>Service - actually a 1 star service. Food was served very late, 12.50pm when my company event supposed to start at 12pm!! Totally unacceptable! The owner appeared really &#34;chin chai&#34; (anyhow attitude), and agrees to everything prior to the event, but failed to deliver.<br>Location - your PowerPoint slides can flash on to their big wall in stage, yes, but in fact it&#39;s day time and there will be light entering the entire bar which makes your visibility of details on screen really low. Although there are TV screens available, but they are not compatible to the laptop and is unable to screen your PowerPoint slides. Here comes the issue. The owner actually mentioned that you can flash your PowerPoint slides prior to your event. That&#39;s cheating!<br>Price - expensive and not value for money.<br><br>Overall experience was bad for a corporate event.<br><br>No doubt, it&#39;s an ok location to hang out with your friends. But if you cannot handle a corporate event, please stop advertising for it, or find someone who is capable of doing it professionally. I can only say, the boss is just a pub owner, not a professional event organizer trained.

text: Amazing! This place has great atmosphere, great service and there&#39;s darts here! The food is great, and affordable, though it might be a bit noisy.

This is a really cool places that organizes various startup events and as such I can highly recommend it to all the startup guys out there. Also, when you come on a regular night, they play cool local music. Even though I was a bit skeptical when I came here for the first time and needed to go through the entire Bugis+ shopping mall in order to come here, I was very nicely surprised when I reached and since that time Hood Bar has become one of my favorite spots for meetings with friends.

text: I had walked by the venue twice and the signage outside was very alluring.  As an American, I love a good burger and the Wagyu burger looked delicious in the picture.  Boy was it misleading!<br><br>The fact that the venue was vacant should have already been an indication, but I was keen on giving it ago.  This may have been hands down, the worst burger I&#39;ve ever eaten.  The bread was stale and dry.  The patty was overcooked and dry.  Too make things worse, they must have used the worst parts of the cow.  It had hard tendon grounded up in the mix.<br><br>The juicy looking thick cut bacon ended up being scrawny turkey bacon.  I can&#39;t believe I had to wait 30+ minutes to receive this crap.  McDonald&#39;s would have been a better meal at fraction of the cost.

text: Wohooo this place rocks!! While it seems like a new place on the cinema level in Bugis + (formally Illuma), Hood have been around for a while. They used to be located in a cosy spot in keong saik street. A relocation with a bigger fit out, bigger bar and now a food menu, the Hood I&#39;ve always loved just got better. Drink prices are reasonable, the live bands great, food wise the hot dogs are the biggest and tastiest in Singapore for sure.<br><br>They have been really clever with their choice of location. It was fantastic to pop in for a drink and a hot dog, before going to the cinema on the same floor before returning for more drinks and a chilled out Saturday evening. Cool tunes, great food and great live music, highly recommend a visit to Hood. It has just got a whole lot bigger and better!!

userinfo: {'link': '/user_details?userid=DQL_mBSKDe30h4uH-kNpgg', 'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/assets/srv0/yelp_styleguide/514f6997a318/assets/img/default_avatars/user_60_square.png', 'srcSet': None, 'markupDisplayName': 'Ciara M.', 'displayLocation': 'Dublin, Republic of Ireland', 'altText': 'Ciara M.', 'userUrl': '/user_details?userid=DQL_mBSKDe30h4uH-kNpgg', 'partnerAlias': None, 'friendCount': 0, 'photoCount': None, 'reviewCount': 1, 'eliteYear': None}
text: The only reason this place gets 1 star and not 0 is that the live band was fabulous.<br>This place handed us an iPad (as many places in Singapore do) and we selected our drinks. My SO selected a pint for $14 and I selected a vodka Smirnoff for $11. A submenu popped up asking me to specialse this drink.  I was surprised when I selected double vodka and apple juice that it remained at $11. Suspicious, I took a photo of our receipt at the end of our transaction. $31. My SO handed a credit card over to pay the bill and we were charged $44!! They had sneakily charged me for the double vodka and apple juice. I suspected this, however I would not have ordered them had I known that there was a charge for this. $11 was fine for me.  They kept this completely secret and upon dispute, even though I kept a picture of the receipt, my SO was charged for this. I will be showing this to our hotel - the intercontinental - to have it rectified and this place will be mortified over it&#39;s appalling customer service.

Sweet things.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Sweet things.'}]
text: If consistency is what you expect, prepare to take a big gamble. <br>My first visit to this fast burgeoning, local entreprising coffee (or rather chocolate) chains was that of awe and much love indeed for the concept and whats not to love when chocolate is the main course! You have to check it out yourself for its &#34;colony&#34; concept that is just a lot of eye candy to take in, with plenty of gold-gilded merchandise for you to bring home.<br>I can&#39;t help but gets nostalgic on the first drink that I&#39;ve had here. Despite the number of tempting Signature drinks, it is down to some chilling drinks in this humid, non-airconditioned mall, and I ordered an Ice Blended Sea Salt Caramel, which taste perfectly icy and well blended with just the right amount of that cocoa powder, just a hint of salt, and a good balance of caramel sauce. How I indulge in it, and wish I have ordered the large cup! Till my next visit.<br>And i did just order the large for my next visit, but oh boy, what could goes wrong, everything just went wrong with my drink. It is too watery, too much powder in it. Despite my request for being less sweet, it is sickeningly sweet. Forget about tasting that delightful sea salt, this is a cup of badly melted ice-cream, and now those heaps of hersey&#39;s corn syrup caramel sauce made it so sickeningly sweet, it is just undrinkable. Ugh, crikey. <br>Dont expect a new cup being made, this is Singapore, not the US, honey, suck it up and trash it into the can baby. <br>For the love that that first cup brings me and its cute cafe design, i cant help but to justify that bad drink to me being greedy and ordered a large, that brings the proportion off, and still was drawn to it to order another cup, this time i stuck with regular. <br>And guess what, thats the last straw (literally) i had with this place. How could a place that uses professional blending machine, and charge the rate of CBTL and Starbucks, be that different in consistency!! Even the worst of my CBTL drink is still much more drinkable than this cup. The blending isnt smooth, powder could still be tasted, proportion is way off. Drinking that gooey failed mixture is enough of a punishment when u lost your gamble. <br>And their success rate is pretty low to me. Sorry, heading back to CBTL here.

Gooey baked Camembert - heaven on a slice of toast', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Gooey baked Camembert - heaven on a slice of toast'}]
text: I grew up in this neighborhood so coming here was like a homecoming of sorts. Where the hardware stores used to be are a slew of hip and happening cafes, bistros and chillax dessert joints. <br><br>Black White Tale&#39;s friendly owner is originally from Hong Kong. Taking a less obvious food direction from the cha chan teng,he decided on serving raclette dishes. <br><br>We had a great time and inhaled most of the dishes quickly. Our faves are the gooey Camembert, so shiok burger and the cheese wheel pasta tossed with truffle oil right at the table.

Live band music with both English and Chinese songs.<br>We didn&#39;t need to make a reservation on a Friday night so kudos to that. Do check out their Fb page for opening days as certain days may be booked for events or so.<br><br>Overall the location of the place is excellent at Bugis+ and they have a smoking area outside as well.<br><br>Typically you get tapas bites and 1 for 1 offers, great for big groups and intimate gathering for beers! Had their luncheon meat fries and they were fried beautifully with a serving of nancho cheese chips.<br><br>They have dart machines in the bar as well so dart fanatics, dart your night away.<br><br>For fellow Yelpers and Yelp Elites, do write a review and get a free luncheon meat fries on ur next visit. Do check with the staff on this promotion!

text: If you&#39;re planning to organize your company event here, this place is a one star only.<br><br>Food - good and sufficient for the flow<br>Service - actually a 1 star service. Food was served very late, 12.50pm when my company event supposed to start at 12pm!! Totally unacceptable! The owner appeared really &#34;chin chai&#34; (anyhow attitude), and agrees to everything prior to the event, but failed to deliver.<br>Location - your PowerPoint slides can flash on to their big wall in stage, yes, but in fact it&#39;s day time and there will be light entering the entire bar which makes your visibility of details on screen really low. Although there are TV screens available, but they are not compatible to the laptop and is unable to screen your PowerPoint slides. Here comes the issue. The owner actually mentioned that you can flash your PowerPoint slides prior to your event. That&#39;s cheating!<br>Price - expensive and not value for money.<br><br>Overall experience was bad for a corporate event.<br><br>No doubt, it&#39;s an ok location to hang out with your friends. But if you cannot handle a corporate event, please stop advertising for it, or find someone who is capable of doing it professionally. I can only say, the boss is just a pub owner, not a professional event organizer trained.

text: Amazing! This place has great atmosphere, great service and there&#39;s darts here! The food is great, and affordable, though it might be a bit noisy.

This is a really cool places that organizes various startup events and as such I can highly recommend it to all the startup guys out there. Also, when you come on a regular night, they play cool local music. Even though I was a bit skeptical when I came here for the first time and needed to go through the entire Bugis+ shopping mall in order to come here, I was very nicely surprised when I reached and since that time Hood Bar has become one of my favorite spots for meetings with friends.

text: I had walked by the venue twice and the signage outside was very alluring.  As an American, I love a good burger and the Wagyu burger looked delicious in the picture.  Boy was it misleading!<br><br>The fact that the venue was vacant should have already been an indication, but I was keen on giving it ago.  This may have been hands down, the worst burger I&#39;ve ever eaten.  The bread was stale and dry.  The patty was overcooked and dry.  Too make things worse, they must have used the worst parts of the cow.  It had hard tendon grounded up in the mix.<br><br>The juicy looking thick cut bacon ended up being scrawny turkey bacon.  I can&#39;t believe I had to wait 30+ minutes to receive this crap.  McDonald&#39;s would have been a better meal at fraction of the cost.

text: Wohooo this place rocks!! While it seems like a new place on the cinema level in Bugis + (formally Illuma), Hood have been around for a while. They used to be located in a cosy spot in keong saik street. A relocation with a bigger fit out, bigger bar and now a food menu, the Hood I&#39;ve always loved just got better. Drink prices are reasonable, the live bands great, food wise the hot dogs are the biggest and tastiest in Singapore for sure.<br><br>They have been really clever with their choice of location. It was fantastic to pop in for a drink and a hot dog, before going to the cinema on the same floor before returning for more drinks and a chilled out Saturday evening. Cool tunes, great food and great live music, highly recommend a visit to Hood. It has just got a whole lot bigger and better!!

text: The only reason this place gets 1 star and not 0 is that the live band was fabulous.<br>This place handed us an iPad (as many places in Singapore do) and we selected our drinks. My SO selected a pint for $14 and I selected a vodka Smirnoff for $11. A submenu popped up asking me to specialse this drink.  I was surprised when I selected double vodka and apple juice that it remained at $11. Suspicious, I took a photo of our receipt at the end of our transaction. $31. My SO handed a credit card over to pay the bill and we were charged $44!! They had sneakily charged me for the double vodka and apple juice. I suspected this, however I would not have ordered them had I known that there was a charge for this. $11 was fine for me.  They kept this completely secret and upon dispute, even though I kept a picture of the receipt, my SO was charged for this. I will be showing this to our hotel - the intercontinental - to have it rectified and this place will be mortified over it&#39;s appalling customer service.

text: Fans of Icebox Cafe would be glad to know that Oriental Ice Bistro is basically the same cafe, reopened under new management.<br><br>The cafe has the same amazing bingsoo (Korean shaved ice) and toasts that flooded Instagram in the past few years. They have local bingsoo flavours (Chendol, Durian, Avocado Gula Melaka etc), as well as the usual flavours (my favourite is the Matcha Azuki, complete with milk served in a syringe).<br><br>The changes made under the new management are great as far as i can see. The basic bingsoo flavours are cheaper while being the same size as before ($12.90 instead of $15.90, which is great value imo), and the toasts, shakes and bingsoo flavours all remain. New management has added food items to the menu  - pizza, baked rice, wraps and so on. Haven&#39;t tried these but they look good.<br><br>Unfortunately the new management doesn&#39;t seem to be as active on social media - but don&#39;t take this as in indication of the food!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/8G6DVPAm6tJ_-EO3YaaoAQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/cafereatt-singapore?reviewid=UyI4V_IK8FSH8eFMebhQNw&select=8G6DVPAm6tJ_-EO3YaaoAQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Cafereatt - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/uA3QKCkEIunL8cDaJP6Q9g/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/cafereatt-singapore?reviewid=UyI4V_IK8FSH8eFMebhQNw&select=uA3QKCkEIunL8cDaJP6Q9g', 'altText': 'Photo of Cafereatt - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: Located in the middle of the very quiet Library @ Esplanade, the café attracted us with the faint aroma of stir-fried pasta. There&#39;s nothing like pasta on a rainy afternoon. And coffee.<br><br>My companion had a Long Black while I ordered a Spicy Chai Tea. The spicy chai tea disturbed my companion a little because it wasn&#39;t the right way Chai Tea was supposed to be made. The waiter had a little friendly discussion with him, and we found out that the waiter loves Oolong Cha.<br><br>AAANYWAYS, you&#39;re not supposed to have high expectations of this place, they&#39;re kind of like a café in school - they give you food and a quiet place to read books. I like the big corner wooden sofa at the side where we had good &#39;low-volume&#39; conversations. There was a sign saying the seat&#39;s reserved for at least 3 pax and above, but there wasn&#39;t much people there on a Saturday evening, so we were left to ourselves.<br><br>Check out <a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Featlikeawhale.blogspot.sg&amp;s=073078668bba0d0a43c2d19980dbd9384767b13a2e1457c8da39273937aa332c" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">eatlikeawhale.blogspot.sg</a> for more pictures and reviews.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/hftTwKPtW2KpLUP2X5xwWQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/cafereatt-singapore?reviewid=-UjgDDHc2BzOLwyYea9ufQ&select=hftTwKPtW2KpLUP2X5xwWQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Cafereatt - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: There used to be a decent café next to the Esplanade library, but they got replaced by Cafereatt a while back and I haven&#39;t tried it until two days ago, partly because of its cheesy name.<br><br>It&#39;s not too bad, actually. The ambience remains largely the same, although it can get really bright during the day if someone rolls the curtain all the way up. There&#39;s no way to control that from inside the café so you&#39;ll have to deal with it.<br><br>The latte I had was okay, and the pastries were fine too. I didn&#39;t try any of the pasta or main courses, but they didn&#39;t look fantastic from what I can see from other people&#39;s tables.<br><br>The chief reason for visiting and staying is the comfortable furniture. I can&#39;t see myself coming back just for this café, and I&#39;ll mostly drop by occasionally when I&#39;m visiting the Esplanade library.

Came here looking for Cafe Tiffany&#39;s (I even paced around the entire library to double check that it hadn&#39;t moved to another corner), and I found this underwhelming shell of what Tiffany&#39;s used to be. Got a latte ($4.80) that was way too overpriced, the power sockets were all taken (and when I tried to use the ones that were next to my sofa, the staff told me they weren&#39;t for &#39;customer usage&#39;). <br><br>There wasn&#39;t anyway the people using the sockets were going to vacate anytime soon, so, peeved and pissed, I left for the Coffee Bean and Tea Leaf at Tanjong Pagar which yielded much more promise. It&#39;s a sad, sad shame when a chain café brings more comfort than a supposedly &#39;comfortable&#39; setup.

This was one of my favourite places to go for lunch during my army days. Since my camp was nearby, I would head out for lunch with some of my army mates and this is one of the usual destinations.<br><br>Whats good about this coffee shop is the roast meat and bak kut teh stalls. Everytime we&#39;re there, we always have a plate of either roast duck or roast meat rice and a big bowl of peppery bak kut teh to share.<br><br>The roast meat rice is quite something on its own. I usually have the roast duck and roast meat mixed rice. The duck is not too fatty and the roast meat has that heavenly crispy skin. Mix that with a scoop of sambal chilli and you&#39;re good to go. I think the rice is cooked with chicken stock, so it has that distinct chicken rice-esque flavour to it. And then wash it down is hot, peppery Bak Kut Teh. Can&#39;t get a better lunch combination than that.

Dry mee siam with assam chicken", 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Dry mee siam with assam chicken'}]
text: I stumbled onto this place when I was checking out the basement food area of Republic Plaza. Being 2 pm, the office crowd has left and there were only a few stragglers left. <br><br>I was told the bestsellers were the dry mee siam with assam chicken, assam laksa and ayam buah keluak set. I decided to get the dry mee siam with assam chicken though my inclination was for the ayam pongteh set. I guessed I liked to go with the recommended dishes when dining at a new place, especially when I was not sure what to order. <br><br>I did not expect much as most dry mee siam I had was pretty lackluster. So I was surprised with their version. The dry mee siam packed a punch. The spices were subtly infused with the rice vermicelli and the sauce/gravy drizzled over it was full of the mee siam flavor - tangy from tamarind, lime and tau cheo (fermented beans). The only thing missing was the dried tau pok (dried bean curd) or tofu cubes. There was a small piece of shrimp and some slivers of fish cake, otherwise it was a plain dish. <br><br>The assam chicken was equally good. There was a hint of smokiness in the chicken (still did not know why it would be smokey but it was all good) which was very tender and fell away from the bone easily with the fork. The gravy was not that assam-y (sour), instead it had lemongrass note to it. I think it would go better with rice than with the noodles. <br><br>I would want to go back to try the other dishes. I find it rare to find places where you could actually taste the individual spices which made the dishes more aromatic and tasty. The last time I experienced that was actually in a nonya cafe in KL, Malaysia. <br><br>The name of the cafe is a bit of a misnomer as the dishes are not solely peranakan. Some dishes are Penang style and the name Jonker is commonly known for Jonker Street in Malacca. Googling more, I found out the the owner&#39;s grandmothers hailed from Malacca and Penang, hence the type of food served.

text: Enjoy coming here<br>- industrial chic atmosphere<br>- bingsu is delicious, especially with strawberries <br>- enough to share<br>- long spoons<br>- open late, 11 pm<br>- friendly staff<br><br>This place is always packed, lots of people studying and hanging out. Younger crowd. The high quality is consistent. The staff quickly learns your regular order.

text: I went there to get a cup of peppermint tea (S$6) today and was horrified that the staff held the bottom of the tea bag in between her bare fingers in the midst of this Covid-19 pandemic. <br><br>Thinking back about it, I am even more horrified at myself for gulping down half the cup of tea before I realised what I had done to myself. <br><br>Definitely not going back no more, even though it&#39;s pretty empty earlier this Sunday evening.
The staff is very prompt and anxious to get you seated quickly. The food comes quickly also. It&#39;s quite a bit of food for the money. Very spacious seating area and the staff is very friendly.

It has become a (particularly bad) habit of mine to get boba milk tea as an afternoon snack. Milk tea on too of the 5 meals a day I have in singapore is definitely going to lead to a 710034727792 lb increase. Ugh I should hit the gym soon. <br><br>This Ding tea is located on the ground floor of the Far East Plaza. Like most of the shops in Far East Plaza, it&#39;s a little run down--the menus are peeling off the counter etc., but the tea and pearls taste good, so I won&#39;t complain too much about the shabbiness of the store. There&#39;s also nowhere to sit unless you sit outside the mall or in the food court area. <br><br>The workers are friendly, and the boba hits the spot after a nice meal at saveur :) or grab a curry puff from outside with a boba drink for a little snack:)

text: Really like that this outlet is literally facing Gong Cha and yet offers the same drinks at 60cents cheaper! It tastes more milky, like Koi! I really like the pearls, it was chewy and each one had the some texture. I had the sugar level at 30% and it was just nice for me. It tastes the same as when I drank Gong Cha or Koi at 25%.

text: Bubble tea with stores over major cities in Asia. They also let you pick the sugar level. <br><br>For me, the tea doesn&#39;t taste as fragrant as the other leading bubble tea stores. I didn&#39;t have any pearls in mine, so can&#39;t comment on the pearls. <br><br>Good only if you are craving for bubble tea on a hot day.
